<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   9 February 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Church, Bottling Plant Bombed To Protest US Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2501014494 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2501014494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report over video by Janeth Cepeda from Bucaramanga; from </F>
the "24 Hours" newscast] 
  [Text] According to an investigation by the intelligence 
division of the Santander Police Department, two medium-power 
explosive devices were detonated in a Mormon church and a soft 
drink bottling plant in Bucaramanga to protest the presence of 
U.S. soldiers in Colombia. 
  [Begin recording of Santander Police Commander Colonel Hugo 
Lozano, identified by caption] These explosive devices were 
placed by the Army of National Liberation to protest the 
presence of U.S. Marines in Colombian territory. [end recording] 
  The explosive devices, which contained 2 kg of dynamite 
apiece, were detonated at the same time. In the Mormon church, 
the damage was estimated at 7 million pesos. Seven years ago, 
another attack completely destroyed the church. 

</TEXT>

