<H3> <TI>   Court Resumes Hearings in Sidqi Assassination Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0702215094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2010 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0702215094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Cairo, 7 Feb (MENA)--The Supreme Military Court, 
which is considering the case of the attempted assassination of 
Prime Minister Dr. 'Atif Sidqi, held a session today to continue 
hearing the testimonies of the prosecution witnesses in the 
case, in which 15 people are being tried, six of them in 
absentia. 
  The court saw two videotapes on which the supreme state 
security prosecution recorded a staged version of the incident 
and how it was carried out. The fifth and sixth defendants 
related how the crime was committed and the role of each one of 
them, as well as the role of the seventh defendant who 
participated in the crime, how they prepared the explosive 
charge used in the incident, and how they monitored the prime 
minister's movements. 
  The court also saw a videotape about an examination of the 
house of the fifth defendant Salah al-Din [name indistinct] in 
al-Minufiyah, in which the police found electrical equipment, 
weapons, and explosives being prepared for use in some terrorist 
operations. [passage omitted] 
  The Supreme Military Court decided to adjourn its sessions 
until tomorrow to hear the remaining witnesses who assisted the 
police or took part in capturing the defendants. 
  The court decided to refer the fifth defendant, Salah 
al-Din, 
to a physician to determine the truth about his claim that he 
was tortured. The court also decided to summon the commander 
and some members of the prime minister's guard to hear their 
testimony. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

