<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Loeschnak Confirms Suspect's Arrest in Letter Bombings </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002131694 Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network in German 
1100 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1002131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Robert Stoppacher report on news conference by Austrian </F>
Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak on 10 February; place not 
given -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] The Anti-Terrorism Task Force has struck again. 
A 24-year-old right-wing extremist has been arrested in 
connection with the series of letter bomb attacks. [see 
Terrorism Reports dated 15, 24, and 28 December 1993 for 
incident reporting] Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak confirmed 
this today. He did not want to disclose any details on the 
man's role. [passage omitted] 
  Reportedly, the recently-arrested man is part of the 
leadership of the terrorist group called Extraparliamentary 
Opposition Loyal to the People, with which Peter Binder and 
Franz Radl Jr are also affiliated. These two right-wing 
extremists have been imprisoned for many weeks. Loeschnak says 
that they are supposedly behind the wave of terrorism. By the 
way, the interior minister also talks for the first time of 
concrete proof against the suspects, not mere circumstantial 
evidence. 
  At any rate, right-wing extremism in Austria has altogether 
become more violent. This is also shown by the criminal 
statistics presented by the Interior Ministry, which, however, 
in general indicates a gratifying reversal of the trend. After 
years of increasing crime rates, the figures for 1993 show, for 
the first time, a slight decrease. The number of crimes and 
criminal offenses is just under 500,000, as compared to 502,000 
the year before. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

