<H3> <TI>   Update on Jordanian Diplomat's Assassination </TI></H3>
<H4>   Envoy Blames `Agent Regimes' </H4>
<F P=102> NC0802121394 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 1000 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0802121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Jordanian Ambassador Fakhri Abu-Talib after </F>
meeting Interior Minister Bisharah Mirhij in Beirut today, 
followed by remarks in response to questions by unidentified 
correspondents--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] Such incidents will not affect 
Jordan or Lebanon. They can happen anywhere. I don't believe 
this incident will deflect the Jordanians from the correct 
course and the wise policy pursued by the king. [passage omitted] 
  [Correspondent] Is it true there was a political message to 
the Jordanian regime behind the incident? 
  [Abu-Talib] According to my own analysis, the motives for 
the 
incident were political and were intended to harm both Jordan 
and Lebanon. The perpetrators were criminals supported by agent 
regimes, which still resort to such incidents. 
  [Correspondent] Who are these agent regimes? 
  [Abu-Talib] I cannot identify them. As I told you, those who 
committed this criminal act did not serve the interest of 
Lebanon or the Arab nation. 
  [Correspondent] Are they Arab or non-Arab regimes? 
  [Abu-Talib] Soon you will start interrogating me. 
  [Correspondent] Today's reports say the culprits are 
Palestinians, do they not? 
  [Abu-Talib] I heard what you heard. 
  [Correspondent] Have you confirmed this? 
  [Abu-Talib] We have not. 
  [Correspondent] Do you suspect any particular quarter? 
  [Abu-Talib] We hold nearly all the main leads. But we cannot 
tell the press because we do not want to infringe upon Lebanese 
security or the judicial authorities in Lebanon and play a role 
that is not ours to play. 

</TEXT>

