<ABS>  The Principles of Combined Arms Battle </ABS>
<DATE1>   7 February 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100></F>
<H3> <TI>     THE PRINCIPLES OF COMBINED ARMS BATTLE </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  93UM0572F Moscow PRINTSIPY OBSHCHEVOYSKOVOGO BOYA in Russian 
1992 pp 1-218, 656-659 </F>

<F P=103> 93UM0572F </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow PRINTSIPY OBSHCHEVOYSKOVOGO BOYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Annotation, introduction, chapters 1-4, and table of </F>
contents of book "The Principles of Combined Arms Battle: 
Military-Theoretical Work", by Major General (Retired) I. N. 
Vorobyev, doctor of military sciences, professor, Orders of 
Lenin and October Revolution Red Banner Order of Suvorov 
Military Academy imeni M. V. Frunze Scientific Research 
Department, Academy publication (signed to press 30 March 1992), 
659 pages and 15 inserts] 
  [Text] 
<H6>  Annotation </H6>
  This book is about tactical art. It details the history of 
the origin and development of fundamental principles of combined 
arms battle and reveals their essence under present conditions 
and their interrelationship with principles of operational art 
and strategy. An identification of ways and methods of 
implementing demands of tactical principles in defensive and 
offensive battle and meeting engagements, and development of 
appropriate recommendations for commanders and staffs, are the 
book's principal content. Main attention is given to new 
problem-oriented questions. The range of questions covered is 
from company to formation. The work is widely illustrated by 
diagrams and tables. 
  The work has no analogues, is distinguished by a 
non-stereotyped nature of construction and exposition, and is 
written in a lively, graphic language. Its purpose is to be a 
supplement to tactics textbooks and training manuals. The book's 
entire content is aimed at shaping officers' creative thinking, 
rejecting banality, fighting routine and conventionalism, and 
reviving tactics as a genuinely innovative art. 
  In examining the evolution of principles of battle, the 
author saw his task as showing as completely as possible the 
role of Soviet military-theoretical thought and, especially the 
contribution of prominent Soviet military leaders of the Civil 
War and Great Patriotic War in developing and enriching them. At 
the same time, the work pays proper attention to analyzing works 
on this subject published in Russia in pre-revolutionary times 
and also works of foreign authors. The book is designed for 
officers at the tactical level and for students and cadets of 
higher military educational institutions. 
<H5>  INTRODUCTION </H5>
  Principles are a "real aid or guiding star for 
the person act-ing." 
  C. von Clausewitz, "On War" 
  ...Principles of military art shine in history 
like the Sun on the horizon, so much the worse for blind men 
incapable of seeing them. 
  Napoleon 
  ...I personally was guided by them (principles of 
military art--I.V.) in preparing all operations. At 
the same time I saw that when these matters were treated 
formally, there was no success in the battle, the engagement or 
the operation. 
  G. K. Zhukov 
  Military leaders have tried to find the "elixir" of victory 
since very ancient times. Centuries went by, a countless number 
of military campaigns and engagements were conducted and a sea 
of blood was shed before inquisitive thinkers, getting to know 
accumulated combat experience and analyzing the secret "springs" 
and "levers" acting in a complex, contradictory situation, 
discovered the guiding threads and developed precepts on how to 
prepare and fight the battle. With the passage of time these 
precepts were enriched and formed into rules and official 
recommendations, which in the final account turned into an 
orderly system of principles of military art reflected in formal 
documents of regulations of all world armies. 
  Encyclopedic sources define the term "principle" as a 
fundamental rule, a guiding proposition, a direction for some 
kind of activity.[.sup]1[/] Principles of battle entered 
military theory as categories defining ties and relationships of 
various aspects of combat activity of formations, units and 
subunits; as fundamental ideas; and, as the most important 
recommendations on preparing and conducting battle.[.sup]2[/] 
Principles of military art are rightly called a coagulation of 
military wisdom, a guiding light in a military leader's command 
and control activity. The experience of many wars were 
accumulated in them; the creative inspirations of field 
generals, bitter lessons of defeats and interpreted results of 
victories were embodied in them. Principles of military art were 
passed on from generation to generation like a most valuable 
scientific baton, an inexhaustible fount of military thought. 
  Soviet military art also adopted principles of military art 
from the moment it originated, inheriting everything valuable 
that had been accumulated in past military affairs. These 
principles were reflected and developed in military regulations, 
textbooks and military-theoretical works of the young Red Army. 
Works of military authors critically revised many theoretical 
provisions of military art and of Army and Navy organizational 
development on a new methodological and material basis and 
revealed the interrelationship of principles of military art and 
laws of war. 
  But under the influence of I. V. Stalin's cult of 
personality, discussions in the press ceased in the mid-1930's 
on questions of development of strategy, operational part, and 
tactics. Statements by certain military specialists crept into 
military literature to the effect that allegedly all principles 
whatsoever were alien to Soviet military science since they 
hobbled military art. During the Great Patriotic War, Stalin 
formulated the thesis of permanently operating and temporary 
factors deciding the course and outcome of war. They were viewed 
as the chief element in Soviet military science, almost as its 
basic laws and principles, although in reality they reflected 
only certain of its areas. Thus, for example, only one factor 
was taken from the sum total of complex questions of command and 
control--the organizing abilities of command personnel. The 
importance of officers' art and of the personnel's scientific 
knowledge, combat proficiency and moral-psychological qualities 
was not taken into account. 
  The postulates of Stalinist lines, considered infallible, in 
fact suffered from one-sidedness and logical and constructive 
inconsistency, contributing to the propagation of dogmatism and 
conventionalism. The development of propositions on logical 
patterns of development of warfare and of fundamental principles 
of military art were consigned to oblivion for many years in 
Soviet military science. Only in the 1960's did provisions on 
principles of military art appear in Soviet Armed Forces field 
manuals, in textbooks and in works on military theory. 
  But the consequences of authoritarianism and of slavery to 
routine in military thinking left a negative imprint on 
military-scientific research. As applied to principles of 
military art, this was reflected in the fact that a number of 
works interpreted their content very arbitrarily. For example, 
the work "O sovetskoy voyennoy nauke" [On Soviet Military 
Science] included among principles of warfare those such as the 
immediate, swift exploitation of success of nuclear missile 
strikes for conducting an offensive against the enemy with all 
available personnel and equipment, swiftness in conducting the 
battle and operation and exploiting success in them at high 
rates, continuous strategic, operational and tactical 
reconnaissance, and so on.[.sup]3[/] 
  An especially large amount of confusion was allowed in 
formulating principles in military-philosophical works. For 
example, in spite of the provisions of regulations, the work 
"Marksistsko-leninskaya filosofiya i metodologicheskiye problemy 
voyennoy praktiki" [sic] [Marxist-Leninist Philosophy and 
Methodological Problems of Military Practice], published in 1982 
following publication of the "Sovetskaya Voyennaya 
Entsiklopediya" [Soviet Military Encyclopedia], elevated to the 
category of principles of military art those such as carefully 
planning combat operations, combining all methods and forms of 
warfare, disposing troops in depth in the battle and operation, 
and preempting the enemy in deploying and in aligning the combat 
formation.[.sup]4[/] I. A. Grudinin's monograph "Dialektika i 
sovremennoye voyennoye delo" [Dialectics and Modern Military 
Affairs] (Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1971, pp 60-61) considers one of 
the principles to be "a combination of centralization and 
decentralization of command and control." 
  The mistake of these and certain other authors in 
interpreting the principles is that they identify principles of 
battle with specific practical recommendations for its 
organization and conduct ("preempting the enemy in 
deploying...", "swiftness of operations...", "immediate 
exploitation of results of fire strikes" and so on). But if one 
follows such logic, it turns out that practically any 
requirement of a regulation on preparing and conducting battle 
can be elevated to the rank of a principle, which of course is 
not legitimate. Principles are generalized rules and logical 
constructions which stem not from some particular instance, but 
from the aggregate of many battles. Their requirements relate to 
all kinds of combat operations. 
  Principles of Soviet military art are set forth in the most 
systemized form in the "Sovetskaya Voyennaya Entsiklopediya" 
(1978), but even this fundamental work did not get by without 
oversights. It does not show the role of Soviet military leaders 
G. K. Zhukov, K. K. Rokossovskiy, A. M. Vasilevskiy, I. S. 
Konev, I. Kh. Bagramyan, A. I. Yeremenko, F. I. Tolbukhin, N. F. 
Vatutin, A. I. Antonov, I. D. Chernyakhovskiy and others at all 
in developing principles of strategy, operational art and 
tactics during the Great Patriotic War. For fully understandable 
reasons (limited volume), the "Entsiklopediya" set forth the 
principles in summary form. And this is essentially the only 
military-theoretical work where principles of military art are 
considered from a contemporary standpoint. 
  Thus, such an important methodological category as 
principles 
of military art, which is of exceptional importance for 
cognition and development of strategy, operational art and 
tactics, has not received in-depth, comprehensive study in our 
military literature up to the present time. Principles of modern 
combined arms battle are revealed especially poorly. They are 
set forth chiefly in Ground Troops field manuals. But the 
specific nature of regulations does not permit showing their 
development, substantiating conceptual propositions, or 
illustrating them with examples, proof and calculations, which 
is very important not only for understanding the nature of 
modern battle, but also for mastering the art of conducting it. 
  All this indicates that a need matured long ago for 
developing a fundamental military-theoretical work devoted to 
principles of combined arms battle. It should be said that this 
task was accomplished to a certain extent with the publication 
of V. Ya. Savkin's work "Osnovnyye printsipy operativnogo 
iskusstva i taktiki" [Basic Principles of Operational Art and 
Tactics] in 1972. It sets forth the views of very prominent 
field generals and theorists of the past rather fully on 
principles of military art, discloses the dialectical 
correlation of laws of warfare and principles of military art, 
and analyzes the mechanism of action of laws and forms of their 
practical use. But the content of the principles is not revealed 
fully enough: Factors determining their development are not 
shown. 
  Inasmuch as the study of principles of military art in the 
postwar period is limited to a certain time frame (1953-1959), 
the work naturally does not reflect those profound changes in 
military affairs which occurred over a little more than the last 
three decades. One also cannot help but note that the above work 
did not cover many principles of battle such as combat readiness 
of troops; the maneuver of subunits, strikes and fire; 
comprehensive support to battle; total exertion of moral and 
physical efforts; use of the moral-psychological factor in 
support of combat mission performance; and firm, continuous 
command and control. 
  Based on a study of the nature of modern combined arms 
battle, the goal of this work is to reveal the essence of its 
fundamental principles, show their role and importance in 
command and control activity of commanders and staffs, reveal 
the new things which have appeared in their content under the 
influence of scientific-technical progress in military affairs, 
identify trends in their further development, develop certain 
practical recommendations by which one should be guided in 
preparing for and in the course of conducting combat operations, 
and creatively put those principles into practice. This book is 
not an account of "recipes" for achieving success in battle 
(they do not exist in nature) and it is not a "catechism" of 
immutable truths (canons and dogmatic lines are alien to 
tactics). It is a reflection on tactical art, an attempt to 
penetrate into the commander's creative "laboratory" and show 
what he encounters in seeking uncommon decisions in battle, what 
contradictions and difficulties he overcomes and in what way. 
  The content of the work is aimed at shaping an officer's 
nonstandard tactical thinking, at rejecting banality and 
stereotyped approaches, at fighting routine and conventionalism 
and at reviving tactics as the genuine art of doing battle. 
Historical method and objectivity in analyzing phenomena of 
combat reality are the basis of the study. In examining 
principles of battle, their origin, and paths of formation and 
development, the author saw his task as showing not only the 
role of Soviet, but also of pre-revolutionary Russian 
military-theoretical thought and that of foreign military 
analysts. 
  For a long time we boasted that only Soviet military science 
had a monopoly on the truth, deliberately rejecting other 
military schools. This too is one of the sources of dogmatism. 
Enriched by the abundant experience of the Civil War and Great 
Patriotic War, Soviet military theory achieved progress in its 
development. We rightly are proud that our Armed Forces have 
grand combat traditions. But this does not at all mean that one 
must disdain the historical past or fail to notice positive 
things achieved in other armies. It is obvious that for the good 
of the cause one must be critical toward one's own opinions and 
not reject other opinions and foreign military experience out of 
hand. This will help get rid of dogmatism, embellishment and 
conventionalism faster and will help pave the way to new 
thinking in assessing military problems. 
  While having based the study of principles of combined arms 
battle on guidance documents, on combat training requirements of 
Minister of Defense orders and directives, and on requirements 
of field manuals in force, the author at the same time expresses 
his own viewpoint on a number of questions that differs from 
what is generally accepted and advances certain new propositions 
in the form of statements and discussion. The work makes no 
claim that coverage of this subject is indisputable or 
exhaustively complete. 
Footnotes 
  1. See "Slovar russkogo yazyka [Dictionary of the Russian 
Language], Vol 2, Moscow, Izd-vo "Russkiy yazyk", 1983, p 428. 
  2. See "Taktika. Biblioteka ofitsera" [Tactics: The 
Officer's 
Library], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1987, p 67. 
  3. See S. N. Kozlov, M. V. Smirnov, I. S. Baz et al, "O 
sovetskoy voyennoy nauke" [On Soviet Military Science], Moscow, 
Voyenizdat, 1964, pp 323-330. 
  4. See "Marksistsko-leninskaya filosofiya i 
metodologicheskiye problemy voyennoy teorii i praktiki" 
[Marxist-Leninist Philosophy and Methodological Problems of 
Military Theory and Practice], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1982, p 311. 
<H3>  CHAPTER ONE - ROLE AND IMPORTANCE OF PRINCIPLES OF COMBINED 
ARMS BATTLE IN MILITARY THEORY AND PRACTICE </H3>
  Like any other art, military art has its own 
inherent theory and its own principles, otherwise it would not 
be an art. 
  F. Foch, "On Principles of War" 
  Denial of principles is denial of theory. 
  B. H. Liddell Hart, "Strategy: The Indirect 
Approach" 
  Woe to those who do not know principles. 
  I. P. Uborevich, "Voprosy taktiki v 
sovetskikh voyennykh trudakh" [Questions of Tactics in Soviet 
Military Works]. 
<H3>  1. Origin and Development of Principles of Tactics and Their 
Interrelationship with Principles of Operational Art and Strategy </H3>
  There is not one social science which would not clothe the 
results of its research and generalizations of practice in 
specific rules--principles. Military science, military art and 
theory of tactics are no exception. They have their own 
fundamental categories here--laws, logical patterns, principles. 
And although command and control in the battle and operation 
will not accept rigid norms, although it is harmed by dogmatic 
blinders, this does not at all mean there are no rules here. 
There are, and they are reflected in principles of military art 
developed by many centuries of practice; as combat experience 
has shown, disregarding them inevitably leads to errors, 
miscalculations and even defeat. Conversely, knowing and 
skillfully embodying them in practical command and control 
activity ensures success. 
  Already in ancient times people realized that one cannot act 
at random in the battle and engagement without relying on 
accumulated experience and on recommendations developed by 
predecessors. Flavius Vegetius, a Roman thinker of the ancient 
world, aptly noted: "...Let whoever wishes victory diligently 
train the soldiers; let whoever wishes to obtain a favorable 
result wage war relying on art and knowledge, not on 
chance."[.sup]1[/] 
  The art of tactics and its guiding principles began forming 
long before military leaders began to view the engagement and 
battle as a natural process. Based on the experience gained 
(successful or unsuccessful) and its interpretation and with no 
contemplation of the fact that the rules developed reflect 
objective ties and relationships, precepts were developed on how 
to prepare the army for a campaign, how to dispose it on the 
battlefield, how to supply it with everything necessary and how 
to fight. It was assumed, for example, that if observing 
requirements for an uneven lateral distribution of forces and 
for concealment and coordination of their actions ensures 
success in battle, this means one must be guided by these 
requirements henceforth. Conversely, if a particular method of 
conducting combat operations led to failure, it was discarded as 
worthless. 
  Formation of the theory of tactics and its "main frame," the 
principles of battle, is a lengthy, complex process. Combat 
experience accumulated intuitively over many centuries by the 
trial-and-error method. Each time, failures were paid for in 
blood, and this forced military leaders and thinkers to ponder 
the way in which they should avoid miscalculations and how to 
organize for battle so as to suffer fewer costs and human 
losses. Rules approbated in the course of many battles were 
reflected in treatises, regulations and manuals and acquired the 
importance of mandatory guidelines. In organizing for the battle 
or engagement, military leaders did not begin developing new 
approaches each time but, relying on accumulated experience, 
structured the combat formation more skillfully, achieved 
concealment, speed and cohesiveness of operations, employed 
procedures of deception and so on. Basing themselves on 
predecessors' experience, talented field generals made their own 
contribution to developing methods of preparing and conducting 
battle. 
  In the period of the slaveholding socioeconomic formation, 
military theory managed to arrive at certain generalizations and 
conclusions approximating cognition of some of the most general 
laws of warfare. Principles of military art began to be 
formulated. This was reflected most fully in works by Chinese 
thinker and military leader Sun Tzu, the ancient Greek 
historians Thucydides and Xenophon, Roman military leader Julius 
Caesar, as well as Roman military historians Frontinus and 
Vegetius. If we take the work by Vegetius, "A Brief Exposition 
of Principles of Military Affairs," which was a model 
generalization of combat experience of armies in the 
slaveholding period, it reflected such principles of tactics as 
concentration of force against weakness, surprise ("surprise 
frightens an enemy and usually costs little"[.sup]2[/]), 
coordination and swiftness of operations. 
  No great progress in military affairs was achieved in the 
era 
of feudalism. The art of fighting a battle and war as a whole 
remained at a low level. But even in this period many works on 
strategy and tactics appeared which enriched military theory and 
facilitated development of principles of battle. Works by N. 
Machiavelli, Maurice of Orange and Gustavus Adolphus should be 
noted especially. Thus, in the "Treatise on Military Art," the 
Florentine Machiavelli substantiated the principle of 
historicity and logical patterns in development of military art. 
In tactics, he gave preference to the principle of aggressive, 
decisive actions. His recommendations on aligning combat 
formations, on establishing reserves and on questions of command 
and control and logistic support of troops were of great 
interest. 
  Maurice of Orange, a major military figure of the 
Netherlands, performed a big job in reorganizing the army, 
giving it features of a regular army, and introduced a new 
combat formation--he began employing a linear alignment instead 
of the square columns used in European armies. In practical 
command and control activity, he attached great significance to 
the principle of thorough support of combat operations and to 
the factor of morale. Principles of tactics, especially those 
such as centralization and firmness of command and control, 
massing of forces and flexibility of interworking, received a 
skillful interpretation in military activity of Swedish military 
leader Gustavus Adolphus. 
  Cromwell made a significant contribution to development of 
military art in the period of the British bourgeois revolution 
(1642-1649). His revolutionary army surpassed the King's troops 
in combat effectiveness, capability of accomplishing bold 
actions, precision and organization. 
  Principles of military art received fullest formalization in 
the late 17th and early 18th centuries. Of military theorists 
and field generals of this period who substantially contributed 
to the development of military affairs, one should note French 
Marshal Turenne, Austrian field general Eugene of Savoy, and 
General Montecuccoli. Their combat experience was studied and 
used as guidance by many field generals. In the work "Notes on 
War," General Montecuccoli set forth such principles of battle 
as purposefulness, the ability to commensurate one's forces 
("whoever intends to conquer the entire world in battle feeds on 
the winds and chases the wind"), swiftness and decisiveness of 
actions, surprise and maneuver. 
  Major military writers Fuller and Gibert devoted much 
attention to questions of development of tactics. In 
generalizing experience of wars, they compared it with the 
experience of wars of the ancient world and drew appropriate 
conclusions from this. Gibert's work "Experience of Tactics" 
played no small role in questions of development of principles 
of linear tactics. He favored high troop mobility and an 
improvement in the organization of infantry. Prussian King and 
military leader Frederick II substantially influenced 
development of strategy and tactics in the 18th century. As F. 
Engels wrote, he took linear tactics to perfection. One 
principle of his actions was the "oblique attack," the essence 
of which was a concentration of efforts against one of the enemy 
flanks. 
  A new stage in development of military affairs begun by 
bourgeois revolutions in Europe and mass employment of firearms 
was marked by military science being given an orderly system. 
Works by British military writer Henry Lloyd and German writer 
Heinrich Dietrich von Bulow played an important role in 
this. 
  In the work "Political and Military Memoirs" General Lloyd 
attempted to develop fundamentals of a general theory of war. He 
believed that military art was based on permanent principles, 
among which he included security of the line of operations and a 
five-march logistic system. To achieve success in an engagement, 
Lloyd wrote, do not split your forces, display swiftness and 
firmness, employ maneuver and strive for concealment. 
  Von Bulow's work "Spirit of the Newest System" 
theoretically generalized everything new that had been created 
in the era of revolution. For the first time he noted the 
significance of a mass army, analyzed the content of strategy 
and tactics and defined them. "Strategy," wrote von Bulow, 
"is the science of military movements outside of view or of the 
reach of a cannon shot, and tactics is the science of military 
movements within these limits."[.sup]3[/] Von Bulow 
developed several new theoretical concepts such as a base of 
operations, strategic deployment, the objective of war and so on. 
  New organizational forms which appeared in wars of the 
French 
Revolution were of great significance for development of 
military theory, particularly establishing the army corps, 
upgrading the structure of the division as the basic tactical 
combat unit, and improving the organization of artillery, which 
in some engagements was massed in large groups numbering 
hundreds of pieces. A cavalry was established capable of 
conducting various combat operations and of swift assault in 
tight formation. The logistic support system was improved, which 
helped increase the army's mobility. 
  The new army advanced new methods of combat operations, 
which 
received the most striking manifestation in Napoleon's strategy 
and tactics. Decisiveness of goals, an attempt to defeat the 
enemy army at one crushing blow, swiftness of actions, 
simplicity of maneuver, the ability to achieve surprise, and 
delivery of an attack with massive concentrated attack 
forces--those were the most typical features and principles of 
his military art, which had an enormous influence on subsequent 
development of military theory and practice. For an entire 
century military theorists were captives of Napoleonic strategy 
and tactics. 
  A major event in military life was the appearance in 1813 of 
a capital work by Austrian field general Archduke Karl of 
Austria "Principles of Strategy Illustrated by An Account of the 
Campaign of 1796 in Germany." It formulated rather precisely 
such principles of strategy and tactics as concentrating a 
numerical superiority of forces and employing them on the 
decisive axis, properly calculating personnel and equipment, 
skillfully choosing the moment for delivering an attack, winning 
time, and establishing strong reserves. But it should be said 
that Archduke Karl was one of the forefathers of the theory of 
eternal and immutable principles of war. He feared risk and went 
down in history as the "circumspect" field general. 
  The formation and development of principles of military art 
are linked closely with names of the most prominent military 
theorists of the latter half of the 19th century H. Jomini and 
C. von Clausewitz. Jomini believed that military art must have 
its scientific theory based on recognition of a number of 
immutable principles, which in his opinion existed since 
earliest times and were manifested in the activity of great 
field generals. He included the following among the most 
important principles of military art: Aggressiveness; proper 
choice of strategic points ("keys"); skillful maneuvering to 
move onto internal enemy lines of operations; economy of forces 
in secondary sectors and decisive direction of one's efforts 
against one of the vulnerable points; and establishment of 
strategic reserves. 
  Outstanding military philosopher von Clausewitz created the 
famous work "On War," which reflected a general theory of 
warfare. Von Clausewitz also played a major role in systemizing 
principles of military art. He included numerical strength, 
concentration of forces and surprise among the most general 
principles. Von Clausewitz took the point of view of conducting 
decisive, aggressive combat operations. He recognized the 
general engagement and crushing of enemy personnel to be an 
important means of achieving the goals of war. Von Clausewitz 
attached great importance to purposefulness of actions, the 
material factor and the factor of morale. 
  While giving due respect in the formation and development of 
principles of strategy and tactics to prominent military figures 
and military writers who laid the foundations of military 
science, at the same time it should be noted that combat 
practice directly played an enormous role in shaping principles 
of military art. It served as a criterion of effectiveness of 
developed standards, rules and precepts. War mercilessly cast 
aside everything far-fetched and artificial, affirmed what had 
been tested, and cleared the way for what was vital and 
necessary. Various hypotheses and theories were born and died in 
the flame of battles, but there was an invariable process of 
forward movement, and tactics, operational art and strategy were 
enriched and developed. 
  The permanent value of principles of battle reflected in 
military works, manuals and regulations is that they serve as a 
unique bridge between past and present. The path to the future 
lies through them. By understanding them, the military leader 
receives the experience of preceding generations and moves 
further and reaches new stages of combat perfection based on 
lessons of the past. 
  The 20th century went down in history as a century of 
machines and motors. New machines and new equipment were 
intensively introduced not only to production, but also to 
military affairs. The appearance of new weapons necessitated a 
search for new strategic and tactical concepts, which gave 
powerful impetus to the study of war and development of 
principles of military art. A large number of 
military-theoretical works were published not long before World 
War I, among them works by German military writers von der Holtz 
"An Armed People," Schlichting "Principles of Modern Military 
Tactics and Strategy," A. von Schliffen "Cannae," Bernhardi "On 
War of Today," major French military figure and military 
theorist F. Foch "On Principles of War" and "On Waging War," 
military writer Levalle "Introduction to the Positive Part of 
Strategy," "March Strategy" and "Battle Strategy," American 
Admiral A. Mahan "The Influence of Sea Power Upon History," and 
British Admiral P. Colomb, "Naval Warfare, Its Basic Principles 
and Experience." 
  World War I was a stern test of military-theoretical 
concepts. Many prewar concepts did not stand up to the tests and 
were rejected by combat practice as impracticable. At the same 
time, the experience of war and the new phenomena of warfare 
which arose in its course served as the basis for further 
development of principles of strategy, operational art and 
tactics. Thus, the theories of "blitzkrieg," "tank" and "air" 
war, and "small professional armies" appeared following World 
War I. The theory of the deep operation originated in Soviet 
military science and saw some development. As a result of this, 
all component parts of military art took a new step in their 
development. 
  World War II influenced the content of strategy, operational 
art and tactics even more than World War I. With respect to 
principles of tactics, their development in the course of this 
war as well as in contemporary local wars will be examined in 
more detail in appropriate chapters of the work. 
  Russia's military-theoretical thought made a ponderable 
contribution to the depository of world military art and to 
development and enrichment of its principles. There is no need 
here to anticipate the further presentation of material; we will 
note only that sources of Russian military art take their 
beginning from ancient times. It took shape and developed 
largely on an independent, distinctive path and therefore has 
many specific features. The successful campaign of Kievan 
princes Oleg and Svyatoslav and subsequently the military 
leadership activity of Aleksandr Nevskiy, Dmitriy Donskoy and 
Ivan the Terrible can serve as a vivid example of how high the 
level of development of military art was in Ancient Rus. 
  The "Poucheniya" [Precepts] of Vladimir Monomakh, which set 
forth important rules (principles) of attaining success in 
campaigns and recommendations on ensuring surprise, making 
marches, and methods of conducting an offensive, was one of the 
early ancient Russian military-theoretical works. 
  Military-theoretical thought developed especially rapidly 
under Peter I and Catherine II. A. V. Suvorov called Peter the 
Great the first field general of his century. The Northern War 
and later the Seven Years' War were a major school for Russian 
military art. The beginning of an independent national Russian 
military school was laid down under Peter the Great; its 
continuers were Russian field generals and naval leaders P. A. 
Rumyantsev, A. V. Suvorov, M. I. Kutuzov and F. F. Ushakov. They 
introduced much that was new to strategy and tactics and they 
glorified and brought fame to Russian military art. 
  The Russian army and navy won numerous victories over armies 
of Frederick II and Napoleon, and also over Turkish troops. The 
Patriotic War of 1812-1814 showed that the Russian Army was the 
bearer of the most advanced military experience. 
  Russian military heritage still needs to be revealed. The 
role of Catherine the Great in glorifying Russia, including in 
developing military affairs, was undeservedly minimized. In 
paying due respect to Western European military figures who did 
a great deal for the formation of military science, due respect 
also must be paid to military-theoretical works of Russian 
military writers. Principles of military theory were developed 
in works by I. G. Burtsov "Mysli o teorii voyennykh znaniy" 
[Thoughts on the Theory of Military Knowledge], N. V. Medem 
"Obozreniye izvestneyshikh pravil i sistem strategii" [Survey of 
the Most Well-Known Rules and Systems of Strategy], P. Ya. 
Yazykov "Opyt teorii strategii" [Experience of the Theory of 
Strategy], M. I. Bogdanovich "Zapiski strategii" [Notes of 
Strategy] and N. D. Neyelov "Ocherk sovremennogo sostoyaniya 
strategii" [Essay on the Present State of Strategy]. Principles 
of military art were formulated especially fully and precisely 
in works by N. P. Mikhnevich "Strategiya" [Strategy], A. G. 
Yelchaninov "Vedeniye sovremennykh voyn i boya" [Conduct of 
Modern Wars and Battle], V. A. Cheremisov "Osnovy sovremennogo 
voyennogo iskusstva" [Fundamentals of Modern Military Art], A. 
A. Neznamov "Sovremennaya voyna" [Modern War], and G. A. Leyer 
"Strategiya" [Strategy] as well as in works by a number of other 
Russian military scholars--D. A. Milyutin, A. K. Puzyrevskiy, D. 
F. Maslovskiy, A. Z. Myshloyevskiy, M. I. Dragomirov, S. O. 
Makarov, A. A. Gulevich, V. F. Novitskiy and others. 
  Publication of the Russian "Voyennaya entsiklopediya" 
[Military Encyclopedia] (1911-1915) substantially contributed to 
the formation and systemization of principles of military art. 
It established four principles of military art: Superiority of 
forces; significance of the spiritual element in war; 
significance of chance happenings, and surprise. It was 
emphasized that superiority of forces is the basis of 
victory.[.sup]4[/] 
  It is apparent from the brief historical sketch that the 
theory of military art underwent a complex evolution over many 
centuries of history. Its study and profound understanding 
permit identifying stable logical patterns which determined the 
origin and formation of principles of military art and tactics. 
  The methodological importance of principles of military art 
was that they served and serve as the pivotal basis of all its 
component parts--strategy, operational art and tactics--and they 
determine unity of views of military cadres on fundamental 
provisions of preparing and conducting combat operations. And 
inasmuch as tactics is an integrally indissoluble component of 
military art, the formation of its principles can be understood 
only by having precisely understood the mutual relationship of 
tactics with strategy and with operational art. Let us dwell on 
this in more detail. 
  The role and place of tactics and its principles in 
evolution 
of military art were determined by the significance of the 
battle in the system of warfare. It is known that for many 
centuries the battle played the deciding role in the course and 
outcome of war and in accomplishing missions of strategy. 
Principles of preparing and conducting combat operations have 
originated and taken shape in the depths of tactics and then 
have been accepted by strategy from time immemorial. This was 
dictated by many objective reasons: First of all, by the fact 
that for many centuries means of warfare were insufficiently 
perfect and all without exception were concentrated in the 
tactical sphere; secondly, armies were relatively small and the 
material base supplying the war was poorly developed. Under such 
conditions military operations usually developed into a brief 
clash culminating in a general engagement. For a long time the 
concept of "battle" was identical to the concept of "military 
operations." Thus, the "Entsiklopediya voyennykh i morskikh 
nauk" [Encyclopedia of Military and Naval Sciences] published in 
1883 gives the following definition of battle: "The battle is a 
general concept," "a battle [boy] of two armies which decided 
the fate of the war or of a separate operation . . . is called a 
general engagement or battle [bitva]," "a battle [boy] of two 
armies of a less definite nature than in the previous case which 
decided neither the fate of the war nor even of a separate 
operation, but which led to a more or less substantial change in 
the situation for both sides in the theater of military 
operations . . . is called an engagement [srazheniye]. . . . A 
clash of independent parts of two armies--corps, divisions--is 
called a battle [boy]."[.sup]5[/] 
  With the origin of operations as a new form of warfare there 
appeared a new intermediate link between strategy and 
tactics--operational art, which initially was still not 
officially recognized by military theory. The battle no longer 
acted as the chief means of achieving the goals of war, but only 
as one of its forms, the operation. One local battle, no matter 
how important it might be, and even one major engagement where 
the sides had several armies, no longer decisively affected the 
general course of military operations. The path of war from its 
beginning to its conclusion began running through many, many 
successful and unsuccessful offensive and defensive battles and 
engagements, which were combined into army and then also into 
front operations (operations of a group of armies), and the 
latter into military campaigns that were lengthy in time. 
  With the appearance of operational art as an independent 
component of military art, the need arose for military theory to 
identify the new interrelationship among principles of strategy, 
operational art and tactics. Traditional interworking between 
strategy and tactics was disrupted under the existing 
conditions. Tactics no longer exerted a direct effect, but an 
indirect effect on strategy through operational art. Only a 
multitude of tactical operations in the aggregate, summed up, 
produced an operational result and through the operation 
determined the content of war and its successful or unsuccessful 
outcome. Under the influence of this the internal 
interrelationship among principles of component parts of 
military art became more complicated and the influence of 
requirements of operational art and strategy on the content of 
principles of battle intensified. 
  The role of battle as the basis and chief means of achieving 
the goals of an operation and war was preserved until the 
strategic and operational command element had at their disposal 
their own personnel and equipment which were not part of 
combined arms formations and units. This process began with the 
appearance of aviation in the course of World War I and 
continued after its conclusion, but it was developed with 
special force in World War II. In addition to long-range 
(strategic) aviation, the strategic (operational) leadership at 
that time had airborne troops; air defense troops; powerful, 
highly mobile tank and mechanized large strategic formations; 
and Supreme High Command Reserve artillery formations. These 
personnel and equipment were employed in operations not only for 
reinforcing operational and tactical groupings, but also for 
performing certain independent missions. 
  But even under these conditions the decisive importance in 
achieving operational and strategic results still remained with 
tactics. Tactical actions continued to hold the principal place 
in the system of operations. This was dictated by the fact that 
immediate defeat of the enemy could be achieved only by battle, 
and the majority of personnel and means of warfare continued to 
be at the tactical level. The supreme and operational command 
elements were purposefully in charge of tactical forces and 
assets and created favorable conditions for their employment: in 
preparing and carrying out the operation, they specified 
objectives and missions for formations and units, organized 
interworking among them within the scope of the operation, gave 
them combat and logistic support, and coordinated combat 
operations. 
  But already at that time their own specific principles 
inherent only to these echelons had appeared within the 
framework of operational art and strategy, such as attaining 
simultaneous deep engagement of the enemy. True, in World War II 
this principle was incompletely implemented in practice. The 
problem was that artillery, which basically was at the tactical 
level and whose range capabilities were limited, accomplished 
the primary mission of suppressing the enemy. Although the share 
of participation of operational and strategic assets in 
defeating the enemy increased considerably, it did not become 
decisive. The goal of the operation was achieved in the final 
account by joint operations of formations and units on the 
battlefield, and beyond the battlefield by air strikes delivered 
against the enemy at a varying depth by aviation forces, by 
commitment of mobile groups of fronts and armies both in the 
tactical as well as operational zones of enemy defense, and also 
by the landing of airborne and amphibious assault forces in the 
defenders' rear. General success in such operations was the 
result of efforts both of tactical as well as operational and 
strategic assets, but the latter's proportion in the war 
remained relatively low because of their insufficiently high 
combat effectiveness. The main enemy forces were "pulverized" 
chiefly on the battlefield, in the tactical zone. The battle 
continued to hold a central place in war. Not one engagement, 
not one operation was conceivable without it. 
  The "disposition of forces" in military art became 
qualitatively different with the appearance of nuclear weapons. 
New interrelationships among strategy, operational art and 
tactics took shape under their influence, manifested in the fact 
that the strategic echelon occupied the predominant role in 
accomplishing missions of war, inasmuch as the most powerful 
weapons were concentrated under its command. Therefore the 
question naturally arises as to what role tactics should play in 
operations under these conditions. 
  It should be said that the development of new approaches to 
forming principles of military art did not go smoothly under the 
new conditions. Both foreign as well as Soviet military 
literature expressed many different viewpoints on prospects of 
development of military art and especially tactics. For example, 
the work "Voyennaya strategiya" [Military Strategy], published 
in 1962 under the editorship of V. D. Sokolovskiy, stated that 
under the new conditions the interrelationship of strategy, 
operational art and tactics should be assessed in a 
fundamentally different way. The authors wrote that the time had 
passed when "it was considered an indisputable fact that a 
general victory in war takes shape from numerous local 
successes. . . . Modern strategic weapons . . . immediately 
subordinate to high commands and permitting achievement of 
decisive results in winning victory in war, often even without 
the involvement of personnel and equipment of the tactical and 
operational level, speak in favor of the thesis that local 
successes now can be determined by successes of a general 
strategic nature."[.sup]6[/] The inference naturally stemmed 
from such a conclusion that the role of tactics essentially is 
becoming secondary under the new conditions. 
  But such views formed under the influence of "nuclear 
euphoria" characteristics of the 1960's, when it was 
unequivocally believed that a future world war certainly would 
be a nuclear war. In the 1970's Soviet military doctrine began 
to take account of the possibility of the outbreak both of a 
nuclear as well as a conventional world war. Accordingly, the 
interrelationship of component parts of military art and the 
role of tactics were presented in a new light. The new concept 
was reflected in the fullest form in the book by A. A. Grechko 
"Vooruzhennyye sily Sovetskogo gosudarstva" [Armed Forces of the 
Soviet State], published in 1975. Speaking of the importance of 
tactics, the author wrote: "Regardless of the means by which war 
is waged, tactics remains the base for achieving operational and 
strategic successes." And even: "It begins . . . specifically . 
. . with tactics, it is accomplished by tactics, and the 
implementation of operational and strategic concepts is 
completed by tactics."[.sup]7[/] 
  In recent years judicious state figures have been conducting 
intensified searches for those military-strategic concepts which 
would provide an opportunity to achieve political goals without 
the danger of outbreak of a general nuclear war threatening 
disastrous consequences for mankind. Today's impressions of a 
possible war differ from past ones by the fact that ever greater 
preference is given to military operations with conventional 
weapons. But inasmuch as the probability of conduct of different 
kinds of war, both a world conventional war as well as a world 
nuclear war, is preserved even now, the armed forces of the 
majority of countries are forced to master methods of combat 
operations with and without the use of nuclear weapons. These 
requirements then are made the basis for development of tactical 
principles. 
  An orderly system of principles of combined arms battle 
encompassing all aspects of its preparation and conduct has 
taken shape in our military art at the present time. The 
following are among the most important of them: constant combat 
readiness of subunits; decisiveness, aggressiveness and 
continuity in fighting a battle; coordinated employment of 
subunits of combat arms and special troops and maintenance of 
continuous interworking among them; surprise of operations and 
the use of stratagem (deceiving the enemy); decisive 
concentration of efforts on the main axis and at the decisive 
moment; maneuver of subunits, strikes and fire; timely 
restoration of subunits' combat effectiveness and comprehensive 
support of battle; full exertion of moral and physical forces 
and use of the moral-psychological factor to perform the combat 
mission; and firm, continuous command and control of 
subunits.[.sup]8[/] 
  Speaking of general principles of combined arms battle, one 
should note their interrelationship with particular principles 
which are the basis of combat employment of formations, units 
and subunits of combat arms and special troops. The latter form 
under the determining influence of principles of general 
tactics. At the same time, specifics of combat employment of 
each combat arm (or special troops) are reflected in their 
content. Particular principles of combat arms exert a specific 
effect on the content of principles of combined arms battle. 
  The content both of general as well as particular principles 
reflects the level of development tactics has achieved. Their 
strength and vitality lies in the fact that they do not rely on 
secondary, insignificant, transient circumstances but reflect 
deep processes of combat operations, stable interrelationships 
and objective logical patterns, cognition of which serves as a 
unique reference point for the commander; by adhering to it he 
finds the true path to achieving the goal set in the battle. 
  Principles of military art are reflected in one form or 
another in field service regulations (field manuals, other 
manuals, and guides of all world armies). The U.S. 
Army attaches great significance to them. The U.S. Field 
Service Regulations point out that principles are the foundation 
of the truth about war, and sensible use of them ensures victory 
over the enemy. According to U.S. Army Field Manual FM 100 
(1982), principles of military art are systemized in the 
following order: general principles of war are formulated, and 
principles of the air-land operation (battle) as well as 
principles relating to kinds of combat operations are formulated 
within their framework. The following are among principles of 
war for the Army: Purposefulness; the offensive; massing of 
personnel and equipment; economy of personnel and equipment; 
mobility; unity of command and control; security; surprise; 
simplicity. 
  The principles of battle are subdivided by kinds into 
offensive and defensive. The following are considered principles 
of offensive operations: concentration of personnel and 
equipment; surprise; swiftness; flexibility and decisiveness. 
Concentration of forces is considered an integral part of the 
offensive. 
  The idea of depriving an attacking enemy of advantages and 
quickly seizing the initiative is made the basis of principles 
of defensive operations. Principle No 1 is worded as follows: 
Seize the tactical initiative in individual sectors, and then 
also the general initiative as the transition is made from 
defense to offensive. Principle No 2 states: deliver attacks to 
the full depth of enemy combat formations, which will permit 
delaying and disorganizing him and also creating conditions for 
launching an offensive. A defense in depth gives an opportunity 
to win time and space for executing a swift, flexible maneuver. 
Principle No 3 requires: Dictate conditions of battle to the 
enemy and maintain swiftness and flexibility of fire, maneuver, 
and employment of EW assets. Principle No 4 requires: Coordinate 
operations of all personnel and equipment at your disposal in 
the course of battle and take advantage of the slightest enemy 
weaknesses to stop his offensive. 
  FRG Bundeswehr field manuals usually enumerate the 
following principles of combat operations: Seizure of the 
initiative and activeness; aggressiveness; concentration of 
personnel and equipment at the decisive place and at a favorable 
time; massing of fire in a decisive sector and execution of a 
bold maneuver; interworking; surprise; decisiveness of 
operations, persistence and display of initiative; 
strong-willed, constant, precise command and control; and 
uninterrupted combat and logistic support. 
  Field manuals of the British Army consider the 
most important principles of battle to be the following: Choice 
and approval of the objective; offensive combat operations; 
interworking; freedom of actions; concentration of forces; 
economy of forces; surprise; indirect actions (deceptive 
procedures); combat support of troops; maintenance of healthy 
morale; and command and control of troops and the rear. 
  It is apparent that principles of battle are understood 
differently in different armies depending on traditions which 
have formed, the level of development of military art, depth of 
cognition of logical patterns of warfare, and their 
philosophical interpretation. Nevertheless, one cannot help but 
note that in its essence the wording of the majority of 
principles has a logical similarity. Their important role in 
military art is assessed to a like degree in all armies. 
Speaking of the content of principles of battle, military 
theorists and practitioners always emphasize simplicity and 
accessibility of their understanding. As von Clausewitz wrote, 
"principles of military art in themselves are to the highest 
degree simple and in full accord with common sense."[.sup]9[/] 
<H3>  2. Guiding Lights in the Commander's Control Activity in 
Battle </H3>
  The principles of battle have dual significance for military 
theory and practice. On the one hand, they are the basis for 
systemization of scientific knowledge and logical construction 
of the theory of tactics, reflecting its corresponding level of 
development. On the other hand, they are guiding lights, guiding 
recommendations, by which the commander finds the true path to 
achieving the assigned objective in a difficult combat 
situation. Figuratively speaking, they are the reference points 
of victory. In this section we will speak of the importance of 
principles in command and control. 
  To begin with let us pose the following question: Is it 
possible to exercise command and control of subunits and achieve 
success in battle without knowing the principles of military 
art? We will answer as follows: Generally such a case is not 
precluded under certain particular simplified conditions. If we 
refer to Great Patriotic War experience, then of course not all 
commanders at the tactical level had high erudition and were 
sufficiently trained theoretically in order to deliberately 
apply appropriate principles in practical activity. It can be 
said that many mastered the difficult science of winning 
intuitively, based on practical experience they gained and a 
knowledge of the provisions of regulations. 
  An officer who does not know the principles of military art 
but who prepares for battle can be compared with a wayfarer who, 
being in open country or a dense forest with neither map nor 
compass, tries to find the road to the necessary point. It is 
quite obvious that he will have to wander a great deal. But 
while this will cost the wayfarer loss of time and effort, it 
will cost a commander loss of people and possibly also loss of 
the battle. In order for this not to happen it is necessary to 
"arm" oneself ahead of time both theoretically and practically: 
Learn the nature of modern battle well, know its principles, and 
learn to apply them skillfully in practice. Like invisible 
"advisers," at a difficult moment they will suggest to him how 
to act, how to find the way out of a difficult situation, how 
not to be taken in, and how to avoid mistakes and 
miscalculations. These "advisers" have the wisdom of experience 
of many, many generations behind them and they can be fully 
trusted. 
  Thus it is a question of scientific command and control, of 
that command and control which relies on a knowledge of laws and 
logical patterns of warfare, from which principles of military 
art logically stem. Delving into the mechanism of action of 
these laws permits finding the most effective methods and 
procedures of exerting an effect in the necessary direction on 
the conditions under which laws arise and function and finding 
maximum opportunities in the situation at hand for making and 
implementing faultless decisions. 
  Laws are an objective category. They act independently of a 
person's will and desire, independently of whether or not a 
commander needs this or whether he likes or does not like the 
effect of the laws. He cannot choose particular laws, but must 
reckon with them. Conversely, principles based on the laws are 
applied consciously by man depending on specific situation 
conditions. They contain recommendations about what must be done 
to achieve victory and how one must act. Principles successfully 
combine both the necessary nature of effect of laws of war and 
the relative freedom of people's conscious activity within the 
framework of this necessity. 
  The wording of principles reflects not only requirements of 
laws, but also those goals and missions to which military 
activity is subordinated. Prominent Civil War military leader S. 
I. Gusev said it well about the interrelationship of laws of war 
and principles of military art: "That which is a law in 
consideration' becomes a rule in action. What is a law in 
science is a rule in art."[.sup]10[/] 
  A knowledge of the nature of battle and its objective laws 
and logical patterns permits a commander to gain a deep 
understanding of the meaning of events occurring, correctly get 
his bearings and estimate that situation in which battle is 
prepared and waged. And on this largely depends the advisability 
of the decision made and of all the commander's actions in 
command and control. But it would be erroneous to take this 
proposition to mean that in studying specific conditions of 
battle a commander must not fail to find the logical patterns in 
them in order to reinforce their beneficial influence or reduce 
their harmful influence. The operation, the battle and their 
processes are infinite in their specific manifestations, 
properties and relationships. Thorough cognition of their nature 
and discovery of logical patterns are impossible based on a 
single particular instance. This is achieved in the course of 
generalizing many battles under the most diverse situation 
conditions, which is within the capability only of military 
theory. In analyzing combat experience, its task specifically is 
to discard everything random and superficial, find what is an 
often repeated logical pattern, and on this basis develop 
recommendations, rules and principles suitable for practical 
command and control activity. 
  The value of principles of military art is that a 
dialectical 
unity of the objective and subjective in an officer's command 
and control activity is achieved through them. They serve as a 
connecting link between theory and practice and translate the 
content of theoretical provisions of military science into the 
language of military practice. 
  Principles make it incumbent not only to realistically 
estimate the situation at hand, but also to alter it in 
necessary directions by carrying out necessary measures, 
creating favorable conditions for friendly troop operations and 
hampering enemy operations. In themselves, principles are 
passive and do not bring success. They are principles of victory 
and defeat to an equal extent. Everything depends on how 
skillfully or, conversely, how unskillfully a particular side 
uses the demands stemming from them in practice. 
  A knowledge of the principles facilitates the work of a 
commander who is organizing for battle and exercising command 
and control of it. A profound understanding of the complex 
system of interrelationship of laws and logical patterns of 
combat operations and the principles stemming therefrom is a 
reliable precondition for scientific foresight in military 
affairs and enables predicting both the primary trends in 
development of events as well as specific results of particular 
command and control measures. In short, principles serve as the 
basis of officers' combat proficiency. 
  It stands to reason that cognition of principles in itself 
leads to nothing without an ability to apply them in a specific 
situation. While being good reference points, principles cannot 
provide an answer on how to act in the situation at hand. 
Principles are only the "canvas," a starting point for 
decisionmaking, not the decision itself. They point out the 
general direction of an officer's practical activity, but do not 
reveal specific ways of achieving the objective set in battle. 
  Principles embody theoretical aims and their strength lies 
only in unity with practice. A. A. Neznamov noted: "Theory 
cannot set as a goal to point out the best method of actions in 
all instances. The situation in war is so diverse and, moreover, 
changes so swiftly that attempts to ascertain similar methods 
suitable everywhere and always are doomed in advance to 
failure."[.sup]11[/] G. A. Leyer wrote with respect to 
principles: "A principle indicates only the goal, 
which is why it is only a regulator of creativeness, 
the force directing it onto the path of correct decisions, but 
it hardly is a substitute for it."[.sup]12[/] 
  It is a far cry from a knowledge of principles to the 
skillful realization of their requirements, and this distance is 
not covered simply. Let us refer to Great Patriotic War 
experience. All of our Army's field manuals and field service 
regulations emphasized the importance of skillful interworking, 
command and control, massing of forces on decisive axes, and 
combat and logistic support, and the majority of our regular 
commanders theoretically mastered these provisions. 
Nevertheless, it was necessary to go through enormous military 
ordeals and fight hundreds and thousands of battles before 
officers learned to realize in practice the demands of 
principles of military art, which were simple in themselves, in 
preparing and conducting combat operations. 
  The fact is that a combat situation is extremely changeable, 
multiform and contradictory. In it the essential always is fused 
with the inessential, the natural and logical with the random, 
the old with the new. While in other kinds of activity man 
himself often is free to create circumstances favoring 
accomplishment of the assigned mission, in battle it is possible 
to ensure conditions for achieving success each time only by 
overcoming enemy resistance, i.e., across many, many obstacles. 
  Outwardly the battle is a battle of strength, a contest of 
the sides in firepower, swiftness of maneuver, speed in 
delivering strikes and abilities to defend. But behind these 
superficial manifestations hides a stubborn confrontation of 
intellect, of commanders' minds, a contest of the personnel's 
combat proficiency, commensuration of their moral-psychological 
staunchness, physical endurance and skill. With all other 
conditions being equal, the officer who is able to make 
effective use of favorable factors and to neutralize and nullify 
negative ones has more chances for success. 
  Exercising command and control in conformity with principles 
of military art means, first of all, commensurating the troops' 
goals and missions with the situation at hand, with their combat 
capabilities; secondly, not allowing subjectivism and an 
underestimation or overestimation of the enemy and friendly 
troops; thirdly, planning the battle and organizing interworking 
and its comprehensive support not blindly, but based on in-depth 
forecasting, calculations and foresight; fourthly, relying on 
objective conditions and a knowledge of the nature of battle and 
trends in its development. 
  The enumerated requirements are realized not mechanically, 
but creatively, in strict conformity with the situation. The 
commander cannot help but reckon with the fact that the desired 
goals far from always can correspond to troops' existing combat 
capabilities. The true reality of the state of affairs often can 
differ completely from the situation data received. Only an 
officer who does not think in a stereotyped manner, who is a 
bold innovator, a seeker, and a strong-willed organizer can 
successfully overcome these and many other difficulties and 
contradictions, make the optimum decision and achieve its 
realization. 
  This is especially important now. Never before have military 
affairs developed with such intensity as now, and this opens up 
a broad expanse for officers' creative searches both in theory 
of tactics as well as in practical command and control activity, 
in decisionmaking, and in innovative application of principles 
of battle. The fact is that at the present stage rates of 
renewal of the troops' material-technical base have accelerated 
extraordinarily. And inasmuch as tactics as the most dynamic 
sphere of military art directly reflects processes of change in 
weapons and combat equipment, officers are faced with the task 
of comprehending new phenomena occurring in military affairs 
with maximum mobility and coming up with necessary 
recommendations for the troops' practical assimilation of the 
most effective methods of preparing and conducting battle 
meeting a higher level of development of means of warfare. 
  Such a task is not new. The need to develop tactics 
creatively arose for military cadres in the past. It is known 
that in the postwar period two qualitative leaps in upgrading 
arms occurred in the Soviet Armed Forces and each time it 
demanded that the theory of tactics substantially revise views 
that had formed on the nature of combined arms battle and on the 
content of its fundamental principles. The first such leap 
occurred in the 1950's in connection with nuclear weapons 
becoming operational with the troops, which as noted above gave 
rise to a genuine revolution in military affairs. And in the 
altered conditions our generals and officers managed to work out 
fully and comprehensively the methods for troops to perform 
combat missions in the offensive and defense and effective 
methods of aligning combat formations of formations and units, 
fire damage of the enemy, and organization and accomplishment of 
interworking, command and control, and comprehensive support to 
battle. In the final account, all this was reflected in the 
content of principles of combined arms battle. 
  Many new missions arose for tactics during the 1960's and 
1970's in connection with introduction of missile weapons to the 
troops, which marked the second qualitative leap in development 
of means of warfare and military affairs as a whole. The 
increased power, depth and quick-acting nature of weapons in 
combination with increased troop mobility gave combined arms 
battle an even greater decisiveness and dynamic nature and 
increased its spatial scope. Under the altered conditions, our 
military cadres had to work out tactics of modern battle on a 
more contemporary material-technical basis, rethink the 
principles of its preparation and conduct, and bring their 
content into line with the increased requirements of operational 
art and strategy. 
  At the present time a third qualitative leap is occurring in 
development of military equipment within the framework of the 
continuing revolution in military affairs. It was caused not 
only by a further upgrading of nuclear weapons, but also by the 
intensive development of deep-strike, precision, automated 
weapon systems and by the ever increasing introduction to the 
Ground Troops of aircraft, diverse EW equipment and equipment 
for automating command and control of troops and weapons. 
  Another important feature of the present stage in 
development 
of combined arms battle is that substantial changes occurred in 
operating tactics of foreign armies. In the early 1980's, the 
U.S. Army adopted a fundamentally new "air-land operation" 
(battle) concept and armies of its Western European allies 
adopted a variety of it, the "follow-on forces attack." 
According to these concepts, as noted in the field service 
regulations of these armies, the success of combat operations is 
made dependent on observance of four fundamental principles: 
Initiative, depth, speed and coordination of efforts. 
  It is emphasized that the principle of initiative requires 
preempting the enemy in order to disorganize his troops and 
alter the correlation of personnel and equipment in one's own 
favor. The essence of the principle of depth is to 
comprehensively strive to increase rates of advance and spatial 
scope of combat operations. 
  It is believed that success of offensive and defensive 
operations depends to a decisive extent on timely, reliable 
engagement of the enemy to the full depth of his combat 
alignment. The goal of deep interdiction in the offensive, note 
the regulations, is to isolate the combat operations area, 
disrupt the defender's maneuver, reduce the mobility of his 
actions, not allow a regrouping of personnel and equipment to 
restore defense integrity, prevent the approach of reserves and 
cut them off from the main body. The following are the primary 
missions of deep fire interdiction in the defense: Splitting and 
disorganizing the attacker's combat formations, destroying enemy 
weapons, command and control facilities and communications 
centers, and covering an ongoing maneuver of personnel and 
equipment. 
  The principle of speed envisages flexibility in the 
organization of troops and promptness in the thinking of 
commanders who are capable of preempting the enemy in operations 
and immediately countering him with measures which may lead to 
disruption of his plans. 
  The principle of coordination of efforts is understood to 
mean complete unification of efforts of all troops involved in 
the battle and also of weapons--nuclear, chemical and 
conventional--to achieve maximum combat power and most effective 
use of combat capabilities of troops as a whole and of each unit 
separately. 
  Profound, cardinal changes in views on the nature of battle 
both in our own Army as well as in foreign armies elevates the 
role of commanders' tactical art. Creative searches for new 
solutions in methods of preparing and conducting combat 
operations, the development and enrichment of principles of 
military art, and foresight of prospects for development of 
tactics now are especially important. The entire system for 
training and educating military cadres must be directed forward. 
  Referring to history, it can be noted that the most 
prevalent 
mistake of many armies was that they often prepared "for the 
past war," if it can be thus expressed. That is, they could not 
determine the outlines of future operations and battles 
accurately enough and, out of inertia, continued to master those 
principles of combat operations which already had become 
obsolete long ago. At one time A. A. Svechin, editor of 
"Strategiya v trudakh voyennykh klassikov " [Strategy in Works 
of Military Classics], speaking of the work by French military 
theorist Foch "On Principles of War," correctly noted that "it 
contains the present military system, but one that has proven to 
be not at all in conformity with that reality which world war 
unfolded."[.sup]13[/] It must be said that a multitude of 
major mistakes and miscalculations were made at all 
levels--strategic, operational and tactical--both on the eve of 
World War I as well as of World War II. 
  It cannot be said that our Army and its military cadres 
presently have shifted completely to the new training system and 
have rid themselves of the burden of attributes of stagnant 
times in combat training. Proof of this is that at times in the 
course of conducting tactical exercises an oversimplified 
ground-air and electronic situation is created, deep targets 
remain outside the enemy's fire effect, a certain methodism and 
linear movement of troops from line to line is displayed in the 
dynamics of battle, head-on attacks are delivered, and a rather 
lengthy, passive confrontation of the sides is allowed in the 
process of combat operations. This clearly does not facilitate 
development of officers' active creative search, does not 
mobilize them for a struggle against a strong enemy, and does 
not contribute to instilling the necessary organizing and 
volitional qualities. This is why many young officers are very 
timid in tackling the independent rehearsal of difficult 
tactical missions and often act by direction. 
  We now need a decisive turning point in officers' creative 
thinking and clear realization of the fact that it is impossible 
to accomplish new missions in combat training by old methods. 
Although the wording of the absolute majority of principles of 
combined arms battle has not undergone changes in recent times 
despite the revolutionary renewal of tactics, their internal 
content and, most important, ways and methods of practical 
realization cannot remain the same. There is nothing now more 
pernicious in combat training than acting in the old way 
according to canons laid down at one time. 
  Profound comprehension of changes occurring in the content 
of 
principles of battle and of methods of their application, and 
development of creative, innovative qualities of military cadres 
are an insistent demand of the time. Experience shows that if an 
officer is devoid of tactical flexibility and adheres to 
banality, then for the most part he cannot apply principles of 
battle effectively. Such an officer has an extremely bare 
arsenal of tactics and, on the other hand, he has more than 
enough oversights and vexing chance happenings. Conversely, an 
active officer who thinks innovatively seemingly doubles or 
trebles the combat capabilities of his troops and increases 
chances for success. The slave to routine cannot get rid of the 
hobbles of dogmatic approaches. Liddell Hart wrote: "It is 
senseless to expect indirect actions of a mediocre general who 
acts straightforwardly and for whom prescribed rules are 
supreme."[.sup]14[/] 
  The basis of an officer's innovative approaches in practical 
application of principles of battle is his erudition, 
operational-tactical outlook, and level of military-theoretical 
training. Only a person who knows military affairs thoroughly 
and comprehensively, studies the probable enemy constantly, and 
supplements and expands his theoretical store can create, seek 
out, and develop tactics. An officer needs theory at every step. 
Not one question that is practical to any extent can be resolved 
without having been comprehended and substantiated 
theoretically. Profound, comprehensive knowledge permits an 
officer to adapt rapidly under any conditions, to assimilate new 
provisions of military art independently and in short time 
periods, and on this basis to seek new, nonstandard decisions 
for missions which arise. 
  An officer's military proficiency can be manifested only on 
the firm foundation of broad scientific knowledge. The one whose 
theoretical knowledge and general erudition is richer always is 
more prepared for a change of weapon systems and for tactical 
innovations. 
  An officer's proper application of principles of battle in 
preparing and conducting battle is impossible without mastering 
the art of dialectical analysis of phenomena of combat reality, 
which permits discovering the inner logic of their development 
and "coupling" a knowledge of logical patterns of warfare in his 
activity with practical embodiment of demands stemming from 
them. Dialectics gives a commander a powerful weapon, the 
method, by relying on which he can uncover the interrelationship 
of phenomena and identify the main, decisive element determining 
success of battle. Great physiologist I. P. Pavlov noted that 
"with a good method even a not very talented person can do a 
great deal. But with a poor method even a genius will work in 
vain and not obtain valuable, exact data."[.sup]15[/] 
  It is necessary to learn to correctly apply principles of 
battle based on a rational learning of lessons from past combat 
experience. Military history is a great teacher. The present 
stands firmly on the shoulders of the past and rests just as 
firmly on wings of the future. The value of the inexhaustible 
treasure-house of military art is that it moves apart the 
framework of an individual's experience which is historically 
limited to a brief time and small space, enriches him with 
cognition of the experience of preceding generations, and 
brightens his thinking with the wise acts of talented field 
generals of the past. The great field generals always regarded 
history with reverence. Napoleon admonished: "Wage an offensive 
war like Alexander, Hannibal, Caesar, Gustavus Adolphus, 
Turenne, Prince Eugene and Frederick; read and then reread the 
history of their 83 campaigns and form your thinking on them; 
this is the only means of becoming a great field general and 
divining the secrets of art; enlightened in that way, your 
awareness will discard rules which are contrary to the 
principles to which the great people adhered."[.sup]16[/] 
  Cognition of past combat experience always is beneficial. Of 
course, military history is incapable of giving answers to 
today's urgent questions. It cannot part the curtains of the 
future, but historical experience is able to persuade, exhort, 
inspire and impregnate an officers' creative thinking, direct 
him to deep reflection and expand his knowledge, and already 
this in itself is a great deal. 
  Combat experience achieved through much sweat and blood of 
many generations permits an officer to choose his aims in life, 
arms him with a value orientation, awakens an innovative spirit 
and a constructive beginning, teaches him to see reality through 
the prism of time, and helps him purposefully solve problems of 
modern times from a scientific standpoint. Historical experience 
of wars also is valuable in that it teaches not only what to do 
and how to do it, but also what should not be done and helps 
avoid repetition of mistakes and find proper ways of 
accomplishing combat missions under modern conditions. By taking 
advantage of historical methods it is possible, in Engels' 
words, to obtain "clarification of the development 
process"[.sup]17[/] and consequently to identify trends, 
trace how principles developed, what stages of evolution they 
went through, and what factors influenced their formation. 
  The study of combat experience should not be passively 
contemplative. It is possible to learn proper lessons from it 
only by examining events in a close interrelationship with those 
conditions and circumstances which took shape at that time. It 
is important here to display maximum objectivity and take into 
account not only the positive, but also the negative 
aspects--the mistakes, miscalculations and shortcomings in 
actions of commanders, staffs and troops. 
  Realization of demands of the principles in a combat 
situation occurs in struggle and involves overcoming a multitude 
of chance happenings occurring literally at every step. And only 
an officer-organizer who has iron will, courage and fearlessness 
and is capable of taking a daring risk where necessary can count 
on success. Hence it is important to comprehensively develop 
organizational, moral-volitional and psychological qualities in 
military cadres. 
  Bagration once remarked wisely that the engagement is a 
simple matter, but winning victory in it is difficult. The 
battle and engagement now have become many times more 
complicated, and difficulties connected with implementing 
decisions also have increased a hundredfold. The battle always 
was a process of fierce confrontation and punished severely for 
oversights and mistakes, which obligated commanders to prepare 
it with all responsibility. Military leaders who participated in 
the Great Patriotic War noted in their memoirs the kinds of 
torture and doubts in which the commander's concepts originated 
each time and what will, courage and ability were required of 
them in decisionmaking. R. Ya. Malinovskiy noted that "the 
moment of decisionmaking was a difficult one for the commanding 
general. You must decide on a great cause and give yourself 
entirely only to one often very risky but very necessary 
decision. In these cases thought works intensely and is full of 
contradictions. One is that the desired decision encounters all 
kinds of objections in terms of calculations; another is that 
enormous difficulties are encountered in implementing it; a 
third is that what is tempting, simple and safe frees one of all 
concerns and legal liability. That is how doubts, difficulties 
and strivings intertwine. But a decision definitely has to be 
made. This demands great courage and enormous 
willpower."[.sup]18[/] 
  It is understandable that such qualities of a commander's 
character as self-control in dangerous situations, courage in 
making responsible decisions, independence, decisiveness and 
determination in achieving the set goal, persistence in 
overcoming difficulties, vigorousness and high working capacity 
do not come to an officer of themselves. It is necessary to 
persistently and purposefully form them in classes and exercises 
in the troops and during training in higher military educational 
institutions. 
  An inclination of some officers to use stereotypes in 
decisionmaking and attempts to find methods of attaining the 
goal by the method of copying another's experience are enemy 
number one in command and control activity. A stereotype's 
tenacity in tactics is explained by the search for easy ways to 
success. Adherence to a stereotype most often is inherent in a 
person whose knowledge is meager and whose operational-tactical 
outlook is narrow. An original idea simply does not appear in 
the officer, but there is a scheme set aside in memory according 
to which either he himself or someone else acted in a similar 
situation. The way to eradicate such a situation is clear--it is 
necessary to elevate the officer's tactical erudition, explain 
to him (best of all from historical examples) where unchanging, 
repetitive actions lead in battle and at the same time show how 
to creatively accomplish missions in the situation at hand, 
achieve surprise, employ stratagem and so on. 
  Often it also happens that an officer is sufficiently 
erudite 
and tactically trained, but still acts conventionally in making 
a decision for battle and does not seek original ways of 
performing the mission. The logic of his reasoning usually is as 
follows: Why take a risk and employ something new? What if 
failure befalls me? In this case the reason for manifestation of 
a stereotype is of a psychological nature. It is the fear of 
responsibility for a bold decision. Consequently, a commander 
must be taught the ability to take a risk, not recklessly, not 
precipitously, but calculatingly and farsightedly. 
  The question has been discussed among military theorists and 
practitioners since olden times as to what should predominate in 
a military leader: Mind or will? Napoleon, for example, believed 
that a field general must have a certain balance between mind 
(talent) and will (character, courage). If character prevails 
over the mind, he said, the field general often acts erroneously 
and, conversely, if the mind outweighs bravery he acts 
indecisively. His companion-in-arms Marshal Marmont reasoned 
differently. In examining the correlation among basic 
field-general qualities, he gave preference to will: "If 
willpower is more strongly developed than mental activity," he 
said, "there is a high probability that the goal will be 
achieved. But if the mind dominates character, a constant change 
of decisions, goals and designs appears..."[.sup]19[/] 
  History resolved this argument of the field generals long 
ago. Combat experience shows that a military leader was equal to 
the occasion only when he combined in himself intellectual and 
organizing qualities--high education, natural intellect, 
farsightedness and prudence, the versatile gift of an organizer, 
an iron will, courage and fearlessness. For example, here is how 
G. K. Zhukov's field-general qualities were described by 
Lieutenant General N. A. Antipenko, his deputy for the rear who 
went through many engagements with him. "A deep inner and outer 
composure, smartness of appearance, high exactingness, 
straightforwardness and principle in views and in relationships 
with people, iron will and an inability to adapt himself to 
anyone's sentiments and opinions whomsoever--these are his 
personality traits which generate a deep respect in me for 
Zhukov.[.sup]20[/] 
  And here is another example. Knowing N. F. Vatutin well, A. 
M. Vasilevskiy wrote: "He was able to decisively concentrate 
personnel and equipment on the main axis, build up efforts and 
suddenly deliver powerful attacks against the flank and rear of 
enemy groupings, skillfully employ large masses of tanks for 
developing the offensive into the operational depth, organize 
firm interworking of combat arms and branches of the Armed 
Forces, and reliably maintain continuous, firm command and 
control."[.sup]21[/] 
  We will note in conclusion that fears of the following 
nature 
sometimes are expressed unjustifiably: Applying principles of 
battle developed by combat experience instils a stereotyped 
approach to accomplishing combat missions. We will make bold to 
assert that such reasoning has no foundation. To the contrary, a 
knowledge and use of principles reflected in field and other 
manuals are a starting point for development of the commander's 
creative initiative. By relying on their provisions and the 
recommendations of regulations, he has an opportunity to seek 
new ways and methods of applying them, arrive at correct 
practical conclusions based on theoretical premises, and develop 
his own commander's "signature." 
<H5>  Conclusions and Recommendations </H5>
  1. The principles of battle are the theoretical frame of 
tactics, its basic scientific foundation. These are not 
arbitrary constructions of theorists' intellect, but the product 
of many centuries of military practice, a compilation of 
military wisdom of many, many generations. The entire lengthy 
historical experience of wars indicates that without guiding 
tactical rules--the principles of battle--directing practice 
along the most correct path and without their regulating role, 
it is impossible to imagine any rational practical activity of 
the commander or staff officer in exercising command and control 
in battle. 
  2. The vitality of principles of military art is that they 
objectively reflect the nature and character of warfare and its 
logical patterns and so allow commanders and staffs to orient 
themselves properly in the most difficult situation, find the 
most effective methods of employing weapons and combat 
equipment, and strive for the enemy's defeat by military art. 
  3. A knowledge of principles of battle becomes a physical 
force on condition that in conformity with a specific situation 
an officer is able to put their demands into practice, thereby 
placing their powerful creative potential at his service. 
  4. Demands of the principles of battle are realized 
practically in complex, unique ways. It always is like solving a 
problem with many unknowns. And the more complicated the battle, 
the stronger the enemy and the more powerful his weapons, the 
more flexible tactical thinking must be. Each time an officer 
must take a new approach to choosing effective ways of achieving 
the goal. 
  5. The value of principles of military art lies in the fact 
that they do not in any way bind an officer's initiative but, 
conversely, grant him a certain freedom in choosing methods of 
operations in performing a specific practical mission. Mobility 
of a search, daring of thinking, a bold risk, realistic 
calculation and reliance on a scientific foundation are 
necessary for creative embodiment of demands of the principles 
of military art. 
  6. Principles of battle are not realized each one 
individually, but in an interrelationship. Each principle is 
only a separate link in a common chain. Achieving success in 
battle requires skillful use of the full scientific arsenal of 
tactics and its fundamental principles. 
  7. Having a common basis, principles of all component parts 
of military art--strategy, operational art and tactics--ensure 
uniformity of views of military cadres at all levels on methods 
of preparing and conducting combat operations. But commonality 
of starting positions does not preclude different approaches to 
applying the demands of a particular principle in a specific 
situation. 
