Echoes], St. Petersburg, 1902, p 85. 
  20. N. A. Antipenko, "Na glavnom napravlenii" [On the Main 
Axis], Moscow, Nauka, 1971, p 229. 
  21. A. M. Vasilevskiy, "Delo vsey zhizni" [A Lifelong Job], 
Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1974, p 398. 
<H5>  CHAPTER TWO - PERMANENT COMBAT READINESS OF SUBUNITS </H5>
  Permanent combat readiness of subunits consists 
of their capability of entering battle in an organized manner at 
any time and at prescribed time periods and performing assigned 
missions successfully. 
  "Boyevoy ustav 
Sukhoputnykh voysk" [Ground Troops Field Manual], Part II 
<H3>  1. From the History of the Origin and Development of the 
Principle of Combat Readiness </H3>
  Each time I have occasion to speak and read about combat 
readiness, there invariably appears before me the indelible 
picture of 22 June 1941, which I witnessed with my own eyes. The 
tornado of artillery fire which suddenly came down on the 
barracks at dawn, the fire which soon blazed up, Red Army men 
rushing about in disarray, the incoherent bustle, the orderly's 
belated command "Combat alert!" and the confusion and 
helplessness of commanders who were trying to get their bearings 
in the situation, establish communications with the senior 
commander, receive at least some kind of instructions and take 
control into their own hands--all this was perceived as a 
nightmarish dream. I finally came to my senses only when I heard 
the desperate appeal for help of a comrade who had been caught 
beneath a heap of rubble. That was how the Great Patriotic War 
began for me. 
  Even now, after 50 years have elapsed since that time, I do 
not cease to ask myself: "How could this have happened?" For on 
the evening before, on Sunday, we heard the cheerful song over 
the radio: "Should tomorrow war come, should tomorrow we march, 
be ready today for the march." The song not only summoned, but 
also inspired: "And we'll crush the enemy with little blood, 
with a powerful blow!" 
  And a week before that we were read an address of the Baltic 
Military District Military Council. "...Today as never before," 
it said, "we must be in full combat readiness. . . . Everyone 
must understand this firmly and clearly, since we must be ready 
to perform the combat mission at any minute..." Later I found 
this portentous document in the Ministry of Defense Central 
Archives.[.sup]1[/] 
  During the War, in the circle of other officers we often 
discussed events of 22 June and said: "No! After everything we 
have gone through, this must not be repeated, the lesson is too 
cruel and instructive." And in fact if we take our military 
literature of today, it is a rare book in which you will not 
find the call to "strengthen combat readiness." But each appeal, 
even the most serious one, loses acuteness from frequent use. 
That often happens with us even now... But about this later. Now 
I would like to say that the tragic events of 1941 might not 
have happened had we been respectful toward military history, 
had we known it, had we not been deaf to its lessons. The fact 
is, the Russo-Japanese War (which, as we know, also began 
suddenly) was a great warning for us. History is a great, wise 
teacher. The past, even the very distant past, teaches a great 
deal. This is why I decided to begin my account about combat 
readiness with history. 
  Although the term "combat readiness" became current and 
began 
to be regarded as one of the principles of military art 
relatively recently, from time immemorial military leaders have 
observed its requirements and attempted to keep the Army in such 
a state that it was capable of going on the march and defeating 
or repelling the enemy. It was ancient Roman historian Onasander 
who wrote about this. In the work "Manual for Military Leaders" 
he recommended, in organizing the march, to keep the foe 
continuously in view even if he is far away, and during a day 
rest halt set up a reinforced camp, post a perimeter guard and 
reinforce it for the night.[.sup]2[/] Vegetius also wrote 
about the importance of soldiers constantly maintaining 
vigilance. In the book "A Brief Exposition of Military Affairs" 
he noted that, caught unawares, even the most tried and tested 
fighting men can be defeated.[.sup]3[/] 
  Thus, the question of ensuring troop combat readiness in one 
form or another ran through military treatises without fail 
already at the dawn of the origin of military art. Similar 
thoughts also occurred in early Old Russian military works. In 
undertaking a march, be careful, directed Vladimir Monomakh in 
his "Poucheniya" [Precepts], "detail the guard yourself . . . be 
in no haste to put down your weapon..." 
  During the third campaign and the taking of Kazan (1552), 
Ivan the Terrible gave great attention to stopping surprise 
enemy sallies and he concerned himself with organizing security 
and reconnaissance. Experience gained in combat expeditions was 
reflected in the "Ustav pogranichnoy (storozhevoy, stanichnoy i 
dozornoy) sluzhby" [Manual of Border (Sentry, Stanitsa and 
Patrol) Duty] published in 1571, and subsequently also in the 
first Russian Army manual published in 1621, the "Ustav ratnykh, 
pushechnykh i drugikh del, kasayushchikhsya do voyennoy nauki, 
sostoyashchikh v 663 ukazakh i statyakh" [Manual of Military, 
Gunnery and Other Affairs Concerning Military Science, 
Consisting of 663 Edicts and Articles]. It noted that the Army 
must prepare for war in advance. "At the present time it has 
become clear that war and hostility are not unexpected and soon 
will begin moving and will take place." Therefore it is 
necessary "to prepare to meet it so we are ready and armed 100 
days before a meeting engagement."[.sup]4[/] The manual gave 
recommendations on how to act "should there be an alert day or 
night, where which people should be and to where which people 
should ride or run, and who should do what."[.sup]5[/] 
  Combat operations took on a more decisive character with the 
appearance of firearms. This heightened demands for maintaining 
combat readiness. Certain new elements appeared in its content. 
More attention began to be given to supporting the troops with 
supplies and to upkeep of weapons and gear. 
  To Peter the Great belongs the astute thought that "one 
always must know the enemy" and what "he can do," "in order that 
in all matters he can be sought out and overturned." The "Ustav 
voinskiy" [Military Regulations] of Peter I noted: "Firmly 
reconnoiter the enemy," "establish security," and "assume battle 
order (combat formation) on time."[.sup]6[/] These precepts 
of Peter I came from life suffering itself. The Russian Army was 
taught a cruel lesson at the beginning of the Northern War 
(1700-1721). By that time Peter had not yet managed to establish 
a combat-effective army which could oppose a strong enemy--the 
Swedish Army headed by skillful field general Carl XII. The 
Swedes managed to rout the Russians in the Battle of Narva. But 
Peter managed to learn an instructive lesson from this 
defeat--he took to creating a regular army and outfitting and 
training it with even greater energy. In assessing these events, 
Marx wrote: "Narva was the first serious defeat for a rising 
nation whose resolute spirit learned to win even from 
defeats."[.sup]7[/] 
  Peter began increasing the Army's combat effectiveness 
beginning with the most important thing--establishing 
centralized command and control. A unified manpower acquisition 
system was established and standard arms and gear of the Army as 
well as a unified training system distinguished by simplicity 
and practicality were introduced. Peter demanded intelligent 
actions of the soldiers and that they learn "how to act in 
battle."[.sup]8[/] Ten years had not gone by since the battle 
of Narva when the Russian Army acquired the capability not only 
of battling the Swedes "as equals," but also of defeating them. 
  The regular army's rearming had been completed by the Battle 
of Poltava: The infantry received smoothbore shoulder arms with 
bayonets, smallswords, broadswords, and hand grenades; the 
dragoons received carbines, pistols and palache sabers; the 
artillery was divided into siege, fortress, field and 
regimental. Regiments' combat proficiency improved 
radically.[.sup]9[/] The brilliant victory at Poltava was the 
result. In revealing the enormous scale of Peter's military 
reforms, M. V. Lomonosov remarked that he was able "to recruit 
many great regiments--infantry and cavalry, supply all with 
clothing, salary, weapons and other military gear, teach them a 
new manual of arms, start up field and siege artillery according 
to the rules, for which a great deal of knowledge of geometry, 
mechanics and chemistry is required, and besides all else have 
commanders skilled in everything."[.sup]10[/] He made 
approving comments about establishment of a regular army and 
about Peter's decision to have regiments in readiness to protect 
the country against attack. 
  The fact that the most advanced form of troop 
training--exercises and maneuvers--began to be employed under 
Peter was of great importance for improving the Army's combat 
readiness. They were considered by him "as a precursor of 
things."[.sup]11[/] Exercises and maneuvers included field 
battles, assaults on fortified camps and fortresses, and so on. 
Such maneuvers take their origin from the Semenovskoye 
(1690-1693) and Kozhukhov (1694) campaigns.[.sup]12[/] 
  Traditions laid down by Peter with respect to maintaining 
Army combat readiness and demands not to lag behind the enemy in 
proficiency and aggressiveness, to anticipate his tactical ruses 
and to "set a trap" for the enemy himself were continued and 
developed by Russian military leaders P. S. Saltykov and P. A. 
Rumyantsev. In the Seven Years' War (1756-1763) the Russian Army 
surpassed the Prussian Army in the level of training and combat 
proficiency, as attested by its brilliant victories in the 
battle at Gross-Jagersdorf and Kunersdorf, in the taking 
of 
the Kohlberg Fortress and in the taking of Berlin. 
  The introduction to troop training practice of summer 
encampments for 1-3 months a year at Rumyantsev's suggestion 
following the Seven Years' War was of great importance for 
keeping the Russian Army in a state of appropriate combat 
readiness. Major exercises involving infantry, cavalry and 
artillery regiments were held during such summer encampments. 
  It was to A. V. Suvorov's credit with respect to upgrading 
Army combat readiness that he subordinated essentially the 
entire troop training system to attaining this goal. The field 
general invariably adhered to the motto: "Be as in war even in 
peacetime." He developed and practiced an effective system for 
training and educating soldiers based not on excessive drills 
and mechanical execution of commands, but on each soldier's 
understanding of his own maneuver. Suvorov instilled a feeling 
of patriotic pride, mutual assistance, courage and initiative in 
soldiers. Maneuvers (marches) conducted by Suvorov--Crimean, 
Tulchin and others--were distinguished by great instructiveness. 
  In studying combat training methods employed by Suvorov, the 
Frenchman Dubocage noted that there could be no chance 
happenings, no obstacles for his army. Such an army cannot help 
but win. Suvorov's methods were such that even "the last soldier 
who ended up in the sphere of his influence came to know combat 
matters better both practically and theoretically than is now 
known in any European army. . . . There was nothing unexpected 
in battle for his soldier, since he experienced the most 
difficult of combat impressions in peacetime. For him there 
could be nothing incomprehensible in what occurred in battle. . 
. . If a person is so seasoned that it is impossible to surprise 
him with anything and if he knows what he is doing in his modest 
sphere, he cannot be defeated, he cannot help but 
win."[.sup]13[/] 
  M. I. Kutuzov showed steadfast concern for keeping Russian 
Army combat readiness at the appropriate level. In battles he 
demanded that commanders organize and conduct effective 
reconnaissance "so as to uncover the French plans in time" and 
constantly know the status, combat effectiveness, state of 
supply, and state of morale of their army. A number of measures 
aimed at improving combat readiness were carried out in the 
Russian Army based on experience of the Patriotic War of 
1812-1814, but many innovations were of a dual nature. The 
"Stroyevoy ustav (rotnoye, batalonnoye i polkovoye ucheniya)" 
[Drill Regulations (Company, Battalion and Regimental 
Exercises)] published in the first quarter of the 19th century 
combined principles of new column tactics with linear tactics. 
Instructions and manuals developed directly in the troops were 
more progressive in nature. Among them, for example, were 
"Pravila rassypnogo stroya" [Rules of Extended Order] and 
"Nastavleniye g.g. pekhotnym ofitseram v den srazheniya 
[Instructions for Infantry Officers on the Day of 
Battle].[.sup]14[/] 
  But it often happened that the lively, creative thought of 
foremost military figures was suppressed by lack of talent and 
conventionalism. Slavery to routine, parade-ground drills and 
blind emulation of the Prussian military school prevailed in 
training methods despite combat experience. Any initiative of 
subordinates was suppressed and cane discipline was implanted. 
Basic attention in training was given to drill training. 
Maneuvers essentially reduced to tactical drill problems. All 
this had a pernicious effect on Russian Army combat 
effectiveness and delayed its development for a long time. The 
Russian Army also lagged behind European armies in technical 
outfitting. The defeat in the Crimean War (1853-1856) resulted 
from this.[.sup]15[/] The heroism of soldiers could not 
compensate for backwardness of military training and the 
"rottenness and impotence of a Russia based on 
serfdom."[.sup]16[/] 
  Russia's defeat in the Crimean War generated criticism of 
Nikolay's military system. Progressive figures called for a 
decisive revision of the existing military structure and this 
had an effect. The military reforms of 1864-1877 in Russia 
carried out under the direction of Military Minister D. A. 
Milyutin completed the process of converting a feudal army into 
a bourgeois type of army. The Army became a mass army with the 
introduction of universal military obligation in 1874. Field 
manuals--the "Ustav o polevoy sluzhbe" [Field Service 
Regulations] (1858, 1879, 1881)--were republished based on 
combat experience gained in the Crimean War and with 
consideration of the troops' new material base (rifled weapons 
had been adopted). They consolidated new forms and methods of 
fighting and methods of combat training. 
  I. V. Gurko and M. I. Dragomirov played a major role in 
reviving traditions of Peter and Suvorov in the Army. The basis 
of Dragomirov's views on questions of combat training was the 
assertion that the Army's principal strength lay in the 
individual and his preparedness for battle, since the readiness 
both of small subunits as well as of the Army as a whole depends 
on the training of every soldier. His "Uchebnik taktiki" 
[Textbook of Tactics] noted that the main goal of education is 
to instill in the soldier a sense of duty taken to 
self-sacrifice and to instill in him fearlessness, 
resourcefulness and mutual assistance. Speaking of training, he 
emphasized that it was necessary to teach the soldier to 
skillfully master weapons, adroitly overcome obstacles 
encountered on the terrain, and coordinate his movements with 
comrades' actions. 
  Beginning with the latter half of the 19th century annual 
district maneuvers, so-called "imperial" maneuvers, began to be 
held in the Russian Army in which a large number of troops took 
part (Kursk maneuvers of 1902). The importance of ensuring the 
Army's high combat readiness in wars of the machine period rose 
especially sharply, dictated by the intensive development of 
means of warfare and major changes in the nature and methods of 
combat operations--their increased scale and spatial scope and 
the increased role of the factor of surprise. The Russian Army 
combat readiness system was given a serious test during the 
Russo-Japanese War (1904-1905), where major miscalculations in 
command and control came to light. Underestimation of the enemy 
and "boasts of easy victory" had their effect. Because of poor 
intelligence the Russian command did not manage to promptly 
identify the moment of the Japanese attack. Poor logistic 
support had an especially negative effect on the Army's combat 
effectiveness. The troops constantly felt a most acute shortage 
of shells and cartridges. Russo-Japanese War experience played 
no small role in upgrading the combat readiness system. The war 
provided very abundant food for thought for military 
researchers. There were many Russian military theorists who 
wrote about the importance of profound comprehension of the 
lessons learned, but after the war no cardinal changes occurred 
in Russian Army training or its combat readiness system. The 
combat experience was far from completely reflected in field 
manuals and field service regulations republished in the period 
from 1906 through 1914. Many conditionalities and deviations 
from requirements of combat practice continued to be allowed in 
exercises, and stereotype and routine continued to predominate. 
Large maneuvers reduced basically to movements. Interworking and 
combat and logistic support were poorly rehearsed in them, and a 
contemptuous attitude was shown toward defense. 
  Nevertheless, many armies learned one important lesson with 
respect to troop combat readiness from Russo-Japanese War 
experience before the beginning of World War I. General staffs 
began to strive to increase the manning of formations and units, 
especially with command personnel, back in peacetime. The task 
was to ensure that border formations could enter battle without 
additional mobilization. As a result, prior to World War I the 
division personnel strength level was brought to the following 
indicators: Up to 100 percent officers, around 70 percent NCO's 
and up to 50 percent rank-and-file in the German Army; up to 
76.4 percent officers, 54.5 percent NCO's and 43.6 percent 
rank-and-file in the French Army; and up to 85 percent officers, 
42 percent NCO's and 48 percent rank-and-file in the Russian 
Army.[.sup]17[/] 
  Nevertheless, this was only a half-measure. Essentially all 
armies had many major shortcomings in the important thing, 
specifically in combat proficiency. Provisions of field manuals 
and field service regulations proved obsolete. They did not meet 
requirements of war. In the work "Voprosy sovremennoy strategii" 
[Questions of Modern Strategy] M. N. Tukhachevskiy wrote: "Not 
one army was guided by those military statutes and regulations 
with which it entered the war in 1914. Each year armies had to 
change their regulations and create new instructions, and they 
had to reteach both the different combat arms and the staffs 
these new instructions. Each year war plans also underwent 
modification."[.sup]18[/] 
  The battlefield employment of large masses of artillery and 
new weapons--choking gases, tanks, aircraft, flamethrowers and 
so on--predetermined the special importance of the "technical 
factor" in the combat readiness system--the personnel's 
knowledge of their own and enemy weapons and the ability to 
employ them in battle and fight new enemy weapons. It so 
happened that when a particular side used previously unknown 
kinds of weapons for the first time in battle, this usually 
generated a psychological shock in personnel or even led to the 
appearance of mass panic. As a result combat operations were 
paralyzed for a more or less lengthy time. 
  The Battle of Ypres (1915) was typical in this respect. 
Violating an international agreement, the Germans made a 
chemical attack on British troops. To support a breakthrough of 
the defense, they undertook a gas-cylinder attack in which 180 
tons of chlorine were used simultaneously from 6,000 cylinders 
set up across a 10 km front. Such an attack proved to be a total 
surprise for the British and their actions in this sector were 
halted. The battlefield ended up lifeless. The Germans advanced 
into the depth of the defense without a single 
shot.[.sup]19[/] And if this battle did not substantially 
affect the subsequent course of military events, it was only 
because the German command was unprepared to exploit results of 
the new weapon's employment. 
  It should be said that surprise employment of new weapons 
also occurred in subsequent operations of World War I. Revenge, 
as it were, by the British on the Germans followed soon after 
the Battle of Ypres. In the Battle on the River Somme (1916) 
they employed a very effective weapon, tanks. Although at that 
time tank combat performance characteristics were poor (they had 
a speed only of 3 km/hr), their appearance on the battlefield 
caused panic among the Germans. According to German soldier 
eyewitnesses, "everyone stood stricken as if having lost the 
capability of moving. The enormous monsters approached us 
slowly, clanking, limping and rocking, but all the time they 
advanced. Nothing held them up. Someone in the first line of 
trenches said that the devil had appeared, and this word spread 
through the trenches with enormous speed."[.sup]20[/] As a 
result the British achieved that success in a day of battle 
which they had been unable to achieve in 4-5 days since the 
operation began. 
  World War I experience greatly influenced further 
improvement 
of the armies' combat readiness system. It became obvious that 
troops had to be prepared purposefully for lengthy, strenuous 
combat operations long before the beginning of war. Not only did 
appropriate manning of formations and units with personnel have 
to be ensured, but their personal gear and equipment, good 
technical outfitting, armament, and combat cohesiveness had to 
be provided for and necessary stockpiles created in good time. 
Following World War I military theorists and practitioners in 
many armies drew an important conclusion: Maintaining armies at 
the proper level of combat readiness above all necessitated 
careful study of the initial period of war and preparation of 
troops for the first battles, in which they certainly would 
encounter many surprises. Many authors wrote that the beginning 
of war always is an enormous psychological shock for troops; 
therefore it is important to prepare personnel for overcoming 
difficulties and to master new tactics in advance. 
  A. I. Yegorov correctly foresaw the nature of the initial 
period of the future war. In 1933 he wrote: "Using methods of 
covert mobilization, the warring side will strive to assemble 
those forces and assets as early and as quickly as possible with 
whose help it is possible to invade enemy territory and disrupt 
mobilization in border areas and concentration of the army of 
one's enemy. . . . By operations from the air and the landing of 
assault parties, enemy aircraft can actively hamper the course 
of transport movements at a depth of 600-800 km (the 
Moscow-Kharkov meridian)..."[.sup]21[/] This was a truly 
prophetic warning which, however, was left without proper 
attention. M. N. Tukhachevskiy, B. M. Shaposhnikov, G. S. 
Isserson, A. M. Zayonchkovskiy, V. A. Melikov, S. N. 
Krasilnikov, Ye. A. Shilovskiy, M. R. Galaktionov and others 
made no small contribution to developing questions of the 
initial period of war. 
  Among Western European military theorists Friedrich von 
Bernhardi, von Moltke Jr., de Grandmaison and F. Foch paid great 
attention to researching the first operations of war. Thus, Foch 
wrote: "Surprise strategic deployments, swift marches and 
lightninglike offensives with which the first clashes of 
European wars break out like thunderclaps obligate armies to 
devote careful attention to their study."[.sup]22[/] 
  V. I. Lenin laid down the methodological foundations on 
whose 
basis the theory and practice of ensuring Red Army combat 
readiness developed. He constantly emphasized that "we must keep 
our Red Army in full combat readiness no matter what and 
reinforce its combat effectiveness."[.sup]23[/] "We will 
commit a terrible crime against the Revolution," he noted, "if 
we forget this."[.sup]24[/] Lenin's works and his directives 
on military questions during the Civil War gave paramount 
attention to such factors ensuring Army combat readiness as 
maintaining a high revolutionary vigilance in Red Army men, Red 
Navy men and commanders, knowledge of the enemy, Army and Navy 
technical outfitting, training of military cadres, creation of a 
unified command element for all Red Army detachments, raising 
the personnel's morale, and strengthening military discipline. 
Lenin warned that it was necessary to be always on guard. He 
wrote: "To let something slip by or to lose one's head means to 
lose everything."[.sup]25[/] 
  In the interwar period much was done in our Army to improve 
troop combat effectiveness. This was caused by the complication 
of the international situation and by military provocations 
repeatedly being undertaken by our enemies on the USSR's 
borders. Taking into account the growing threat of military 
attack, the Soviet government devoted constant attention to 
strengthening the Armed Forces' combat power, above all to their 
technical outfitting, and it must be said that much was 
achieved. The adoption in 1939 of the new Law on Universal 
Military Obligation, which established a unified system for Army 
and Navy manpower acquisition, was of great importance for 
improving Army combat readiness. Much attention was given to 
improving the combat and political training of troops. 
  Beginning in the 1930's it was the practice to hold major 
opposed-forces military maneuvers. Thus, maneuvers were held in 
the Ukrainian Military District in 1931, test exercises in the 
Volga area during 1932-1933, and large-scale maneuvers in the 
Kiev Special Military District in 1935 in which questions of the 
deep operation and battle were rehearsed. Airborne troops took 
part in them for the first time. In all, more than 1,000 tanks 
were in action here. Subsequently more than 1,300 tanks, 632 
aircraft, and 2,276 various vehicles took part in a Belorussian 
Military District exercise.[.sup]26[/] 
  Nevertheless, the combat readiness system of Red Army troops 
was far from perfect in prewar times. The very first relatively 
small-scale military conflicts indicated that combat proficiency 
of formations and units did not meet the demands of war. Thus, 
despite our troops' overwhelming numerical superiority during 
the battles at Lake Khasan and the participation of tanks and 
aircraft in them, losses proved unjustifiably high (408 killed 
and 2,807 wounded).[.sup]27[/] The Soviet-Finnish War taught 
us an especially severe lesson with respect to combat readiness 
and combat effectiveness of troops. It was planned to defeat the 
enemy in 2-3 weeks, but in fact this required three and one-half 
months. The result was 289,500 killed, wounded or frostbitten. 
Finland lost 23,000 killed and 43,000 wounded in this war, i.e., 
several times less.[.sup]28[/] 
  The Soviet military leadership drew many useful conclusions 
from the experience of this war--decisive steps were taken to 
improve troop field proficiency, technical outfitting, personal 
gear and equipment and armament. And vigorous actions by 
People's Commissar of Defense S. K. Timoshenko must be given 
their due. Nevertheless, the main task of teaching personnel to 
fight in a modern way failed to be fully accomplished in the 
prewar period. The reason for this was that ideas which existed 
at that time on the nature of combined arms battle were far from 
the reality which troops encountered at the very beginning of 
the Great Patriotic War. A high price had to be paid for the 
fact that methods of repelling a surprise enemy invasion had not 
been mastered in peacetime. 
  The Great Patriotic War began in a completely different 
operational-strategic situation than that being created in 
prewar exercises and maneuvers. Tactics employed by the Germans 
of psychological attacks, deep tank spearheads, creation of 
large and small "pockets," and a drop of airborne assault forces 
and sabotage teams in our rear proved unexpected for the troops. 
The terrible events of those years again and again give a 
reminder of the immutable truth that war punishes severely for 
peacetime blunders in questions of combat readiness. One of the 
major mistakes in the Red Army combat readiness system in prewar 
years was that personnel were oriented toward easy conditions, 
toward winning victory "with little blood, with a powerful 
blow," and toward conducting combat operations on enemy 
territory. The defense was underestimated and the withdrawal and 
combat in encirclement were not studied, but it was specifically 
with difficult defensive battles, with a withdrawal, and with 
combat in encirclement that our troops' combat operations began, 
for which they were not ready. 
  The imperfection of the combat readiness system was one of 
the main preconditions for defeat of many armies in local wars 
as well. Their lack of readiness to repel the enemy's first 
surprise attack told. The multistep system that was used for 
placing formations in a combat-ready status in a period of 
threat and with the beginning of military operations, lengthy 
collection of situation data, slow and usually manual processing 
of that data, sluggishness in decisionmaking, and giving units 
and weapons imprecise and often belated or even contradictory 
instructions led to where the aggressor succeeded in catching 
troops unawares, seizing the initiative, imposing his will and 
dictating his conditions. 
  Now it has become obvious that many armies do not manage to 
restructure their combat readiness system and troop training in 
accordance with demands of scientific-technical progress. The 
appearance of new weapons catches unawares those who are 
unconcerned with timely modernization not only of their means of 
warfare, but also of tactics. Here are just a few examples from 
the experience of local wars. 
  The Korean War (1950-1953) broke out just five years after 
World War II, but even in this short time interval substantial 
changes occurred in technical outfitting of the armies of 
developed states. For example, for the first time here the U.S. 
Army used jet aviation, guided robot bombs, a massive amount of 
napalm, certain new types of antitank and antipersonnel mines, 
and new parachutes and devices for dropping guns, light prime 
movers, mortars and other combat equipment to the 
ground.[.sup]29[/] The Americans used new weapons in the 
Vietnam War (1964-1975) on an even wider scale. Guided 
projectiles, bombs and missiles; a massive number of combat 
helicopters; fuel-air explosives; and means of meteorological 
and geophysical warfare were used here for the first time. 
  The battlefield appearance of new, more effective weapons 
lent impetus to the upgrading of field training and the system 
of troop combat readiness. Tactics of airmobile operations 
originated in the Vietnam War, which marked the beginning of 
development of the modern U.S. Army operational-tactical 
"air-land operation (battle)" concept. The experience of this 
war showed that an indispensable element of troop field 
proficiency should be their ability to fight enemy airmobile 
troops, tactical airborne assault forces and raiding and 
reconnaissance parties and take measures for protection against 
mass destruction weapons and precision weapons. 
  Military operations in the Near East (1967, 1973, 1982) and 
the Anglo-Argentine military conflict (1982) dictated further 
development of methods of troop combat operations, and 
particularly lent impetus to the development of tactics of the 
long-range firefight, which began to be characterized by the 
sides' attempt to conduct a firefight beginning from maximum 
ranges. Arab combat operations against the Israelis developed 
into opposition of artillery against artillery, ATGM's against 
tanks, and tanks against tanks. Under such conditions the 
personnel's high weapon handling skill, their ability to hit the 
target with the first round, launch or pass, and execution of a 
flexible maneuver of fire became determining in troop field 
training. 
  Thus, in order to continuously upgrade the troop combat 
readiness system it is necessary to constantly keep up with the 
development of military affairs, the appearance of new weapons 
and changes in the probable enemy's operating tactics. There is 
nothing more pernicious than acting in the old way. As the heart 
of troop combat readiness, development of their tactical 
proficiency must not fail to keep in step with technical 
innovations. 
<H3>  2. Problems Connected With Upgrading Troop Combat Readiness 
at the Present Stage </H3>
  Under present conditions the significance of the principle 
of 
troop combat readiness has grown as never before. It has become 
the epicenter of all research conducted in military art. 
Everything now being done in questions of improving the table of 
organization structure of formations and units, their technical 
outfitting, the command and control system, combat proficiency, 
combat, technical and logistic support, strengthening of the 
personnel's political attitude and morale, and discipline and 
orderliness--All this in the final account is aimed at preparing 
the troops for organized commitment to battle in case of war and 
at their ability to repel an enemy attack and defeat him. Just 
what problems are arising now in upgrading the combat readiness 
system and what are the ways of solving them? 
  Correct, profound foresight of the nature of a future war 
for 
which it is necessary to prepare is the very first precondition 
for successful accomplishment of tasks of improving troop combat 
readiness. Exclusive responsibility for this rests with military 
theory. It is what must develop and determine the right 
reference points in combat training: What and how should the 
troops be taught so they are ready for any ordeals, have good 
mastery of weapons and the tactics of modern battle, know the 
probable enemy and his strong and weak sides, and be able to 
combat the latest weapons and protect themselves against them? 
  Developing scenarios of future battles is one of the most 
difficult tasks of military art. History attests to the fact 
that military theorists and practitioners far from always 
managed to penetrate the veil of time and display profound 
insight with respect to developing advisable methods of combat 
operations. It often happened that an army was prepared 
essentially not for a future war, but for a past war and 
mastered antiquated, obsolete methods of combat operations. In 
other cases military theory overestimated or, conversely, 
underestimated the experience of small wars and drew incorrect, 
one-sided conclusions from it regarding combat readiness. The 
influence of new weapons on tactics was not always taken fully 
and comprehensively into account and biases were allowed in 
assessments of the enemy's actual combat capabilities and 
methods of his probable operations with the initiation and 
conduct of war. 
  In our time forecasting the conditions and nature of a 
future 
war has become unbelievably complicated above all because the 
upgrading and replacement of means of warfare and the troops' 
technical outfitting is occurring at unprecedentedly rapid 
rates, and this introduces radical changes to battle tactics. It 
is common knowledge that under present conditions 3-4 
generations of equipment change in the life of one human 
generation.[.sup]30[/] Based on this, as shown by the 
experience of local wars, the attacking side's massive 
introduction of the latest systems of weapons and combat 
equipment previously unknown to the enemy as well as the use of 
unexpected tactics have become characteristic of combat 
operations in first operations. 
  But the most important distinction is that there is the 
danger of employment of nuclear weapons as well as of diverse 
systems of precision weapons (reconnaissance-strike complexes, 
reconnaissance-fire complexes) which approximate nuclear 
weapons. Just the very fact of existence of these exceptionally 
effective kinds of weapons forces troops to be in constant 
readiness for operations when these weapons are employed and to 
take appropriate measures of protection. 
  Special demands on the troop combat readiness system at the 
present stage also stem from the circumstance that there has 
been a sharp increase in the significance of the factor of 
surprise, which largely predetermines not only the course and 
outcome of first operations, but also of the entire military 
campaign. The experience of local wars has shown clearly that 
its pernicious consequences became irreversible in those armies 
which did not take advance measures to prevent surprise. In this 
connection one important task of military theory is to 
comprehensively research and come up with recommendations on 
upgrading the combat readiness system so an aggressor cannot 
catch troops unawares and unprepared and so they can repel an 
enemy invasion in any (even the most difficult) situation, 
deliver a retaliatory attack against him and successfully 
execute assigned combat missions. 
  The combat readiness system cannot form abstractly, without 
consideration of specific conditions of the troops' entry into 
war. Research has shown that the first days of war and the first 
battles are the most difficult, critical moments for them. It is 
initial operations that are the touchstone on which the vitality 
of the prewar combat readiness system, the provisions of 
regulations developed in peacetime, the normative indicators of 
troop combat proficiency, the command and control system, the 
personnel's morale and fighting qualities, and so on are tested. 
  Hence the principal direction of peacetime combat training 
is 
to study conditions of operations of the initial period of war, 
which are characterized by special complexity and intensity; 
difficult predictability of development of combat events; 
abrupt, swift changes in the situation, in the troops' situation 
and status, and in the sides' force ratio; and the possibility 
of the unexpected appearance of critical situations, disruption 
of command and control, and disorganization of the work of the 
rear and lines of communication. 
  It is important to train personnel in good time so they have 
a clear picture of what they will encounter in actual battle and 
what kind of enemy they will come up against. They must be 
taught the ability to counter enemy tactics with their own more 
advanced tactics, employ a more skillful maneuver, and strive 
for a turning point in the situation and seizure of the 
initiative. For this it is necessary that every officer, NCO and 
private know his duties precisely and perform them without fuss 
in a combat alert so that in the terrible hour of ordeals 
equipment and weapons do not let him down and instruments, 
hardware and mechanisms operate faultlessly. 
  Battle sternly tests troops for combat maturity, ideological 
conditioning, staunchness, courage and bravery and punishes 
mercilessly for blunders. Readiness for military ordeals must be 
comprehensive. The modern soldier has to know and be capable of 
a great deal in order to successfully fight a strong, 
technically well outfitted enemy. He must surpass the enemy in 
tactical proficiency, psychological stability, the ability to 
handle weapons, and physical endurance. Special demands are 
placed on military proficiency and the organizing and volitional 
qualities of officers, their ability to flexibly lead troops, 
thoroughly foresee, quickly grasp and put into practice new 
methods of operations, clear the way for subordinates' creative 
undertakings and encourage their initiative. 
  The state of combat readiness is very dynamic. There can be 
no indifference, negligence or self-complacency in such a major, 
important matter. Normative indicators of combat proficiency are 
growing and becoming more complicated all the time. They are 
different today than they were yesterday, and tomorrow they 
inevitably will be different than today. Therefore the 
responsibility for the state of combat readiness is constantly 
increasing. 
  Let us pose the question: Are we doing everything in the 
Army 
now as demanded by conditions of modern war from the standpoint 
of adjusting the effectiveness of combat training so that it is 
possible to say with all confidence that the mistakes of 1941 
will not be repeated? Judging from external manifestations, the 
call to strengthen combat readiness and to teach what is 
necessary in war is not leaving the pages of the military press 
and is constantly and persistently being repeated here, there 
and everywhere. 
  But deep-seated processes also indicate something else: 
Concern is growing among the officers for the state of affairs 
in troop combat readiness. People are arguing in a concerned 
way, thinking, and seeking an answer to questions which life 
poses for them. Among the problems relating to troop combat 
proficiency, greatest attention is drawn by the following: Why 
have our tactics, which absorbed the rich experience of the 
past, which stood up under a severe test on the battlefields, 
and which proved their indisputable superiority over tactics of 
leading world armies in years of the Civil War and Great 
Patriotic War, lately begun to fall behind the demands of life, 
thus having a negative effect on troop combat readiness? Why 
have stereotype and conservatism penetrated deeply into combat 
training? Why have formalism and conventionalism with their 
inherent maximum programmed nature of problems and exercises, 
the authoritarian assessments and judgements in scientific 
research, and the abstract schemes and hard-and-fast postulates 
been implanted for a long time instead of bold, innovative 
searches? 
  Pertinent, vital, painful questions are posed. Without 
having 
answered them, without having delved into the reasons which 
dictated the dominant influence in the troop training system of 
dogmatic blinders which shackle officers' creative thinking and 
retard the perestroyka process, it is impossible to accomplish 
the cardinal task of achieving a radical turning point in 
improving troop combat training. 
  It should be said that negative phenomena in combat training 
have been accumulating for us for years and even decades; as a 
result not one, but a multitude of different objective and 
subjective reasons have been concentrated which predetermined 
the stagnation in troop training and education. Above all we 
will note that the very difficult process of developing military 
affairs cannot be understood and explained correctly if it is 
considered by itself, outside of contact with the life of 
society. Military organizational development always has been and 
is now under the determining influence of a system of 
sociopolitical and socioeconomic factors and acts as a unique 
reflection of their development level. The ailments of society 
in years of stagnation could not help but affect the state of 
the Armed Forces. This was manifested in particular in the fact 
that a firm belief was implanted in people's social awareness, 
including among servicemen, that our advance on all fronts was 
going according to "laws of accelerated development." This 
inspired confidence that we were steadily on the ascent and the 
thought did not arise about the possibility of any kind of lag. 
  The thesis that "advantages of the system of socialism also 
ensure advantages of its military organization"[.sup]31[/] 
was interpreted straightforwardly. In being guided by this 
thesis, the attention of military cadres was not always directed 
to the fact that the social system in itself merely creates 
objective preconditions for successful accomplishment of tasks 
and that it can in no way insure the Army against mistakes and 
lag. In this connection it is impossible not to reproach our 
military philosophers, whose sacred duty is to arm officers with 
correct methodological lines conforming to the spirit of the 
time and to act as pace-setters in an uncompromising struggle 
against manifestations of inertness, cliches, and routine in 
military affairs. Unfortunately, our military-philosophical 
thought did not withstand the "euphoria of general successes" in 
the stagnant times and did not perceive in due course the growth 
of crisis phenomena in combat training during the 1960's and 
1970's. 
  It is necessary to speak about this now because without the 
involvement of social sciences, without activation of the 
ideological-theoretical activity of military scientists, 
philosophers, sociologists, psychologists and economists, and 
without appropriate scientific and philosophical comprehension 
of the processes occurring in the Army, it is impossible to 
achieve a fundamental perestroyka of military science in 
accordance with new political thinking, a qualitative turning 
point in improvement of troop combat training, and the revival 
of tactics as a genuine art of conducting modern battle. But 
this by no means relieves the combined arms generals and 
officers of responsibility for the state of affairs in the 
troops. 
  The deep roots of the lag in the system of troop training 
and 
education must be sought first and foremost in routine tactical 
thinking, in administrative-pressure methods and voluntaristic 
methods of directing combat training, and in the dominant 
influence of ostentation, subjectivism and parochialism in the 
awareness of a certain portion of military cadres. 
  Speaking of reasons for a temporary suspension in questions 
of tactics, some authors are inclined to believe that this 
occurred to a certain extent through the fault of certain 
military leaders who came to prominence during the Great 
Patriotic War. These authors assume that their opinion, based on 
victorious combat experience, in the final account turned into a 
kind of pattern, into a stereotype.[.sup]32[/] Without a 
doubt, thoughtless fetishism of front experience and 
mechanically following it under new, altered conditions could 
not help but negatively affect the development of tactics, of 
military art as a whole, and the troop training system. But it 
would appear that one of the main reasons for the penetration of 
dogmatism and stagnation into combat training nevertheless lies 
in something else, in the fact that the very abundant combat 
experience of Soviet troops, won at a dear cost in fierce 
battles, in its time ceased to be analyzed from contemporary 
positions, largely remained unused, "did not work" in a genuine 
way to form officers' creative thinking, and did not contribute 
to the development of new operational-tactical concepts. 
  It is necessary to return to the first postwar years to find 
the roots of such a superficial attitude toward Soviet troops' 
combat experience. Immediately following the end of the Great 
Patriotic War an aureole of "infallibility" of Soviet tactics 
began to be created in the era of Stalin's cult of personality. 
This in itself precluded any kind of criticism of mistakes and 
failures, which of course occurred in combat readiness of 
formations and units in prewar time and which had a negative 
effect on the course of troop combat operations with the 
beginning of war. It was essentially completely forgotten that 
our Army, "armed" with obsolete tactics, entered into opposition 
with a very strong and very experienced fascist German Army and 
it essentially had to learn to fight anew in the flame of 
battles. 
  Common sense suggested that our Army's failures in 1941 
should not have passed without leaving a trace for subsequent 
improvement of the troop combat readiness system. Without 
belittling the greatness of the Soviet Army, which despite 
everything managed to wrest victory from the hands of a powerful 
enemy, it was insistently necessary to soberly and impartially 
understand how and why failures were allowed in troop combat 
training on the eve of war, which dictated the enormous losses 
with the beginning of war and loss of strategic initiative. But 
the ancient wisdom that says whoever does not learn from past 
mistakes inevitably is forced to repeat them clearly did no 
good. Strictly speaking, that is just what happened with us 
after the war. Certain prewar concepts which had not proven 
themselves again prevailed. This concerned above all the 
assessment of the role and place of defense in tactical 
training. For a long time it simply was ignored and the most 
difficult mobile forms of defensive operations, the withdrawal, 
battle in encirclement, and repulse of the first and most crafty 
attack of the enemy with the beginning of war were not rehearsed. 
  And combat experience itself sometimes was received in a 
hypertrophied form and instead of benefit sometimes did a 
certain amount of harm to troop field training. Thus, the 
popularization in military history textbooks primarily of 
winning tactical episodes in which Soviet units achieved success 
led in the final account to where a superficial impression about 
battle formed in young officers and the opinion began to 
predominate that it seemingly could be won without particular 
effort and without thorough training. The archaic, stereotyped 
methodology of conducting tactical exercises (especially field 
fire exercises) and thoroughly staged procedures of playing out 
combat episodes, where the sides' actions were assigned and 
rehearsed in advance, contributed to this to no small extent. 
  The striving to present one's activity in a "rosy light" led 
to the predominance of "ostentatious" tactics, where no place 
remained for a display of creative quests either on the part of 
training instructors or on the part of trainees. For example, 
the conduct of a "march" offensive of troops with truly 
hyperbolic rates of advance (80-100 km or more per day) and 
nonstop negotiation of defensive lines and water obstacles (even 
when massive destruction, abatis, inundations, fires, and zones 
of radioactive and chemical contamination were created), which 
took root in the troops during the 1960's and 1970's, 
unquestionably contradicted front experience. 
  At one time G. K. Zhukov cautioned that without the most 
thorough, scrupulous training it was impossible to achieve 
success in an operation or battle.[.sup]33[/] Behind these 
words of the prominent military leader stand the very abundant 
experience of four years of war and hundreds of the most 
difficult battles, defeats and victories. But despite this, in 
tactical problems it became the rule to conduct ground 
reconnaissance hastily, often according to the same type of 
scheme, and to rehearse delivery of fire, interworking, and 
command and control hurriedly, even without having genuinely 
clarified the enemy's fire plan. Often questions of combat, 
technical and logistic support were omitted, seemingly as 
"unimportant." Engineer preparation of terrain was not conducted 
to the full extent. Political work was carried out formally. Of 
course, it would be unjust to reflect the development of tactics 
and the combat training in postwar time only from a negative 
side. Even in stagnant times tactics did not stand still. The 
troops had many highly active, creative generals and officers 
who worked long and selflessly, boldly broke settled canons, 
conducted problems and exercises in an interesting, instructive 
way, fought stereotype and conventionalism, and enriched 
military theory with new provisions. 
  Tactics received a sharp leap in its development with the 
arrival of nuclear missile weapons in the troops. Under 
conditions of genuinely revolutionary changes it was required to 
take a fundamentally new approach to developing forms and 
methods of combat operations, and Soviet military theory 
successfully coped with development of "nuclear tactics." 
Nevertheless, the "renewal boom" largely remained incomplete and 
indeterminate. Things also did not get by without certain costs. 
Under the influence of nuclear weapons, attention toward tactics 
was relaxed, especially toward developing methods of combat 
operations in the course of a conventional war. This also 
retarded its development. And what was important was that the 
era of rapid renewal of the means of warfare did not introduce a 
radical turning point to the psychology of officers' tactical 
thinking--the old tactical yardsticks largely were retained. 
Ground-air, "electronic" battle even with use of nuclear weapons 
was viewed largely in the light of experience of past wars. The 
stereotyped approaches which dominated for many years did not 
disappear into the past. The category of positional 
confrontation, linear forms of warfare, methodism and the 
measured nature of development of battle by no means became 
"museum-piece" procedures of tactics. All of them are in effect 
even to this day in a somewhat modernized form. This emphasizes 
once again that a conservative psychology in military affairs is 
extremely tenacious. 
  Even with the use of nuclear weapons relapses of obsolete 
methodology remained in the process of combat 
training--implantation of the cult of "normative tactics" 
continued. Personnel training took place in the channel of 
monotonous tactical orientation. Regulation, over-organization, 
and fear of deviating from the regulations continued to suppress 
living, innovative thought. Original decisions by trainees, use 
of procedures of stratagem, and misleading the enemy regarding 
one's true intentions were a great rarity. Stagnation had its 
effect even in times of scientific-technical progress. 
Creativeness in tactics did not prevail over banality, daring 
risk over passive caution, or innovation over slavery to routine. 
  Negative processes in combat training without question could 
not have grown to a critical point had democratic traditions not 
been lost at one time in the Soviet military press. It was the 
broad exchange of opinion of command and political personnel in 
pages of the journals VOYNA I REVOLYUTSIYA, VOYENNAYA MYSL, 
MEKHANIZATSIYA I MOTORIZATSIYA RKKA and VOYENNYY VESTNIK and in 
the newspaper KRASNAYA ZVEZDA and discussions held regularly in 
the 1920's that largely contributed to a proper orientation of 
military cadres and their development of views on such 
fundamental questions of military organizational development as 
the development of fundamentals of military doctrine and a 
determination of ways of accomplishing military reform and 
improving combat readiness of the Army and directions of 
development of strategy, operational art and tactics. It was not 
by chance that Soviet military art made a sharp spurt in its 
development specifically in those years. Evidence of this was, 
for example, development of the theory of deep battle and 
operation. But the subsequent banishment of lively discussion 
and creative thinking and the actual removal of the broad Army 
public from polemic discussion of military problems in the pages 
of the press dealt an especially heavy blow to tactics, which 
well-known Soviet military leader A. I. Yegorov aptly called 
"all-Army creative work." 
  Experience showed that tactical thought is bold and sharp 
and 
is in full swing when nourished by the life-giving juices of 
troop practice and filled daily and hourly with new ideas coming 
from the troops, from the lower strata. It inevitably withers if 
it loses vital contact with its creative aktiv, officers of the 
tactical echelon. But despite this well-known thesis, at one 
time primary attention in upgrading tactics was focused on 
directive instructions. Of course, theoretical and practical 
science conferences were held in the troops and in higher 
military educational institutions, but even here a biased nature 
and intolerance for "different thinking" were manifested. They 
were held basically to substantiate provisions of regulating 
documents and the statements of authorities. A pluralism of 
opinions usually was blocked even in the press, and if bold, 
out-of-the-ordinary thoughts were expressed, as a rule they were 
not heeded. The fact that during the last four and one-half 
decades not one broad discussion of problems of tactics has been 
held in pages of the press eloquently attests to the damping of 
creative searches. 
  It stands to reason that one cannot help but take into 
account the specifics of military service. In military affairs 
it is extremely important to have unified views, unified 
approaches and norms for fundamental issues. Herein lies the 
great importance of doctrinal lines and the consideration of 
demands and principles of military art developed by 
centuries-old practice. Herein is manifested the organizing, 
disciplining role of regulations, manuals, instructions, orders 
and directives. But excessive centralization and the attempt to 
establish full "like-mindedness" in tactics are just as harmful 
as lack of a system. If everything is decided by direction from 
above, then the "lower strata" are left with nothing else other 
than to await instructions of higher commanders. There where the 
practice of awaiting "innovation with the stamp of approval of 
higher-ups" has been established, officers inevitably form a 
contemplative psychology, creative activeness dies out, and 
tactics, which is the bearer of everything foremost and new, in 
the final account turns into a preserve of inertness and lack of 
initiative. 
  Stagnation in tactics also was facilitated to no small 
extent 
by the fact that for a long time it "took a back seat" in our 
leading journals and military-theoretical and 
military-historical works. A gap was created between strategy, 
operational art and tactics, and this could not help but tell on 
development of military theory and practice and on the general 
state of troop combat readiness. There are numerous examples of 
this. For example, the rubric "Formation Tactics" appeared in 
VOYENNAYA MYSL only in the early 1980's. Before this evidently 
it was believed that tactical questions were too "petty" to be 
considered in a military-theoretical journal. In this connection 
I foresee the objection that there is a special journal, 
VOYENNYY VESTNIK, which is tactical in purpose, for this. Yes, 
this is so, but one only has to look carefully at the subject 
matter of articles in this journal and it becomes clear that its 
writings are strictly of an applied nature and are designed 
chiefly for the lower tactical echelon--platoon, company and 
battalion commanders. Other journals and newspapers also rarely 
come out with problem-oriented tactical articles, but the fact 
is that they could influence formation of new tactical thinking 
in officers and "agitate" thought more actively with 
"provocative" polemical writings. 
  Extremely few books on tactics are being published. Never 
before in the entire history of our Army has the officer's 
library been so bare as now. The first military-theoretical 
work, "Taktika" [Tactics], appeared only after 20 years had 
passed since the end of the Great Patriotic War (1966) and had a 
very limited printing. Only a total of three editions of this 
book came out in postwar times.[.sup]34[/] 
  We will note that too few constructive ideas and innovative 
thoughts are advanced in published works on tactics. Theory of 
tactics does not always act as a driving oscillator of 
perestroyka processes. The era of the cult of personality and 
stagnation implanted "normative" thinking in many officers and 
led to depreciation of theory. Many textbooks were written as if 
"using carbon-paper," in a formal style. Provisions of 
regulations are retold in them according to the same type of 
scheme. Often they do not discuss any kind of genuine tactical 
art. 
  Dogmatic restrictions, fear of going beyond the bounds of 
customary ideas, banality instead of originality, tedious 
rehashing of common truths, and calloused thoughts--those are 
the main things that dictated the creative sterility in military 
theory and the deafness to innovation. This difficult heritage 
of stagnation will drag military affairs backward like a heavy 
weight for a long time yet if a resolute struggle is not put up 
against it. 
  The insufficiently high level of scientific achievements in 
tactics largely is determined by an absence of fundamental 
military-theoretical research in prospective problems of combat 
readiness. Primacy was given to current, strictly applied, 
"momentary" interests. No works appeared here in postwar years 
that were equal in theoretical depth, boldness and scale of 
posing questions to such works as "Novoye v razvitii taktiki 
Krasnoy Armii" [New Things in Development of Red Army Tactics] 
by M. N. Tukhachevskiy, "Mozg armii" [Brain of the Army] by B. 
M. Shaposhnikov, "Kharakter operatsiy sovremennykh armiy" 
[Nature of Operations of Modern Armies] by V. K. Triandafillov, 
"Obshchaya taktika" [General Tactics] and "Ogon, manevr, 
maskirovka" [Fire, Maneuver and Maskirovka (lit. "camouflage", 
however, includes "concealment" and "deception" -- FBIS)] by A. 
I. Verkhovskiy, and others. But the fact is, these works 
appeared just 5-10 years after the birth of the Red Army. 
  The circumstance that we practically ceased to publish 
military-theoretical works of foreign authors beginning in the 
1960's did much damage to development of the theory of tactics. 
New works that appear on the whole remain unnoticed in journals 
and newspapers, and annotations and reviews are not even 
provided on them. But despite extremely limited capabilities in 
prewar years, there were many publications of foreign military 
literature. These were works by Machiavelli, Napoleon, von 
Clausewitz, Jomini, Delbruck, Foch, Kuhlmann, 
Fuller, 
Langlois and others. 
  It follows from the above that at the present stage in 
theory 
and practice of military art and in questions of troop combat 
readiness a need arises to rethink and reassess a great deal in 
light of the increased demands of the time and changes in the 
material base of warfare. Not simply "cosmetic cleansing" is 
needed, but fundamental perestroyka for many positions and a 
search for new approaches and fundamentally new solutions. It 
would appear that above all it is important to sharply elevate 
the social status of military theory and genuinely (not in 
words, but in fact) give full play to innovative scientific 
thought. It is perverse and inadmissible to set theory and 
practice in opposition and to calculate in percentages how much 
there should be of theoretical classes and how much of 
practical, let alone in higher military educational 
institutions. Theory must "be present" in literally every class. 
It is impossible to resolve any practical question without this 
"searchlight of scientific thought." 
  In an impetuous time of scientific-technical progress it is 
pernicious to reduce the role of theory only to registering 
events and interpreting provisions of regulations. Military 
affairs mean dynamism, constant uniqueness, destruction of 
stereotypes and established postulates, a continuous search and 
confirmation of new things, and the bold rush of thought into 
the future. Even the most radical changes in the 
material-technical base of battle cannot automatically, of 
themselves, lead to the appearance of new forms and methods of 
combat operations, to the establishment of new tactical 
thinking. The greatest importance in this belongs to a theory 
unswaddled by any lines, free of a biased approach and of 
pressure from above. Under present conditions it must develop a 
scientific concept of perestroyka in the troop combat readiness 
system. Without theoretical study, all practical conditions in 
upgrading the system will be done blindly, by guesswork. 
  A need has matured to infuse a new spirit into tactical 
training methodology, especially in higher military educational 
institutions. It is advisable to teach officers not tactics, but 
the art of tactics, to teach them not decisionmaking 
for battle, but the art of making such a decision, 
and so on. The fundamental difference is that with the new 
methodology the principal goal of training is not to learn the 
work scheme of a commander and staff officer in a combat 
situation, but teach them to creatively analyze, compare, 
foresee the development of combat events, find ways out of 
difficult situations, display aggressiveness, employ procedures 
of deception and stratagem, and strive for victory by means of 
skill. In this connection there is increased importance of 
problem-exploration methods of holding classes and giving 
lectures, of use of mathematical models of the engagement or 
battle, of "atypical games," of problem solving by the 
"brainstorming" method and so on. 
  Military-historical science plays an important role in 
upgrading the combat readiness system. It must "work" more for 
the present. The time has come for military historians to shift 
to a new, higher stage of scientific disclosure of the very 
abundant Great Patriotic War experience, to a detailed 
comparison of belligerents' plans with the involvement of new 
archive sources, to a profound comprehension of events, to a 
demonstration of what kind of troop losses resulted from 
miscalculations and insufficiently considered decisions, and to 
an analysis of how many commanders and staffs managed to win 
victory over superior enemy forces thanks to tactical 
proficiency. A quality research work on the development of 
military art in local wars, and above all on experience of 
combat operations in Afghanistan, is very necessary. It is 
important to deeply comprehend the combat experience gained in 
this war and learn instructive lessons from it, especially in 
fighting in the mountains and improving reconnaissance, physical 
and psychological training of personnel. 
  It should be noted that the work of analyzing and using 
combat training experience in order to upgrade combat readiness 
still is unsatisfactory. Each year a large number of various 
exercises are held in the troops, but their results are not 
properly generalized and, most important, are not communicated 
to the troops and higher military educational institutions. A 
strange practice has formed: While it is the practice to have an 
analytical survey of the experience of operational-tactical 
training of armies of the United States and NATO in pages of 
central military journals, our own combat training experience 
goes ignored. It is not accessible to the broad Army public. It 
turns out that such truly invaluable scientific capital--on 
which, by the way, no small amounts are spent--does not produce 
a proper practical return for improving combat training and 
combat readiness, often disappears in the archives without a 
trace and does not receive new life in textbooks and training 
manuals. But the fact is, this is first-rate "building material" 
for combat improvement of troops and for military theory. 
  In the final account the job of radically improving combat 
readiness never will budge decisively until the entire broad 
Army public joins in a discussion of pressing problems in pages 
of the press and wages a resolute struggle against obduracy, 
slavery to routine and stagnant phenomena. The revival of 
democratic traditions in the press and broad discussion are the 
main line that will help get to new milestones faster in 
training troops and in military organizational development as a 
whole. Only in the light of polemics, by collective reason, is 
it possible to develop faster and better the correct line for 
forward movement and avoid a repetition of mistakes. We have 
more than enough bright, talented officers who are bold in 
opinions and actions. It is important only to arouse their 
creative activeness in the right way and resolutely cast off the 
fetters of irrational limitations and dogmatism. The most 
dangerous enemy in military affairs is stereotype. Until it is 
gotten rid of, one need not speak of any kind of perestroyka. 
  One of the important tasks in upgrading combat readiness is 
increasing the personnel's morale and fighting qualities. Never 
in the past has the factor of morale played such a determining 
role in accomplishing missions facing the troops as at the 
present stage. Commanders and all officers of command and 
control entities should spare no efforts to tirelessly form in 
soldiers a high ideological conviction and devotion to the 
Motherland, persistently instil in them moral qualities, 
internationalism and comradely mutual help, and develop a 
striving for tireless combat improvement, staunchness of spirit, 
selflessness, heroism and the ability to overcome difficulties 
of life in the field. It is important to remember that entry 
into a mortal clash with the enemy and the transition from 
peacetime to combat life is an enormous test of 
moral-psychological qualities. A soldier can learn weapons well 
and learn to use them skillfully, but if he has no inner 
readiness for actions, appropriate ideological conditioning, and 
emotional and volitional stability and is not constantly 
mobilized for fighting, he may not hold up, may waver in a 
minute of a very difficult combat ordeal and thereby endanger 
himself, his comrades in arms and his subunit. Today as never 
before it is necessary for the concepts of a "knowledgeable," 
"skilled" soldier to merge as one with the concepts of "brave" 
and "courageous." 
  To this end, in days of peacetime combat training, in the 
course of problems, drills and exercises, it is necessary to use 
all opportunities to temper a soldier's will and develop in him 
the character of a fearless warrior, self-control, and readiness 
to perform the assigned mission at any cost right up to 
self-sacrifice. Great experience has been accumulated in the 
troops in this matter and it must be used, enriched and 
developed in every way. The tested way of psychological 
conditioning is to move into the assault following the bursts of 
friendly artillery and mortar rounds and bombs, be rolled over 
by tanks, operate tanks underwater, throw live grenades, 
negotiate live-fire assault courses and so on. 
  Problems containing elements of danger and risk permissible 
in peacetime and strictly controlled by the commander prepare 
the personnel for real conditions of war, reinforce their 
professional expertise and increase combat effectiveness. 
  One of the most responsible sectors of work to improve 
combat 
readiness is comprehensive strengthening of discipline and 
efficiency and the establishment everywhere in subunits of 
strict regulation order and the personnel's compliance with 
demands of the military oath, regulations and the commander's 
orders. An old truth goes that without discipline there is no 
combat effectiveness and combat readiness, and there is no army. 
Now, when weapons and the character of battle have become 
immeasurably more complicated and when conditions for performing 
combat missions have become more difficult, the role of 
discipline as a very important factor has grown by many times. 
Lack of discipline even of one soldier, the sluggish, imprecise 
execution of one's duties and of commanders' orders and 
instructions, and a deviation from provisions of regulations in 
battle can lead to serious consequences right up to nonexecution 
of the combat mission by the entire subunit. In days of 
peacetime combat training and day-to-day service the personnel 
must be brought up in a spirit of faultless execution and 
implicit obedience. Any violations of regulation order and 
discipline, indulgences on the part of commanders, and absence 
of proper exactingness toward subordinates are impermissible. 
  Today we clearly realize that there are many difficult 
questions and unresolved problems in matters of upgrading combat 
readiness, but necessary premises for real changes already are 
being created. 
<H5>  Conclusions and Recommendations </H5>
  1. This work considers the importance of the principle of 
combat readiness from two aspects: Theoretical and practical. 
From the standpoint of theory this work shows how the content of 
the "combat readiness" concept "evolved" under the influence of 
development of means of warfare, changes in views on the nature 
of war, the operation and battle, and methods of their conduct. 
The conclusion should be drawn on a practical plane that demands 
of the principle are strictly immutable: It is necessary for 
troops always to be on guard and fully armed to repel 
aggression. War does not forgive blunders and indulgences in 
combat readiness. Here there are none of those trivial matters 
and secondary details which could be ignored; here everything is 
important and everything must be taken into account. 
  2. Demands on combat readiness have increased immeasurably 
under present conditions. There should be no place for 
seasonality in it. Combat readiness must be maintained at a 
proper level at any time of year and day. The factor of time 
plays a deciding role in it. Nothing can make up for the loss of 
time. It can result in loss of people and the initiative. Time 
periods for taking steps to transfer units and subunits to 
higher conditions of combat readiness now are figured not in 
weeks and not even days, but in hours and minutes. 
  3. High combat readiness of troops is forged gradually and 
imperceptibly, day in and day out, by the strenuous labor of all 
personnel. Military theory develops the reference points in its 
improvement, the ideology, the direction of combat training, the 
improvement in the command and control system and the other 
components making it up. 
  4. Measures for maintaining combat readiness of units and 
subunits in peacetime should be conducted purposefully based on 
conditions of the initial period of war as applied to that 
theater of military operations where they are stationed. All 
personnel, right down to every soldier, should know precisely 
what mission is to be executed and how it is to be executed in 
case a military threat builds up or with the beginning of combat 
operations. They should learn the probable enemy's weapons and 
tactics thoroughly, know his strong and weak sides, and in a 
critical situation of aggression which has begun be capable of 
wresting the initiative of actions from the enemy's hands and 
imposing one's own will on him. Only those troops will be able 
to fight in a modern way and repel the attack of a strong enemy 
who master all forms and methods of warfare to perfection in 
peacetime, learn to use the attack, maneuver and protective 
qualities of weapons and combat equipment with maximum 
effectiveness, prove capable of accomplishing missions arising 
suddenly in battle, and can if necessary quickly restructure 
their tactics, develop effective methods of combating previously 
unknown enemy weapons, actively counter his new tactics and 
impose their own will on him. 
  5. It is important to remember that strengthening combat 
readiness is work both of today and for the future. It is 
necessary to take into account not only what the probable enemy 
has now, but also what weapons he will have tomorrow and how his 
battle tactics and conditions of the military situation in 
general can change. Therefore it is necessary to upgrade combat 
readiness with an eye to the long term and with profound 
foresight, it is necessary to resolutely cast aside everything 
that is obsolete and boldly seek out and introduce to practice 
everything new and progressive. Sober realism, precise 
understanding of new problems, boldness backed up by strict 
calculation, rejection of formed stereotypes of thinking, and 
the most profound conviction as to the exceptional significance 
of this very important task are what should permeate the 
activity of military cadres in further comprehensive improvement 
of troop combat readiness. 
  6. The center of gravity in work of strengthening combat 
readiness should be shifted to practical work directly in 
battalions and companies. Organizing execution and implementing 
the orders and directives of senior commanders, one's own 
decisions, and combat readiness plans are the important thing in 
officer cadres' work to improve combat readiness. This requires 
precise assignment of missions, considered disposition of 
people, their purposeful training and principled exactingness. 
Upgrading organizational work to increase combat readiness 
presumes the ability of command personnel to identify the 
important thing, correctly distribute the time budget and 
resources, mobilize people and organize effective control. 
  7. One of the responsible tasks which rests with commanders 
for ensuring subunit combat readiness is their ability to 
organize proper upkeep and maintenance of weapons and combat 
equipment and to ensure their constant readiness for immediate 
use. Every serviceman must know his weapon well, comply with 
rules for maintaining it under field conditions, and promptly 
identify and remedy malfunctions. 
  8. A flexible command and control system is an important 
component element of combat readiness. Effective use of the 
combat capabilities of units and subunits with the beginning of 
war and in its course depends largely on mobility in leading 
them. The demand of the time is such that combat readiness of 
command and control entities in peace and wartime should be one 
step higher than combat readiness of subordinate troops. 
  9. The field is the genuine academy of troop combat 
proficiency. Only in field problems, in a difficult situation, 
is military proficiency forged, combat maturity of commanders 
and staff officers achieved, their will tempered, command and 
control skills improved, and necessary combat and 
moral-psychological qualities and the ability to staunchly 
endure the hardships of life in the field acquired. A subunit 
whose officers and all personnel are unable to live in the field 
as in combat and who are not trained to quickly arrange housing 
and rest for themselves, prepare food, strictly comply with 
rules of personal hygiene, and constantly preserve cheerfulness, 
endurance, and readiness to enter battle at any moment cannot be 
deemed combat ready. 
