<H3>  CHAPTER THREE - DECISIVENESS, AGGRESSIVENESS AND CONTINUITY 
OF CONDUCTING THE BATTLE </H3>
[.sup]1[/] 
  Decisiveness, aggressiveness and continuity of 
conducting the battle consist of a constant striving to defeat 
the enemy, the delivery of powerful blows to him, imposition of 
one's will, disruption of his plans, creation of unfavorable 
conditions for him, and daring, bold, vigorous actions conducted 
persistently and stubbornly day and night in any weather. 
  "Boyevoy ustav Sukhoputnykh voysk" [Ground 
Troops Field Manual], Part II 
  My motto is to seek out and hit. 
  P. I. Bagration 
  The fact that the initiative has been seized in 
itself "proves superiority either in quantity or quality of 
troops or in the art of field generalship, and maintains the 
soldiers' morale in all failures and retreats..." 
  F. Engels 
<H3>  1. From the History of the Origin and Development of the 
Principle of Decisiveness and Aggressiveness </H3>
  If we trace the activity of great field generals beginning 
from ancient times up to the present, then despite the specific 
nature of each one's manifestation of military art, nevertheless 
it also appears possible to single out a certain trait of their 
activity common and similar to all. It consists of the ability 
to act resolutely, forcefully and aggressively in the engagement 
and battle. 
  Sun Tzu called decisiveness the supreme art of waging war. 
He 
believed it was possible to frustrate enemy plans through 
decisiveness and daring. He set forth his own rules on how to 
achieve decisiveness and aggressiveness as follows: "If you have 
ten times more forces than the enemy, surround him from all 
sides; if you have twice the forces, split him into parts; if 
forces are equal, be able to engage him in battle; if forces are 
fewer, be able to defend against him; if you have something 
generally worse, be able to evade him..."[.sup]2[/] 
  There is a great distance between what is desirable and what 
is possible in battle. Tens on hundreds of possible obstacles 
arise before the military leader on the path to achieving his 
goal. In entering a clash against the enemy, each time he 
experiences doubt as to whether or not everything has been taken 
into account, whether or not everything has been weighed in 
preparing the battle, whether or not everything has been done as 
necessary to achieve success. Vacillations in decisionmaking are 
inevitable. Therefore it is not enough to possess a brilliant 
mind, the gift of foresight, and organizing qualities; one also 
has to be capable of displaying enormous will in order to cast 
aside all contradictions and be able to implement with supreme 
persistence a decision which has been made. 
  Decisiveness and persistence are not synonyms for 
stubbornness and thickheadedness. Acting decisively does not 
mean stopping at nothing and striving for success at any cost, 
regardless of losses. Decisiveness is that trait of a military 
leader manifested in his ability to act vigorously and boldly 
and at the same time calculatingly and cleverly; to employ 
daring, aggressive methods of fighting a battle, but at the same 
time to skillfully protect himself against any surprises. 
  Displaying decisiveness and aggressiveness cannot be a goal 
in itself; it is only a necessary means for implementing one's 
concepts and plans. Realization of demands of the principle of 
decisiveness and aggressiveness for field generals always has 
been closely intertwined with skillful application of other 
principles--attainment of surprise in delivering an attack, bold 
concentration of efforts, precision of command and control, 
flexibility of interworking, comprehensiveness of support, and 
prudence. In short, decisiveness always acted as a necessary 
condition for implementing demands of all other principles. 
  In describing the campaigns of Alexander the Great into 
Persia and India, Arrian Nicodemus noted that the field general 
achieved decisiveness in striving to force the enemy to take an 
incorrect step and thereby place him in a difficult spot, and 
also to divert attention by decoy and cunning procedures. His 
aggressiveness was manifested in bold, farsighted decisions, in 
the ability to perplex the enemy with uncommonness of actions, 
and in employing unknown means of warfare. For example, 
unexpectedly for the Persians, in the assault on Halicarnassus 
Alexander employed siege equipment which could breach their 
fortress walls. Taking advantage of this, the Macedonians lobbed 
stones, animal corpses and barrels of snakes on the city. After 
inflicting heavy losses on the besieged, they executed a 
decisive assault on the fortress. 
  Thanks to aggressiveness and resourcefulness and to daring, 
surprise actions, the Macedonians managed to take the Persian 
fortress of Tyre. Alexander was not troubled by the circumstance 
that the city not only was protected by fortifications, but also 
was situated behind a vast water obstacle, a strait. He acted 
without delay, ordering a mole to be built across the strait, 
catapults and ballistas set up on it and the city bombarded with 
stones. The unusual assault, aggressive actions and 
unprecedented "infernal machines" all played their role. The 
enemy was broken morally and physically. The action was crowned 
by a concerted assault on the city from different 
sides.[.sup]3[/] 
  In order to achieve decisive actions and stun the enemy, 
Alexander encouraged soldiers' inventiveness and resourcefulness 
in every way and brought in engineers to seek new means of 
supporting battle. His army proved capable of making an assault 
crossing of broad water obstacles in short time periods because 
wineskins inflated with air and wooden boats disassembled into 
parts during transportation were employed as crossing 
equipment.[.sup]4[/] The enemy in no way expected such 
actions and was not ready for resistance. From above, the 
conclusion can be drawn that it is not enough to wish to achieve 
decisive, aggressive actions; one must be able to create 
necessary conditions and favorable premises for this and 
immediately exploit results. 
  Aggressiveness and decisiveness were characteristic traits 
of 
Julius Caesar's field-generalship activity. He used swiftness 
and decisiveness of actions and was able to take advantage of a 
favorable moment to throw the enemy into disarray, to break and 
split his combat formations and hit them in detail. 
  Caesar looked for his own special "key" to success in each 
engagement. Therefore each of his campaigns was dissimilar from 
another both in concept and in methods of achieving 
aggressiveness. In the battle at Pharsalus (48 B.C.) he 
surpassed his enemy Pompey because he acted uncommonly--not like 
everyone, but in his own way. Caesar aligned the combat 
formation in a new way, establishing a reserve of six cohorts, 
which none of the field generals previously had employed. This 
gave him an opportunity to build up his forces at the height of 
the engagement, to act more boldly and forcefully than Pompey 
and impose his own will on him.[.sup]5[/] 
  The decisiveness and swiftness of Caesar's actions played a 
main role during the campaign into Asia Minor, where his army 
smashed a strong army from Pontus in five days. Just like 
Alexander the Great, Julius Caesar made skillful use of engineer 
art to achieve aggressiveness. The Roman Army was able to build 
bridges not only on floating piers, but also on piled piers. We 
know, for example, of a timber pier bridge around 600 m long 
built in ten days across the Rhine River during the campaign 
against the Germans.[.sup]6[/] The high level of engineering 
art during the Roman Empire is attested to by the circumstance 
that each legion's supply train had a certain number of light 
boats with a frame of willow branches covered by 
skins.[.sup]7[/] This enabled the Romans to negotiate water 
obstacles quickly and unexpectedly for the enemy and to 
decisively smash his confused army. 
  Soldiers' resourcefulness and knack, which were the basis of 
the principle of aggressiveness, were inherent to tactics of 
Slavic tribes. Ancient chroniclers noted the high skill, 
decisiveness and resourcefulness displayed in their combat 
operations. In wars against Byzantium (6-7th centuries) they 
showed they had good mastery of siege art. The Slavic army would 
skillfully lure the enemy into a prepared trap, demonstrate 
false retreats, employ abatis and ambushes, and execute raids on 
the enemy from different directions. Portable and mobile screens 
made of brushwood hurdles were used to covertly approach his 
fortified camp, and earth embankments were built. 
  In assaulting fortresses the soldiers would make earth 
mounds 
next to them which they would ascend, then they would cut off 
the paling and set fire to towers and walls of the enemy 
fortress. Much that was new and unexpected for the enemy in 
methods of fighting a battle was employed during the campaign 
into Byzantium in 551 by a 3,000-man Slavic army detachment. 
After making an assault crossing of the Danube River on rafts 
and barrels, the detachment passed through all of Illyria and 
reached the city of Dyrrhachium on the coast of the Adriatic Sea. 
  The decisiveness and scale of actions of the ancient Russian 
Army in the 10th century is attested to by the campaign of 
Kievan Prince Oleg (907) against Tsargrad (Constantinople), 
during which interworking of the land detachment with a 
detachment of vessels (200) was done very successfully. Later, 
2,000 vessels took part in the campaign of Kievan Prince Igor 
(944).[.sup]8[/] Just as with the Greeks and Romans, 
decisiveness and aggressiveness of operations by the ancient 
Russian Army largely were increased by use of various siege 
equipment. Thus, siege machines, iron rams, enormous pieces for 
throwing rocks, and so-called "testudos"--structures covered 
with dry hides--were prepared for taking the fortress of 
Thessalonia. 
  The improvement of weapons and methods of combat operations 
dictated an ever greater diversity of forms and methods of 
achieving decisiveness and aggressiveness in battle. While 
usually relatively small detachments took part in engagements of 
the 10th-12th centuries, the scale of combat operations rose 
substantially during the 14th-16th centuries. For example, in 
the battle against the Golden Horde by Prince Dmitriy of Moscow 
on Kulikovo Field almost 300,000 persons took part on both 
sides. Dmitriy Donskoy's decisiveness of operations in this 
battle was manifested in the fact that he managed to preempt the 
enemy in deploying and delivering an attack (Fig. 1). The 
Tatar-Mongol army under the command of Mamai also acted with 
great determination and aggressiveness in this engagement. But 
in the final account the preponderance was on Dmitriy's side, 
because at the decisive moment he managed to take skillful 
advantage of his general and special reserves to deliver the 
final attack against the enemy, which predecided the battle's 
outcome. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-29A>             Fig. 1. Battle of Kulikovo </FIG>



  With the appearance of firearms in the 14th-15th centuries, 
decisiveness and aggressiveness of troop operations in battle 
began to take on new forms in connection with the use of fire. 
Although at first the ruchnitsas [hand-held 
harquebus-type firearms] being used by Russian soldiers were 
imperfect, the Moscow, Rostov, Novgorod and other chronicles 
tell, in describing battles in the defense of Moscow (1408 and 
1451), Uglich, Rzhev (1446 and 1447), Galis (1451) and Novgorod 
(1471), that "more than once the enemy was very frightened by 
the firing." 
  The appearance in the Russian Army of the first models of 
guns--tyufyaks--firing shot [grapeshot] played no 
small part in increasing the decisiveness and aggressiveness of 
battle. Use of cannons in defense of fortresses enabled fighting 
off an enemy assault and conducting counterattacks. In wars of 
Rus with Lithuania, Poland, Livonia and the Kazan and Crimean 
Khanates in the latter half of the 15th century and in the 16th 
century, along with the fight for fortresses, field battle began 
to be employed more and more widely in which the Russian Army 
found ever newer tactical methods of operations. Thus, in 1530 
Russian druzhinas for the first time used mobile field 
fortifications made of wood and shields with firing ports, the 
so-called gulyay-gorod. Using the mobile shelter 
enabled inflicting losses on an enemy from short range by fire 
from harquebuses and guns and also by fire from bows. As soon as 
the enemy combat formation managed to be breached, the cavalry 
would join the action, completing the enemy's defeat by a 
surprise attack. 
  When more powerful cannons called treskotukhas and 
barsy became operational during the Livonian War 
(1558-1583), an opportunity appeared to engage the enemy not 
only in close battle, but also from a distance of more than 1 
km.[.sup]9[/] The long-range (distant) firefight originated 
as a result. The Russian Army's achievement of high combat 
aggressiveness was facilitated by the soldiers' combat 
qualities, staunchness, valor, selflessness, love for the 
Motherland and hatred for the invaders. This gave them strength 
in battle and inspired them to exploits. The six-month defense 
of Pskov (August 1581-January 1582) was an example of the 
Russian Army's exceptional staunchness, determination and high 
combat aggressiveness in the defense. The fortress garrison 
numbered 16,000 persons and the city was besieged by a 
50,000-man Polish army headed by King Stefan Batory. But the 
besieged did not sit it out behind fortress walls; they often 
made bold sallies, hampered the enemy's engineer work, inflicted 
losses on him and conducted reconnaissance. The Pskov garrison 
withstood a sum total of 31 assaults, but just did not surrender 
to the enemy.[.sup]10[/] 
  Even longer than Pskov, the garrison of 
Troitsko-Sergiyevskaya Monastery defended 16 months (September 
1608-January 1610) and the Smolensk garrison 20 months (October 
1609-June 1611). What was new in the defense of these fortresses 
from the standpoint of combat aggressiveness were the 
long-distance, rather lengthy sallies by detachments of the 
besieged and decisive counterattacks executed not only during 
the day, but also at night. This enabled keeping the enemy under 
constant stress and wearing him down. Enemy attempts to 
penetrate the fortress through breaches in walls were quickly 
stopped. 
  The principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness found a 
certain reflection in the first Russian "Ustav ratnykh, 
pushechnykh i drugikh del, kasayushchikhsya voyennoy nauki" 
[Manual of Military, Gunnery and Other Affairs Concerning 
Military Science] (1607-1621), written by Onisim Mikhaylov. It 
pointed out that it was necessary to display persistence in 
erecting city fortifications and in their siege. In order to be 
aggressive it was recommended preparing siege assets ahead of 
time. 
  The establishment of permanent armies in a number of 
European 
states was a material precondition which contributed to 
increased decisiveness and aggressiveness of operations in wars 
of the 16th-18th centuries. Being well trained, they had an 
opportunity to conduct field engagements and a more active fight 
for fortresses. Prominent military figures of that time Maurice 
of Orange and Swedish King Gustavus Adolphus played an important 
role in reorganizing their armies and developing new, aggressive 
tactics. 
  In Russia Peter the Great was an outstanding military 
reformer. His views on military art, particularly on the 
principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness, were reflected in 
the treatises "Pravila srazheniya" [Rules of Engagement] (1708), 
"Rassuzhdeniya o dobyvanii Vyborkha" [Reflections on Taking 
Vyborg] (1710) and especially the "Voinskiy ustav" [Military 
Regulations] (1716). These and other documents reflected ideas 
of acting boldly, swiftly and forcefully, but prudently in 
battle, "not be led by the enemy, but constantly keep an eye on 
him and hit him as much as possible." 
  A. V. Suvorov made no small contribution to developing the 
principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness. In an era when 
European armies were dominated by linear tactics, which shackled 
the initiative of commanders and troops like a straitjacket, 
Suvorov developed and brilliantly employed column tactics in 
combination with an extended order--a method of battle created 
in the West only during the Great French Revolution of the late 
18th century and later developed by Napoleon.[.sup]11[/] 
  Suvorov taught: "The true rule of military art is to attack 
the enemy directly from the side most sensitive for him and not 
come together by timidly taking a roundabout way, . . . the 
matter can be resolved only by a direct bold 
offensive."[.sup]12[/] 
  Suvorov set forth basic principles of his aggressive tactics 
especially clearly in the plan for the Italian campaign (1799): 
"1. Nothing but the offensive. 2. Speed in marches, swiftness. 
3. Methodism is not needed, but good visual estimation is. 4. 
Full authority to the commanding general. 5. Attack the enemy 
and hit him in the field. 6. Lose no time in sieges . . . take 
fortresses chiefly by assaults or open force... 7. Never divide 
forces for security of different points. If the enemy went 
around them, so much the better: he approaches in order to be 
defeated. . . . Never occupy yourself with vain 
maneuvers."[.sup]13[/] This was truly a catechism of rules of 
combat aggressiveness. 
  Among western authors who paid greatest attention to the 
principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness were Turenne, 
Montecuccoli, Eugene of Savoy and H. Lloyd. Thus, the "Notes of 
Count Raimundo Montecuccoli..." (1664) stated that initiative 
must be aimed at preempting the enemy, at swiftness, firmness 
and aggressiveness. He recommended not splitting up one's 
forces.[.sup]14[/] Napoleon attached great significance to 
the principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness. Rejecting 
cordon strategy, he believed the principal goal of combat 
operations was not seizure of territory and fortresses, but 
defeat of the enemy army. He said: "I see only one thing--masses 
of enemy troops. I try to destroy them, confident that all the 
rest will collapse together with them."[.sup]15[/] 
  The principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness was 
manifested in the field-generalship activity of M. I. Kutuzov in 
the diversity of methods of strategic and tactical operations 
employed, in the capability of foreseeing how the enemy will act 
in order to take timely steps to constrain his maneuver and 
disrupt his plan, in flexible use of reserves in dangerous 
sectors of the front, in a more rational alignment of combat 
formations, in a broad display of initiative and in granting 
"freedom of initiative" to subordinates. Like Suvorov, Kutuzov 
took skilled advantage of the Russian soldier's combat 
qualities, resourcefulness, sharpness and stratagem. 
  Before a battle Kutuzov would inspire the soldiers, and they 
would display supreme decisiveness and valor. Here, for example, 
is how a participant of the Battle of Borodino, F. Glinka, 
describes it: "Experience shows that the Russian line that has 
been pierced, cut up, and broken still holds. . . . And even 
when the French penetrated into the rear of our troops, their 
combat formations did not get confused. Dokhturov and Rayevskiy 
decided: If the enemy is behind us, we will turn ourselves 
inside out, we will begin to hit the front ones from the front 
faces and the rear ones from the rear faces."[.sup]16[/] 
  In describing the field-generalship art of Barclay de Tolly, 
many military historians focus attention on his excessive 
caution. But when necessary he also skillfully employed the 
principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness. In setting forth 
his war strategy in a letter to P. I. Bagration on 1 June 1812, 
de Tolly demanded: "...a) hit and destroy a weak enemy; b) avoid 
all decisive engagements with a very strong enemy; c) irregular 
troops must have the enemy in unimpeded view, encircle him from 
all sides, bother him day and night and hamper his supply by 
operating against a line of operations." In an instruction to 
General Platov he directed: "Even in defensive operations an 
chance must not be missed to inflict telling blows on the enemy 
and pound him in detail."[.sup]17[/] 
  K. Marx and F. Engels had high esteem for the 
field-generalship activity of Barclay de Tolly in the first 
stage of war. They noted that he "executed a withdrawal with 
wonderful art."[.sup]18[/] H. Jomini also wrote about this. 
"That withdrawal which the Russian Army made in 1812 from the 
Neman to Moscow over a distance of 240 lieue 
[approximately 1,080 km] without allowing an enemy such as 
Napoleon to put them in disarray or partially defeat them . . . 
should be placed above all others."[.sup]19[/] 
  Jomini noted that the principle of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness should be employed in close combination with the 
principles of concentration of efforts and attainment of 
surprise in operations. "...If military art," he wrote, 
"consists of throwing one's forces at a decisive point, it is 
understandable that the first means for application of this 
principle will be seizing the initiative in operations. Whoever 
has seized this initiative knows in advance what he is doing and 
what he wants: With his masses he arrives at that point where he 
should deliver the blow. Whoever waits, is preempted everywhere: 
The enemy pounces on separate parts of his army; he knows 
neither where the enemy wishes to direct his efforts nor the 
means which he must counter."[.sup]20[/] 
  Also to Jomini's credit in developing this principle is that 
for the first time he extended it not only to the offensive, but 
also to the defense. Jomini correctly pointed out that the 
defense must not be waiting, but aggressive in purpose and must 
include elements of the offensive, i.e., bear an 
offensive-defensive character. 
  C. von Clausewitz called this principle boldness, firmness 
and aggressiveness. He remarked that "theory has no right to 
restrict it by virtue of its legislative power . . . Boldness is 
a creative power. . . . Even foolhardiness, that is boldness 
without an object, is not to be despised. Boldness lends wings 
to the mind and the discernment . . . it is impossible to 
imagine a distinguished General without boldness."[.sup]21[/] 
  Clausewitz set aside just as significant a role for firmness 
in a military leader's activity. He wrote that a commander 
"finds himself in a constant whirlpool of false and true 
information, of mistakes committed through fear, through 
negligence, through precipitation, of contraventions of his 
authority, either from mistaken or correct motives, from ill 
will, true or false sense of duty, indolence or exhaustion, of 
accidents which no mortal could have foreseen."[.sup]22[/] 
And one who takes it into his head to yield to these 
impressions, concludes Clausewitz, will display weakness, he 
will be incapable of firmly defending or of implementing a 
decision. 
  Speaking of decisiveness and aggressiveness, the military 
classic notes that "our basic principle is to view the 
destruction of enemy armed forces as the most important thing 
not only in the entire war . . . but also in each individual 
battle."[.sup]23[/] As we see, Clausewitz's opinion in this 
matter fully coincides with the views of Napoleon. Attainment of 
the principal goal of war, destruction of the enemy, according 
to Clausewitz is achieved only by battle. "Tactical successes in 
war," he wrote, "have a dominating importance."[.sup]24[/] 
This thesis was correct for that time, but now strategic and 
operational echelons have their own very effective means of 
warfare which are not part of formations. Therefore the role of 
tactics and the battle should be viewed in a different manner, 
in the overall system of operations and engagements. 
  In analyzing the experience of wars of the late 18th and 
19th 
centuries, one can be convinced as to what major role the 
steadily increasing firepower played in the change in content of 
the principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness. Adoption of 
firearms with a curved stock, which made aimed fire possible, 
played a very important role in this matter. A transition from 
column tactics to extended order tactics occurred in the 
Crimean, Franco-Prussian and Russo-Turkish (1877-1878) Wars, 
which gave the offensive greater penetration and dynamism and 
increased mobility. The aggressiveness of the defense also 
increased and field defense originated. To reduce losses from 
aimed fire and increase the stability of defending troops, in 
addition to building earth-fill fortifications (redoubts, 
fl&egrave;ches, lunettes) they began digging group emplacements 
(logements) and building protective cover and shelters for 
reserves. The importance of engineer preparation of terrain rose. 
  Russian military theorists of the 19th century promptly 
identified the new trends in development of the principle of 
decisiveness and aggressiveness. This was reflected in 
particular in military works by Decembrists P. Pestel, N. 
Muravyev, I. Burtsov, F. Glinka and others. Thus, in his work 
"Russkaya pravda" [Russian Truth] P. I. Pestel noted that 
"success of a military battle . . . depends on decisive 
action..."[.sup]25[/] He linked this both with the force of 
weapons as well as with the Russian soldier's combat qualities. 
D. Davydov, a courageous partisan of the Patriotic War of 1812, 
expressed many instructive thoughts with respect to increasing 
decisiveness and aggressiveness. He developed tactics of 
partisan warfare. Fervent patriot Davydov believed in Russia's 
strength and might and in the valor of the Russian soldier. It 
is to him that belong the prophetic words: "Russia has never yet 
risen to its full gigantic height, and woe to its enemies should 
it rise at some time!"[.sup]26[/] 
  The principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness can be 
traced through the works of G. A. Leyer and M. I. Dragomirov. 
"The very worst thing on which one can decide in war," wrote 
Leyer, "is not to decide on anything."[.sup]27[/] Many 
provisions expressed by Dragomirov regarding the principle of 
decisiveness and aggressiveness are in keeping with these 
thoughts of Leyer. He wrote in the "Uchebnik taktiki" [Tactics 
Textbook] that the one who wins is the one who "has the ability 
to make up his mind for combat undertakings without the 
slightest vacillation . . . and only one who does not fear 
perishing wins. . . . One incapable of making up his mind on 
something is like a person with tied hands with whom anyone can 
do what he likes. . . . The most ill-thought out undertaking 
does not present such a risk as indecisiveness."[.sup]28[/] 
  In wars of the late 19th and early 20th 
centuries--Spanish-American (1898), Anglo-Boer (1899-1902) and 
Russo-Japanese (1904-1905)--rifled longarms were used in 
considerable numbers; their combat capabilities had increased by 
almost tenfold compared with the Model 1808 smoothbore shoulder 
arm. Combat capabilities of artillery had increased 3-4 times. 
Machineguns began to be used on the battlefield for the first 
time.[.sup]29[/] In forecasting the influence of more 
advanced means of warfare on the content of principles of 
tactics, many military theorists concluded that from now on fire 
would displace hand-to-hand combat more and more. 
  This thought was expressed rather precisely by A. A. 
Neznamov, who wrote: "Decisive success in a modern engagement is 
based on attaining a preponderance of fire; silent weapons have 
faded into the background."[.sup]30[/] From an assessment of 
the factor of fire he draws the conclusion that under its 
influence the intensity and aggressiveness of combat operations 
will increase and tactical pauses will shorten. He noted: "The 
time is past in a war when people fought for weeks but waited 
for months."[.sup]31[/] 
  Works by Neznamov and other authors noted a trend toward 
substantial changes in confrontation of the offensive and 
defense under the influence of development of means of warfare. 
While confrontation of the offensive and defense had the nature 
of a confrontation of strength before the appearance of firearms 
and was accomplished in the form of a brief clash of close-order 
infantry or cavalry masses where the outcome of the battle 
depended on the force of soldiers' physical attack, with the 
appearance of firearms belligerents received the opportunity of 
exerting influence on each other at a distance, as a result of 
which troop losses increased and their determination in holding 
positions and their aggressiveness and decisiveness in the 
offensive rose. Fire began to act as the principal "motive 
force" in upgrading forms and methods of preparing and 
conducting combat operations. 
  This was manifested very clearly in the Russo-Japanese War, 
in which new offensive battle tactics were employed under 
conditions of strengthened rifle-machinegun and artillery 
firepower. Decisiveness was reflected in an increased proportion 
of night battles and employment of certain new means of warfare. 
The resourcefulness and inventiveness of Russian soldiers and 
officers were of great importance in increasing combat 
aggressiveness. Thus, in the defense of Port Arthur a method was 
found for throwing round sea mines from fortress fortifications 
into the assaulting Japanese infantry. Hand grenades also were 
used successfully. The world's first models of mortars were 
created with a range of fire up to 500 paces, and the first 
bomb-throwers for firing a six-inch (152-mm) bomb were designed. 
Siegecraft and countermine warfare was employed rather widely. 
  Changes in the nature of battle, its increased duration, 
intensity and spatial scope, and the increased complexity of 
command and control of subunits with the use of thinned extended 
lines on the battlefield sharply increased the role of 
independent actions of initiative by commanders at the tactical 
level. Subsequently this was reflected in the "Ustav polevoy 
sluzhby russkoy armii" [Russian Army Field Service Regulations] 
published in 1912. It instructed: "Every commander and 
rank-and-file soldier is granted independence in executing his 
assigned mission. He should display his own initiative in 
actions in conformity with situation changes if this is 
necessary for achieving a common cause, without awaiting an 
order to himself from the senior commander." 
  Attention also should be given to the fact that the 
aforementioned Regulations included a section on the meeting 
engagement for the first time. This occurred under the influence 
of Russo-Japanese War experience. Prior to this war, neither 
regulations of the Russian Army nor of other European armies 
gave any instructions regarding its conduct. The Russian 
"Nastavleniye dlya deystviya v boyu otryadov iz vsekh rodov 
oruzhiya" [Manual for Actions in Battle by Detachments of All 
Combat Arms] (1904) had only the most general instructions on 
this question. The meeting engagement was viewed as a rare, 
chance phenomenon. Troops did not study this kind of combat in 
exercises and maneuvers. Therefore the circumstance that 
numerous major meeting engagements occurred during the 
Russo-Japanese War in a vast space between the rivers Huanho and 
Shaho in October 1904 was a great surprise to the Russian 
command. Both sides attempted to take the initiative into their 
hands and deprive the enemy of freedom of actions by an assault 
on a selected axis with superior forces. But just like his 
enemy, General Oyama, General A. N. Kuropatkin displayed 
indecisiveness. He extended troops across a broad front out of 
fear of envelopment of the flanks. 
  Conditions for executing a bold maneuver, delivering attacks 
against the enemy flank and rear, and executing surprise close 
and deep envelopments were repeatedly created in meeting 
engagements. But, trained to act only on orders from above, the 
commanders in many cases missed an opportunity for decisive 
actions. 
  Russo-Japanese War experience with respect to development of 
the principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness was reflected 
in field manuals of the Russian and other European armies 
published prior to World War I. The aforementioned Russian 
"Ustav polevoy sluzhby" [Field Service Regulations] (1912) gave 
the main attention to offensive battle. They pointed out: "An 
attack on the enemy serves as the most effective means for 
defeating him." At the same time the Regulations did not deny 
the importance of the defense and recognized a transition to the 
defense to be necessary when the assigned goal could not be 
achieved by the offensive. The Regulations demanded that the 
defense be aggressive and end with the launching of an 
offensive: "In defending, one must strive by all methods and 
means to place the enemy in disarray by fire and, having 
undermined his morale, launch an offensive and defeat him." The 
Regulations paid attention to battle at night and in the 
mountains. But it had no provisions about the need for 
conducting artillery preparation prior to an assault, which was 
taught by Russo-Japanese War experience. Despite certain 
shortcomings, the Field Service Regulations were the best in 
Europe at that time. The German "Infantry Drill Regulations" 
took poor account of the influence of fire. It demanded that the 
infantry attack continuously and move at full height without use 
of the terrain and without digging in. The French "Infantry 
Drill Regulations" (1904) underestimated the increased 
importance in battle not only of artillery, but also of rifle 
and machinegun fire. In the offensive the Regulations provided 
for deploying the infantry into an extended line with an 
interval only of one pace between fighting men. 
  It should be said that the defense was underestimated in 
many 
European armies on the eve of World War I. Thus, it was noted in 
the French "Manual for Senior Troop Commanders" (1914) that, 
having returned to its military traditions (having in mind the 
Napoleonic Wars--I.V.), the French Army "does not 
allow another law in conducting operations than the 
offensive."[.sup]32[/] Such a one-sided approach to assessing 
the kinds of combat operations resulted in no small losses for 
armies in the course of military operations. Mistakes made in 
prewar time had to be corrected on the battlefields. 
  The content of the principle of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness underwent substantial changes in wars of the 20th 
century compared with wars of the 19th century. This was 
dictated by the upgrading of armies' technical outfitting and 
means of command and control and support and by increased scope 
of military operations. In the pre-imperialist period offensive 
and defensive operations usually were accomplished within the 
framework of one engagement, which unfolded on relatively 
limited territory and was waged for a short time. For example, 
the Battle of Borodino in 1812 unfolded on a front of around 8 
km to a depth of up to 6 km and lasted only a few hours. 
  In wars of the 20th century the confrontation of offensive 
and defense took on a more determined and intensive nature. Now 
it was carried on in the form of several successive offensive 
and defensive engagements, which began to develop into a new 
form of military actions, the operation. Thus, in the 
Russo-Japanese War the continuous front of battle reached 75 km 
at Liaoyang and 155 km at Mukden. Depth of the engagement 
increased from 2-4 to 25-50 km, and the duration rose from 1-2 
to 10-17 days. Offensive actions were closely combined with 
defensive ones. 
  In subsequent wars the scope of confrontation of offensive 
and defense increased even more, and the content of the 
principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness also was largely 
updated. World War I began with a meeting clash of large masses 
of troops in the Eastern (Russian) and Western (French) theaters 
of military operations. In not one past war had there been such 
a significant number of meeting engagements as in the maneuver 
period of World War I. This was a result of prewar concepts of 
acting only offensively in war in order to win it in short time 
periods. 
  War subjected prewar theories regarding the meeting 
engagement to a very tough test and introduced much that was new 
to methods of its conduct. Combat experience showed that such an 
engagement is distinguished by fluidity, absence of a continuous 
front, and the presence of exposed flanks, and that success is 
attained in it by the one who acts creatively and with 
initiative, who organizes reconnaissance well and who preempts 
the enemy in deploying, opening fire and maneuvering. 
  Aggressiveness was displayed in the defense with 
unprecedented force. Use of rifle-machinegun and artillery fire 
in combination with the building of engineer obstacles, 
fortification of terrain and execution of counterattacks made 
the defense insurmountable for an attacker. The defense managed 
to withstand his striking power even when new means of 
warfare--tanks and aircraft--appeared. Both field position 
defense as well as defense of fortresses was employed 
successfully during the war. 
  The Russian troops' heroic defense of the Osowiec Fortress 
(1915) serves as an example of high staunchness and 
aggressiveness in holding fortresses. It was characterized by 
the fact that the defenders did not passively sit behind 
fortress fortifications, but undertook aggressive actions and 
constantly harassed the enemy with night sallies and delivery of 
counterattacks. 
  The Germans made the first assault on the fortress in 
February, but it was beaten off. Some time later one assault 
followed another over a period of two weeks, but the garrison 
not only did not waver, at every convenient instance it would 
deliver answering attacks. Convinced that the fortress could not 
be taken by assault, the Germans changed tactics--they began an 
exhausting bombardment of the fortress by heavy artillery and 
put 305-mm howitzers into action. The fortress was almost 
totally demolished, but it held out staunchly. After a half-year 
siege, the Germans undertook a gas-cylinder assault. Around 70 
percent of its defenders perished from fire and gases, and still 
the soldiers found the strength to retake positions by 
counterattacks.[.sup]33[/] Defense of the Osowiec Fortress 
was the prototype of Soviet troops' heroic defense of cities of 
Odessa, Sevastopol, Tula and Stalingrad in the Great Patriotic 
War, a symbol of the Russian soldier's supreme staunchness of 
spirit and resolve. 
  Important trends in development of aggressiveness of the 
defense during World War I were the increase in its depth and in 
anti-artillery, antichemical and antitank stability. There was a 
gradual transition from center-of-resistance defense and an even 
infantry distribution in the first line of trenches to trench 
defense with establishment of sturdy strongpoints and fire 
pockets between them (Fig. 2). 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-34A>             Fig. 2. Alignment of the defense during World War I </FIG>



  Offensive battle tactics were perfected simultaneously with 
development of the defense. An increase in its decisiveness was 
facilitated by the massing of a large amount of artillery in 
breakthrough sectors (160-180 pieces per kilometer of frontage); 
conduct of a powerful, lengthy artillery preparation prior to an 
assault; employment of a gas-cylinder assault in certain 
engagements; the attackers' use of a ramming tank attack to 
breach the enemy defense; an ever increasing buildup of air 
efforts to support attacking troops; conduct of an infantry 
assault following a rolling barrage; and an increased role and 
importance of night battles. 
  But many factors were observed in the course of the war 
which 
reduced effectiveness of the offensive. These were the 
predominance of methodism and linearity in troop actions, 
stereotyped alignment of combat formations and stereotyped use 
of methods of making a breakthrough. Low rates of advance 
resulted. Thus, in the Verdun operation German troops advanced 
at a rate of only 40 meters per day, the Anglo-French on the 
Somme advanced at a rate of 70 meters per day, and only in the 
Amiens operation (1918) for the first time in the entire war did 
the Anglo-French manage to successfully penetrate the enemy 
tactical defensive zone. On the first day they advanced 8 km and 
on the following six days advanced 19 km.[.sup]34[/] 
  On the whole, World War I was a classic example of the 
balance which had formed in the ratio of attack and defense 
means, which led to the sides' lengthy static confrontation. In 
order to find a way out of the positional impasse which had 
formed and give combat operations a decisive character, warring 
armies above all strived to improve their means of warfare and 
create those weapons and combat equipment which would be capable 
of reliably suppressing the defenders' fire plan and providing 
an opportunity for a broad offensive. Tanks and aircraft were 
these means, but they did not decisively influence the overall 
nature of military operations because of their poor combat 
qualities and relatively low numbers. As a result, belligerents 
were forced to be on defense for the greater part of the time, 
and only for eight months (altogether) of the overall length of 
the war (more than 51 months) did they conduct aggressive 
offensive operations on a broad scale.[.sup]35[/] 
  Decisiveness and aggressiveness were characteristic features 
of Red Army troop operations in the Civil War in Russia. M. V. 
Frunze noted: "Almost all significant operations of Civil War 
times bear traces of a manifestation of a spirit of 
aggressiveness and initiative on our side."[.sup]36[/] This 
was determined not by quality of weapons (they were the very 
same as in World War I), but by features of combat operations, 
by the absence of continuous static fronts and, most important, 
by the revolutionary enthusiasm of Red Army men and commanders 
and their initiative and innovativeness in employing decisive, 
mobile methods of warfare. 
  All prewar Red Army field manuals and field service 
regulations were imbued with a spirit of aggressiveness, 
decisiveness and offensiveness. Fighting men and commanders were 
required to display initiative, resourcefulness, determination 
and persistence in achieving the goal. Regulations noted that it 
was not the one who did not achieve success in combat despite 
all measures taken who deserved reproach, but the one who, 
fearing responsibility for failure, let the time slip by, showed 
no initiative, and did not take advantage of all opportunities 
for performing the assigned mission. 
  The aggressiveness, decisiveness and offensiveness of troops 
stemmed from the content of Soviet military doctrine, which 
provided for waging war only on enemy territory and defeating 
him "by a powerful blow" in short time periods. The idea of 
winning victory "with little blood" was so attractive that it 
left no place to be concerned with teaching troops to fight the 
lengthy, exhausting, bloody defensive and offensive battles 
characterizing the war which later came unexpectedly. Here we 
see an example of being excessively carried away by a 
decisiveness which did not correspond to a realistic assessment 
of the enemy and of one's own combat capabilities. 
  An attempt by Soviet commanders to act offensively no matter 
what with the beginning of war, as demanded by the supreme 
military leadership, led to enormous, unjustified losses and a 
sharp deterioration in the troops' situation. Therefore 
decisiveness and aggressiveness should not be an end in 
themselves. In the final account Soviet troops learned to 
skillfully apply this principle in the course of battles. As 
Zhukov noted, "all major offensive and counteroffensive 
operations of Soviet troops beginning with the fall of 1942 were 
distinguished by originality, decisiveness, swiftness and total 
completeness."[.sup]37[/] 
  Just what new things did World War II introduce to the 
content of the principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness? 
Above all we will note that the ratio of attacking forces and 
means of defense shaped up differently in this war than in World 
War I. In many operations the attacker succeeded in achieving a 
decisive fire superiority over the defender, which was the 
result of the changed material base of war. Massive employment 
of aircraft, artillery and tanks in operations in combination 
with increased striking power and firepower of formations 
enabled not only making a quick break-in of the enemy defense, 
but also decisively building up the force of the attack by 
commitment of mobile groupings, turning tactical success into 
operational success. 
  But even under these relatively favorable situation 
conditions, demands of the principle of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness were realized in a difficult, intense struggle. 
Commanders and staffs were required to display high proficiency 
in order to surpass the enemy in employing aggressive forms of 
battle, imposing their will on him, and seizing and holding the 
initiative. 
  The belligerents usually found effective methods of 
opposition rather quickly when enemy tactics changed and new 
methods of warfare appeared. For example, in response to a 
strengthening of striking power and penetration of attacking 
troops, trends began to be reinforced in the defense toward a 
transition from a shallow, center-of-resistance defense to a 
continuous, deeply echeloned trench system of building positions 
and zones, which balanced the sides' capabilities. If the 
attacker attempted to increase rates of advance by massive 
employment of tank troops, the defending side would increase its 
capabilities in response by upgrading the antitank defense 
system--establishing antitank strongpoints, centers and areas to 
the full depth not only of the tactical, but also of the 
operational defense. The sides' competition occurred in a 
similar way in building up attacks from the air and reinforcing 
air defense. 
  The main sphere of the sides' opposition in World War II was 
the struggle to win and hold fire superiority. Decisiveness of 
the offensive and attainment of high rates of penetration, 
pursuit, and nonstop crossing of water obstacles by Soviet 
troops largely were ensured by perfection of methods of fire 
damage of the enemy. Use of the so-called artillery and air 
offensive, which provided effective, continuous fire support to 
attacking infantry and tanks to the full depth of combat mission 
performance, played a major role here. 
  But to counterbalance this the German command began seeking 
more effective methods of counterbattery fire and of conducting 
a counterpreparation, and it began employing deceptive 
procedures more widely to covertly remove its subunits from the 
FEBA into the depth on the eve of Soviet troops' artillery 
preparation of an assault. 
  And although the Great Patriotic War experience largely 
enriched the content of the principle of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness and Soviet commanders set brilliant examples of 
skillful realization of the demands of this principle in 
practice, many negative points also were observed. Decisiveness 
and aggressiveness were not always achieved through art and 
cunning. Reliance was placed most often on achieving a multiple 
superiority in personnel and equipment over the enemy. 
Stereotyped procedures and banality sometimes occurred in 
preparing and conducting the battle. Linear, methodical actions 
often prevailed over maneuver. Some commanders' fear of 
responsibility also told at times, which paralyzed a display of 
initiative. 
  The revision of field manuals did not always keep up with 
the 
development of tactics. For example, in prewar times it was 
believed that a platoon or company commander should draw 
subordinates into the assault by personal example and therefore 
was obligated to be in front of the combat formation. In the 
first period of war this led in practice not to increased 
aggressiveness of actions, but to heavy losses of command 
personnel. 
  Or take another example. Prewar Red Army field manuals 
provided for a deeply echeloned alignment of the combat 
formation in the offensive, beginning with the company and 
ending with the division. It was believed that this created 
conditions for decisive forward movement at an increasing rate. 
But at the beginning of the war the German defense was shallow 
and center-of-resistance. Penetrating it did not require having 
such a considerable number of personnel and equipment in second 
echelons and reserves. In practice this led only to excessive 
personnel losses. It often happened that they suffered heavy 
losses from enemy fire even before commitment. 
  What was new in realizing this principle in modern local 
wars 
was the increased power and depth of fire damage of the enemy; 
wide employment of airmobile troops and airborne and amphibious 
assault forces for creating an aggressively operating front in 
the enemy rear and splitting his grouping into parts; a more 
frequent and broader use in battle than before of new 
weapons--napalm, combat helicopters, guided weapons, MLRS, 
automated reconnaissance and command and control equipment, 
fuel-air explosives, new kinds of engineer obstacles and so on. 
  The result of this was an increase in the decisiveness, 
dynamic nature and mobility of combat operations. Military 
analysts have calculated that while the coefficient of combat 
operations intensity during the Russo-Japanese War was 0.2 and 
in World War I (based on the experience of western countries) it 
was 0.46, then in World War II (based on experience of the 
Soviet-German front) it was 0.88. Based on experience of 
contemporary local wars, it is approaching unity.[.sup]38[/] 
It is apparent from this that the role and importance of the 
principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness in battle has had a 
stable tendency to rise in the course of wars. At the present 
stage of development of military affairs, material preconditions 
have been created for development of this trend, which is 
dictated by the outfitting of troops with qualitatively new 
weapons possessing great range, high destructive power, accuracy 
and mobility, as well as by very sophisticated means of command 
and control and support. 
<H3>  2. Principle of Decisiveness and Aggressiveness in Defensive 
Battle </H3>
  High aggressiveness in combination with the troops' 
determination in holding occupied positions is the principal 
condition for achieving defense stability. Combat practice has 
shown convincingly that waiting and passivity are pernicious for 
a defender. Speaking of the importance of aggressiveness and 
initiative in defense, prominent Soviet military leader General 
of the Army A. V. Gorbatov remarked in a conversation with young 
officers that "this is that weapon which you always have, which 
always will help you get out of a difficult spot, even if it 
theoretically turns out that no way out of the situation at hand 
is evident. . . . Let it not frighten you that the enemy is 
highly experienced and refined and that he surpasses you by many 
times in forces. He still is not all-powerful. Think, organize, 
search well, and you definitely will find his vulnerable spot, 
you will discover his blunder, by taking advantage of which you 
can nullify all his efforts or even rout him."[.sup]39[/] The 
value of this advice is immense--it comes from experience. 
  The correlation and interrelationship of the defense and 
offensive have appeared differently in each war depending on the 
level of development of means of warfare. But one also can 
follow the manifestation of a certain general trend in their 
interrelationship. It is that an ever increasing mutual 
penetration of these kinds of combat operations is occurring. 
Points in time arise more and more often in the offensive where 
it is impossible to get by without defense or to advance without 
consolidation on captured lines. Offensive forms and methods of 
operations are being used more and more widely and fully in the 
defense, which increases the decisiveness of its goals. 
  Many military analysts are inclined to conclude from this 
circumstance that this trend will have even more striking 
development in the future. Thus, the authors of the 
military-theoretical work "Taktika" [Tactics] arrive at the 
conclusion that the contemporary defense is acquiring a new 
quality--in contrast to the past, it is receiving an opportunity 
not only of repelling an attack by superior enemy forces, but 
even of disrupting his offensive.[.sup]40[/] This means that 
its decisiveness is increasing sharply. 
  I assume such a conclusion hardly can be deemed 
unequivocally 
indisputable, for the sides' combat capabilities are each 
growing. This means that a manifestation of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness of the defense inevitably will be opposed by the 
attacking side's determined countermeasures. One also cannot 
fail to take into account that the defense as a kind of combat 
operation not only has strong aspects, but also a certain 
vulnerability. Defending troops are significantly dependent on 
the attacking enemy's actions. 
  Just the circumstance alone in choosing the time, place and 
methods of delivering attacks are on the attacker's side; this 
places the defense in an unequal situation with him. To this 
must be added that, as a rule, the attacking side possesses a 
quantitative or even a qualitative superiority. Hence, it 
becomes understandable that the defense is far from always in a 
position to impose its will on the attacker, inasmuch as it 
chronically experiences an acute shortage of personnel and 
equipment. 
  Opposition of the offense and defense always has been the 
motive force of development of military art in all wars. At the 
present stage it is manifested with special vividness. This 
essentially means that it is necessary to seek new forms and 
methods of displaying aggressiveness and decisiveness in battle 
in order to achieve superiority over the enemy. As shown by 
combat experience, in addition to the advantage taken of 
objective factors, much depends here on the tactical 
creativeness of commanders, staffs and troops. 
  We will refer to the Great Patriotic War experience to 
illustrate this thesis. It is common knowledge that the quality 
of weapons and combat equipment did not undergo any substantial 
changes whatsoever during the War, but the results of battles, 
including also in the defense, can be said to have been striking 
in the first and subsequent periods. Thus, while enemy troops 
managed to advance to a depth of 250-270 km in 67 days of 
defensive battles during the Battle of Moscow, they advanced 
only 120-150 km in 124 days in the Battle of Stalingrad. The 
maximum advance of offensive groupings of fascist German troops 
during the defensive engagement at Kursk did not exceed 35 km. 
  The increased stability of defense by Soviet troops in the 
course of combat operations was largely determined by the fact 
that each time the commanders and staffs tried to find ever more 
improved tactics, this contributed to attaining decisive goals 
in battle. Now, when foreign armies, particularly the U.S. Army 
under the "air-land operation" concept, are seeking methods for 
delivering a deep strike in the offensive in order to paralyze 
enemy actions in a short time by taking advantage of the factor 
of surprise (Fig. 3), the defender's mission is to counter the 
attacker with his own more aggressive methods of opposition; to 
not allow combat formations to be broken up laterally and in 
depth; and to disrupt the enemy's ground and air maneuver. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-38A>             Fig. 3. Essence of the "air-land operation" </FIG>



   Fig. 4 clearly shows the possible forms and methods of 
applying the principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness in the 
defense. Their common characteristic feature is the diversity of 
tactics and the growing role of fire, maneuver and obstacles in 
achieving goals of the defense. And although in terms of 
external characteristics certain methods of conducting a 
defensive battle are indistinguishable from those used during 
World War II, their content has largely been renewed. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-39A>             Fig. 4. Methods of realizing the principle of </FIG>



  Take for example a well-known method such as successive 
delivery of damage on the enemy as he approaches the FEBA and 
wedges into the depth of the defense. Its difference from the 
past is that the defender now has the capability of more 
actively pressuring the enemy in all stages of his preparation 
of the offensive beginning with his troops' concentration in 
attack positions, during forward movement into the assault, and 
ending with the fight to hold defensive positions. 
  The increased range of weapons contributes to this (Fig. 5). 
Thus, in World War I artillery had a range of fire of 
6,000-9,000 m and in a defense could lay down barrage fire ahead 
of the FEBA and use fire basically to exert an effect on combat 
formations of attacking first-echelon regiments. This only 
partially weakened the attacking troops' offensive potential. 
Therefore, hand-to-hand combat played the main role in repelling 
an enemy assault. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-40A>             Fig. 5 [caption missing] </FIG>



  In World War II the range of the bulk of artillery increased 
to 9,000-12,000 m, which enabled the defender to keep the full 
depth of the combat formation of attacking enemy formations 
under fire. Fire aggressiveness and stability of the defense 
increased in connection with this. As a result, there was a 
significant increase in the attacker's losses to the fire of 
defending troops. Hand-to-hand combat was used more rarely. 
  Under present conditions the maximum range of weapons of 
combined arms formations, counting combat helicopters and 
supporting aviation, has increased by 4-5 times compared with 
World War II. The depth of fire strikes has increased 
accordingly. For example, based on NATO troop exercise 
experience, fire engagement of the enemy is planned in the 
division defense to a depth of 80-110 km. This means that, using 
its own assets, a formation now essentially is capable of 
continuously exerting a fire effect not only on the enemy's 
tactical reserves, but also on his immediate operational 
reserves and of keeping him under constant tension. 
  When one takes into account that now not only maximum range, 
but also destructive power and accuracy of weapon strikes have 
increased, it becomes obvious that the defender is capable of 
making wider use of the principle of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness to achieve his goals. 
  But this principle is realized especially effectively in the 
case where a deep combination effect is used on an attacking 
enemy from the ground and air. This is a new form of combat 
aggressiveness in the defense dictated by the appearance of such 
weapons as precision weapons, helicopters, EW assets, and 
equipment for remote mining of terrain. The essence of this 
method of defensive battle is to constrain enemy operations to 
the maximum extent, disorganize his command and control, wear 
him down, inflict losses on him, and reduce his offensive 
groupings' rates of advance by fire. The latter is accomplished 
by landing airborne assault forces and raiding and 
reconnaissance units in the enemy rear, by establishing 
defensive fire barriers on his routes of forward movement, and 
by employing massive electronic jamming. We will emphasize the 
important role in attaining these goals played by defensive fire 
barriers, which are created by remote minelaying equipment, in 
combination with massive fire strikes, delivered by 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, reconnaissance-fire complexes, 
MLRS systems, combat helicopters and artillery. 
  One effective method of displaying combat aggressiveness in 
the defense is to deliberately draw the enemy into a planned 
area (fire pocket) and deliver strikes against him from the 
front, flanks and rear. This is essentially also a new method of 
conducting defensive battle. Although a withdrawal of subunits 
from the FEBA into the depth to deceive the enemy sometimes was 
employed in World War II; first of all it was done on a limited 
scale; secondly, it was done very rarely; and thirdly, at that 
time the defender had no opportunity to deliver a combination 
strike against a wedged-in enemy from different directions, 
including also from the rear. 
  Now, as a result of increased firepower and striking power 
and employment of airborne assault forces, combined arms 
formations more often than before can deliberately create fire 
pockets in order to lure the enemy into them and then decisively 
destroy him by massive artillery fire, strikes by aircraft and 
by reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire complexes, and 
delivery of surprise flanking counterattacks in combination with 
the landing of airborne assault forces in the enemy rear. 
  Forms and methods of displaying combat aggressiveness in 
fighting the enemy on approaches to the defense now have become 
more decisive and diverse. In principle, even in past wars the 
defender tried to exhaust and wear down the enemy to the maximum 
extent back before he launched an assault, but capabilities for 
this were very limited in World War I due to the short range of 
weapons. But it was then that the need arose for establishing a 
shallow (3-4 km) security area ahead of the FEBA which was 
saturated with various obstacles and covered by artillery fire. 
  A tendency to move the battlefield as far forward as 
possible 
beyond the FEBA saw further development in World War II. This 
was manifested in the fact that the depth of the security area 
increased to 10-12 km and its stability also rose, due to the 
fact that it began to have more thorough engineer preparation 
and rather considerable forces were assigned for its defense. 
  A decisive form of fire aggressiveness such as conducting an 
artillery and air counterpreparation against an offensive enemy 
grouping poised for the attack also began to be employed to 
disrupt an enemy offensive. The Soviet command began organizing 
the counterpreparation already in the first defensive operations 
(in June 1941 on the Northwestern axis), but its effect was 
insignificant due to the fact that the enemy grouping had been 
poorly reconnoitered and there was a shortage of artillery and 
ammunition. 
  Approximately the very same thing was repeated in the Battle 
of Leningrad in September 1941 and in the Battle of Moscow. 
Although in the latter instance counterpreparation was prepared 
more thoroughly by the Western Front command, few personnel and 
equipment were involved in conducting it. The counterpreparation 
mission assigned was to disrupt a possible enemy offensive. For 
this it was planned to use artillery fire to suppress and 
destroy his infantry and tanks in concentration areas and at 
attack positions, suppress enemy artillery and disrupt command 
and control. 
  To this end, detailed counterpreparation plans were worked 
out in the armies which envisaged the involvement not only of 
guns, but also of 82-mm and 120-mm mortars. Thus, on 1 and 2 
October 16th Army artillery in the vicinity of Yartsevo 
conducted a counterpreparation three times lasting up to 10 
minutes on a front of 10 km with a density of 30 guns per 
kilometer of front and with an expenditure of 0.3 units of fire. 
Its results could not be determined, since the enemy was not 
attacking on this axis.[.sup]41[/] 
  Artillery counterpreparation was conducted several times 
during the defensive battles at Stalingrad. Its duration usually 
was 40-60 minutes and consisted of 2-3 fire assaults (5-10 
minutes each) and battery fire for suppression. As a result, the 
enemy assault managed to be disrupted on certain 
axes.[.sup]42[/] 
  The experience of conducting an artillery counterpreparation 
in the Battle of Kursk in the defense zone of Central and 
Voronezh fronts deserves special attention. It was set to last 
30-40 minutes. A considerable amount of artillery was involved 
in the counterpreparation. Thus, in 13th Army it reached 1,100 
guns, mortars and combat vehicles, which provided a density of 
36 weapons per kilometer of front. Overall ammunition 
expenditure was specified as 0.25 units of fire. Aircraft took 
part in the counterpreparation. In assessing results of the 
counterpreparation, Zhukov wrote: "It should be said that the 
artillery staffs and all artillery commanders of fronts, armies 
and formations worked well and wisely to organize the artillery 
defense and counterpreparation."[.sup]43[/] 
  Under present conditions opportunities are being created for 
increasing the effectiveness of counterpreparation fire and 
organizing it in shorter time periods. The involvement of 
precision weapons, reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire 
complexes, a more significant amount of MLRS, and also front and 
army aviation contributes to this. 
  We will note that already in the past war defending troops 
sometimes delivered an attack ahead of the FEBA to exploit 
results of the counterpreparation with the goal of causing 
confusion in enemy ranks, disorienting him with respect to one's 
plans, and reinforcing the effect of the fire strike. 
  Such aggressive actions by defenders can receive wider scope 
under present conditions. For example, sometimes along with the 
delivery of a surprise counterattack against the enemy, it is 
possible to simultaneously land an airborne assault force in his 
rear and organize operations by raiding and reconnaissance 
parties in order to divert or dissipate the attacker's combat 
efforts and weaken or disrupt his attack. 
  Troops may use all forms and methods of aggressive 
operations 
during the battle to hold the main defense area. Main efforts 
are directed above all at holding the FEBA. As is apparent from 
Table 1, decisive disruption of the enemy assault requires 
disabling 50-60 percent of his personnel and combat equipment. 
With the degree of fire damage at 30 percent, there is a 40 
percent probability of the enemy giving up the assault. 


Table 1 - Probability of Enemy Giving Up the Assault as a Function of 
the Level of Personnel and Combat Equipment Losses Suffered (based on 
tactical exercise experience) 

Magnitude of      10     20     30     40     50     55     60     70 
personnel 
losses and 
disabling of 
enemy combat 
equipment, % 

Probability of    4      14     38     65     88     95     97     99 
enemy 
discontinuing 
assault, % 


  Methods of displaying combat aggressiveness during troop 
defense operations in the main and subsequent defense zones 
depend on the goals set, the sides' force ratio, and other 
situational conditions. In those cases where the mission 
assigned is to firmly hold occupied positions by a stiff 
position defense, fire aggressiveness basically prevails in 
order to prevent a breakthrough of enemy tanks and motorized 
infantry across the FEBA and to isolate the battlefield from an 
influx of his reserves from the depth. A stubborn fight must be 
waged for every strongpoint, hill, and road junction. Every 
meter of enemy advance must come to him with a fight and be 
accompanied by heavy losses. 
  In the past, counterattacks were one of the chief forms of 
displaying combat aggressiveness in conducting a position 
defense. It must be said that in the Great Patriotic War they 
were conducted by Soviet troops very often, but not always 
successfully, especially in the first period of war. 
  Here we are dealing with that case where aggressiveness 
became an end in itself. The sources of this subjectivist 
approach to displaying combat aggressiveness in the defense 
originated in prewar times, when the offensive idea was 
insistently advanced in all regulation documents--crush the 
enemy by a powerful attack in short time periods. For example, 
here is how this concept was interpreted in the prewar textbook 
"Obshchaya taktika" [General Tactics], which noted: "The 
guarantee of victory in the defense is supreme aggressiveness 
and decisiveness of operations, consisting of the troops and 
their commanders unceasingly striving not only to hold up the 
attacker, but also to inflict a crushing blow on 
him."[.sup]44[/] 
  In practice, with the beginning of military operations this 
developed into a situation where our division and regimental 
commanders were forced to act aggressively in accordance with 
the operations plan even in difficult, vague circumstances, when 
the enemy surpassed our troops many times in tanks and 
artillery, and when his aircraft had undivided rule of the air. 
To seize the initiative they would throw the troops against the 
enemy and would organize counterattacks clearly doomed to 
failure. 
  Under present conditions counterattacks by no means have 
lost 
their importance as a method of inflicting defeat on the enemy 
and restoring a lost position. But in making the decision to 
conduct them, we must weigh everything dozens of times and 
calculate what is more advantageous--repulse an assault of enemy 
tanks and infantry by fire from in place or throw subunits out 
to meet him. A counterattack that is insufficiently prepared 
with respect to fire, especially in those cases where the enemy 
has not been halted and has a clear superiority in personnel and 
equipment, can lead to excessive losses and worsen the 
defender's situation. 
  The simplest calculations show that a motorized rifle 
battalion is capable of repelling an assault of up to an enemy 
brigade by fire from in place, while it can rout only a company 
in delivering a counterattack. But this does not mean that one 
should reject counterattacks entirely. This would be incorrect, 
inasmuch as a situation may take shape in battle where it is 
possible to improve the situation at hand only by delivering a 
counterattack. 
  We will dwell in more detail on applying the principle of 
decisiveness and aggressiveness in a mobile defense, as this 
question has been less studied in our military theory. The 
mobile defense largely differs from the position defense in 
goals and methods of attaining them. It is conducted most often 
as a forced measure in a difficult, often critical situation 
against enemy forces that are many times superior. Therefore 
commanders, staffs and troops are required to display special 
skills so that they compensate for an acute shortage of 
personnel and equipment, win time, and exhaust and wear down the 
attacker by delaying actions on a number of lines favorable for 
defense. 
  Forms and methods of aggressive operations employed by 
Soviet 
troops in a mobile defense during the Great Patriotic War were 
not distinguished by great diversity. Units and subunits tried 
to damage the enemy chiefly by fire as he approached the FEBA 
and then, without taking matters to a decisive assault, would 
break contact with him, disengage and withdraw to the next 
defensive line in the depth, where these operations usually were 
repeated. Now the increased fire, attack and maneuver 
capabilities of combined arms formations and units permit 
significantly broadening and enriching tactics being used in 
order to immobilize the attacker's initiative, constantly wear 
him down and disrupt or hamper maneuver by harassing actions, 
and mislead him regarding one's true intentions by means of 
deceptive methods (Fig. 6). 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-43A>             Fig. 6. Forms and methods of tactical operations </FIG>



  Under present conditions it appears possible to make wider 
use of an effective method of combating the enemy, such as 
ambush operations. Ambushes were employed rather skillfully by 
Soviet troops in the mobile defense even in the Great Patriotic 
War. Thus, in January 1945 subunits of 110th Tank Brigade 
repelled up to ten enemy tank attacks during the day by fire 
from ambushes and thereby supported the withdrawal of 18th Tank 
Corps and its organized transition to a defense northwest of 
Budapest.[.sup]45[/] But at that time ambushes were set up 
primarily in immediate proximity of the FEBA, in gaps, and on 
strongpoint flanks and were insufficiently mobile. 
  Now the aggressiveness of fire ambushes is growing 
considerably in connection with the fact that not only tank and 
motorized rifle subunits can be involved in establishing them, 
but also combat helicopters, IFV's, APC's, ATGM systems, air 
defense systems and self-propelled guns. Helicopter ambushes, 
for example, can be set up on distant approaches to the defense. 
Other kinds of fire ambushes can be established throughout the 
zone or in a sector of the defense. 
  Roving tanks, IFV's, APC's, guns and mortars play an 
important role in increasing the aggressiveness of a mobile 
defense. Their wide, skillful use in a system of ambushes, as 
well as in strongpoints and in the space between positions, 
increases the tenacity and effectiveness of the fire plan and 
helps mislead enemy reconnaissance. Fire pockets may be set up 
in a mobile defense more often than before. Any opportunity is 
used to set them up: A favorable configuration of the front 
line; a gap between strongpoints; approaches to commanding 
heights and populated points; chokepoints; valleys; gorges and 
so on. Essentially all kinds of small arms are used in 
establishing fire pockets. Not only the regimental commander, 
but also every company and battalion commander can set up fire 
pockets with his own personnel and equipment. 
  In addition to fire pockets, an operational pocket can be 
established in an operational-level defense by decision of the 
large strategic formation commander to draw an enemy offensive 
grouping into it and defeat it by delivering surprise flanking 
counterthrusts. 
  It is typical that offensive forms of operations can be used 
in the course of a mobile defense in order to activate it; 
especially those such as landing airborne assault forces and 
assault teams in the enemy rear; sending out enveloping and 
raiding detachments; and conducting counterattacks and 
counterthrusts. Bold, daring raids through enemy rear areas made 
by air assault detachments are especially effective. Their 
surprise raids on columns; command and control facilities; 
weapons; air defense, EW and reconnaissance assets; and rear and 
other installations are capable of spreading disorganization in 
enemy actions and in the command and control of his troops and 
weapons, and substantially hampering maneuver capability. 
  With respect to counterattacks, there are many features in 
their conduct in a mobile defense. In contrast to a position 
defense, in a mobile defense they usually are delivered more 
often, but with small forces and briefly, and their success is 
not exploited. The main goal of counterattacks is to support the 
disengagement of defending subunits. Delivering a surprise 
attack on the enemy considerably contributes to this. 
  It is not difficult to notice that the basis of all tactics 
examined which are employed in a modern defense is a broad 
maneuver of fire, personnel and equipment. It is important that 
it be swift and preemptive in nature. An attacking enemy's 
efforts will be successfully nullified only when he is late in 
deploying, in delivering a fire strike, in executing regroupings 
and in building up efforts. 
<H3>  3. Principle of Decisiveness and Aggressiveness in Offensive 
Battle and the Meeting Engagement </H3>
  Decisiveness and aggressiveness reflect the main qualitative 
feature of the offensive. As the history of warfare shows, 
however, with each new stage in development of means of warfare 
it becomes more and more difficult for the attacking side to 
achieve superiority over the defense, whose stability and 
aggressiveness increase simultaneously with the growth in 
penetrating power of attacking troops. 
  Fig. 7 schematically shows certain ways and methods of 
realizing requirements of the principle of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness in offensive battle and the meeting engagement. 
The paramount task which arises for troops in offensive battle 
and the meeting engagement is to seize and hold the initiative 
of operations. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-003LC-44A>             Fig. 7. Methods of realizing the principle of </FIG>



  The attacking side has an important advantage in this 
respect. It is capable of choosing the time, place and methods 
of delivering attacks at its discretion. This creates 
preconditions for dictating one's will on the enemy. But the 
first-strike advantage usually is not retained for long. It can 
be lost if the attacker displays indecisiveness and sluggishness 
in actions, which enables the defender to recover from the 
attack and organize a stubborn resistance. 
  Combat experience shows that even the "argument of force," 
i.e., the superiority in personnel and equipment established on 
the main axis, may not play its role in such a situation. Here 
is an example. In the Volkhov operation in the summer of 1943 a 
superiority over the enemy was achieved in the breakthrough 
sector of 12th Guards Rifle Division as follows: 1:3.5 in 
battalions, 1:5 in guns and 1:3 in tanks. But this did not 
ensure success. During the assault, division units succeeded in 
taking only two enemy trenches, after which their advance was 
halted. 
  This happened because sluggishness was shown in taking 
advantage of the results of fire, much time was lost negotiating 
engineer obstacles ahead of the FEBA, and the infantry assault 
was listless. Taking advantage of this, the enemy managed to 
restore the disrupted fire plan and soon also undertake a 
counterattack. 
  The commander of 69th Army's 312th Rifle Division acted 
differently in the Vistula-Oder operation in January 1945. 
Despite the fact that superiority over the enemy in the division 
zone of advance was minimal (1:2.5 in infantry, 1:2.3 in tanks 
and 1:2.4 in artillery), success of the units' operations was 
significant. On the very first day the division advanced 12 km. 
This was achieved because the division commander acted boldly 
and decisively. He succeeded in ensuring covertness in preparing 
the offensive, carefully organizing for battle, and mobilizing 
the personnel to display high aggressiveness in combat. 
  Here is how the commander taught inexperienced soldiers to 
act during the assault. He said: "The important thing is to rise 
up for the assault promptly. . . . Remember: The enemy has not 
yet collected himself in the first minute after artillery 
preparation; in the second minute the enemy feels himself to see 
whether or not he is whole; in the third minute he searches for 
weapons and fires. We are 300-400 m from the enemy. A fighting 
man walks 120 paces and runs 250 paces per minute. That means in 
the first two minutes you will be hitting an enemy who has not 
come to his senses. But if you delay just for a minute or a 
half-minute, the enemy will greet you with fire."[.sup]46[/] 
  At the present time, in contrast to the past, conditions are 
being created for increasing the decisiveness of an assault. In 
the past war it was executed in dismounted formation and its 
rate was low, in the best case 800-1,000 m/hr, and the depth of 
a penetration assault was 2-3 km. Based on exercise experience, 
now in an assault in IFV's (APC's) without the personnel 
dismounting the rate of forward movement in penetrating a 
deliberate defense is 3-4 km/hr and the average daily rate is 
20-25 km. 
  Decisiveness of operations in the offensive and in a meeting 
engagement largely depends on how rapidly troops succeed in 
creating fire superiority over the enemy. This task is 
extraordinarily complex. A modern defense possesses high 
firepower. Its saturation with various weapons has increased by 
2-4 times compared with World War II. Their mobility and 
firepower increased sharply and the maximum range of weapons 
rose by 3-5 times (Table 2). They are capable of exerting 
pressure on an attacking grouping to its full depth. 


------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
