  For example, here is how the depth of weapon effect is 
distributed in the U.S. Army defense in accordance with the 
"air-land operation" concept. A zone of fire of from 1 to 30-40 
km is assigned for artillery, including MLRS, from 10-15 to 
60-70 km for tactical missile systems, from 50-70 to 400-1,000 
km for operational missile systems, up to 300-400 km for J-SAK 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, 300-500 km or more for tactical 
aviation and up to 20-70 km for combat helicopters. 
  The ratio of offensive and defensive weapons now is such 
that 
it permits drawing the conclusion that their opposition will 
take on an especially intensive character. The "fire tenacity" 
of the defense has increased many times and now it is not enough 
to disorganize the artillery-mortar fire plan in order for an 
attacker to be able to dictate his will on the enemy; this 
requires deep engagement of targets, above all precision weapon 
systems--reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire 
complexes, nuclear attack weapons, combat helicopters, EW 
assets, as well as remote minelaying equipment. 
  We will note that the striving to increase the depth of 
effect on the enemy also was clearly displayed in Soviet troop 
operations in the Great Patriotic War. While the defense was 
suppressed to a depth of 2.5-3 km by massed artillery fire in 
offensive operations of 1941-1942 and to a depth of 3-4 km in 
operations of 1943, during 1944-1945 the depth of simultaneous 
suppression of the enemy defense increased to 6-8 km and in the 
concluding operations it often reached 15 km or 
more.[.sup]48[/] 
  Under present conditions deep fire engagement should take in 
enemy weapons situated both in the tactical as well as 
operational zone of his defense. This is determined by the fact 
that the bulk of enemy weapons are situated at a considerable 
depth from the troops' line of contact. Thus, the experience of 
NATO Allied Forces exercises held in the 1980's showed that 
field artillery firing positions in the defense of formations 
are assigned at a distance of 3-5 km, firing positions of 
artillery employing Copperhead and SADARM guided projectiles 
8-10 km, and MLRS 10-25 km from the FEBA; helicopters with 
jammers operate from zones 10-15 km from the line of contact; 
control centers for J-SAK reconnaissance-strike complexes are 
situated at a distance of 30-50 km, facilities of the TACELIS 
and REMBASS reconnaissance systems at a distance of 30-160 km, 
and loiter zones of aircraft of the PLSS, AWACS and Nimrod 
systems at a distance of 30-160 km from the FEBA.[.sup]49[/] 
  The depth of fire engagement in the offensive increases 
accordingly. American specialists assert that the depth of the 
zone of simultaneous combat effect by organic and attached 
weapons should be 15 km for brigade, 70 km for division, 150 km 
for army corps and 300-500 km or more for army 
group.[.sup]50[/] Within limits of these zones the priority 
in fire engagement is given to continuous fire effect on nuclear 
attack weapons, precision weapon systems, facilities for command 
and control of troops and weapons, and targets of the enemy 
first and second echelons, which creates a precondition for 
disorganizing his fire plan. 
  Decisiveness in the struggle to win fire superiority over 
the 
enemy is manifested in preempting him in delivering deep fire 
strikes. There now are capabilities for this. Integration of 
weapons, reconnaissance equipment and command and control 
equipment in an automated system permits fire damage of the 
enemy in real or near-real time. Thus, adoption of the TACFIRE 
field artillery automated control system in U.S. Army formations 
enabled reducing fire planning time in the division from 2 hours 
to 2 minutes, and fire preparation time in the artillery 
battalion from 30 minutes to 1-2 minutes.[.sup]51[/] 
  J-SAK and PLSS reconnaissance-strike complexes possess even 
greater speed. In a matter of seconds they can detect enemy 
targets, identify them by type, issue a target designation on 
them to appropriate weapons and deliver precise, powerful fire 
strikes against the detected targets, including small moving 
ones. Pave Tiger drones also are used in an automatic mode. They 
perform an automatic search, detection, identification and 
precise destruction of air defense system radars and aircraft 
guidance radars from alert duty zones. 
  In order to achieve decisiveness and high rates in 
conducting 
an attack, it is necessary to achieve a high degree of fire 
damage of various targets in the defense. The Great Patriotic 
War experience showed that in a breakthrough it was necessary to 
destroy as a minimum up to 25 percent and suppress around 30 
percent of various targets situated in the first and second 
positions of the enemy's main defensive zone. That degree of 
fire damage now is no longer enough. 
  Such targets as means of nuclear attack, precision weapon 
systems, and facilities for command and control of troops and 
weapons must be damaged with a degree of up to 100 percent, and 
the other targets with no less a degree than 70-75 percent; 
otherwise the defender may disrupt the attack. 
  A question arises on how to attain such a high degree of 
fire 
damage if the attacker's capabilities for creating high 
artillery densities in a penetration are very limited. The only 
way to increase effectiveness of fire damage of the enemy is to 
achieve the delivery of precise, aimed strikes against targets 
and exclude the "area" suppression method. This will enable a 
significant reduction in numbers of artillery, missile 
launchers, aircraft and helicopters as well as the amount of 
ammunition used for this purpose. 
  Performance of this mission is facilitated by the fact that 
weapon accuracy now has increased sharply. For example, range 
tests showed that employment of Copperhead and SADARM precision 
artillery projectiles permits reducing ammunition expenditure by 
10-15 times. It is also the very same in aviation--use of the 
LAD guided air-dropped clusters enables reducing the expenditure 
of aerial bombs by 4-5 times. 
  An increased power of munitions largely contributes to 
effective performance of the fire damage mission. Based on 
foreign press data, the power of fuel-air explosives used by 
armies of the anti-Iraq coalition during Operation Desert Storm 
(1991) were close to a low-yield nuclear weapon in force. This 
also helps considerably decrease artillery and air densities in 
the offensive. 
  Successfully combating enemy helicopters is a new component 
element of winning fire superiority. At the present time many 
foreign armies view combat helicopters as one of the important 
means of increasing decisiveness and aggressiveness in battle. 
In the defense they are assigned to perform a mission such as 
destroying the attacker's weapons--field artillery, army 
aviation, tanks and EW assets. 
  Combating helicopters presents no small amount of 
difficulty. 
Their operations are characterized by covertness of the target 
approach, swiftness and surprise in delivering a strike, and 
high accuracy of engaging targets at long range without having 
the platform enter the impact zone of air defense weapons. Based 
on the experience of local wars and exercises, helicopters have 
proven themselves to be a highly effective means of combating 
armored targets. For example, a company of helicopters with TOW 
ATGM's is capable of destroying 80-100 tanks in one sortie. 
  In NATO troop exercise strikes by mixed aircraft-helicopter 
elements (ground attack aircraft and strike and reconnaissance 
helicopters) are widely practiced for direct air support of 
combined arms formations. In Operation Desert Storm methods of 
operations were employed, such as successive delivery of strikes 
against tanks and air defense weapons with a lengthy effect on 
the enemy and simultaneous strikes by helicopters, artillery and 
aircraft against one or more targets. 
  Combat practice and exercise experience attest to the fact 
that high helicopter mobility permits combined arms commanders 
to decisively mass fire at the necessary moment against the most 
important targets and transfer it from one axis to another in 
the shortest time periods in order to win and hold fire 
superiority. Concentrated strikes by helicopters usually are 
delivered at the most important moments of battle: Repulse of an 
assault by major tank forces, commitment of a second echelon, 
assault crossing of water obstacles. 
  All this indicates that without successfully combating enemy 
helicopters it is impossible to achieve high decisiveness and 
aggressiveness in offensive battle and the meeting engagement. 
The antihelicopter warfare system is laid down in planning the 
battle and in organizing interworking and comprehensive support. 
Measures taken for this purpose include prompt detection of 
helicopters and warning subunits of the possibility of their 
delivering strikes. The most likely strike delivery lines are 
determined in order to combat enemy helicopters, and necessary 
weapons are assigned for destroying helicopters in concentration 
areas, assembly areas and at tactical positions. Small arms 
fire, particularly antiaircraft machineguns of tank subunits 
when helicopters are in their zone of effective fire, is of no 
small importance in combating helicopters. 
  Skillful choice of effective methods of defeating the enemy 
plays a special role in realizing the principle of decisiveness 
and aggressiveness in the offensive and in the meeting 
engagement. The attacker's attempt to paralyze the defender's 
actions by delivering strikes against him from different 
directions--front, flanks and rear--was observed long ago. Such 
a method enables dissipating enemy forces and creating 
conditions for breaking up his grouping and defeating it in 
detail. But with formation of a continuous static front, such 
conditions in the two world wars were presented to troops 
primarily in a meeting engagement or in the dynamics of combat 
operations, when the attacker employed maneuver and took 
advantage of gaps which had formed and of exposed flanks in the 
enemy combat alignment. 
  In breaking through an enemy defense prepared in advance and 
well fortified in the engineer sense, the attacker was forced to 
methodically "gnaw through" it, gradually grinding down his 
personnel and equipment. Under such conditions mobile operations 
were extremely limited. Still, as the troops' attack potential 
built up, the attacker tried to increase the aggressiveness of 
operations by delivering frontal attacks against the enemy 
across a broad front on a number of axes. But at that time this 
was the prerogative only of the operational echelon. 
  Now the situation has changed. Combined arms formations have 
the capability of employing very decisive methods of defeating 
the enemy, such as delivering splitting attacks from the front 
by forces of tank and motorized rifle units on one or two axes 
in combination with a simultaneous landing of airborne assault 
forces in the enemy rear, and also with swift penetrations by 
mobile units and subunits--forward, enveloping and raiding 
detachments--into the depth of the defense. This permits 
paralyzing the defender's operations, constraining the maneuver 
of his reserves and creating preconditions for their swift 
defeat in detail. 
  In a meeting engagement, when the enemy has exposed flanks, 
a 
combination ground-air strike can be delivered both from the 
front as well as from the flanks. As shown by exercise 
experience, a special effect is produced by a two-sided deep 
envelopment of the enemy with a move into his deep rear in 
combination with operations by a tactical airborne assault force. 
  Speaking of realizing the principle of decisiveness in the 
offensive, one cannot fail to take into account those 
difficulties which arise in this connection, especially in 
overcoming a stable antitank defense. Already in World War II 
the antitank defense was the "backbone" of the entire defense 
system. It was established to the full tactical and operational 
depth. The density of antitank weapons on the most important 
axes reached 20-30 or more. Under present conditions the 
importance of an antitank defense has grown even more and, what 
is especially important, the majority of antitank weapons are 
armored and self-propelled. The number of such targets in 
formations of foreign armies is constantly increasing (Table 3). 


Table 3 - Number of Armored Antitank Weapons in U.S. Divisions[.sup]52[/] 

Antitank          Inf Div      Inf Div      Mech    Mech    Mech    Mech 
Weapons           1945-1954    1954-1960    Div     Div     Div     Div-86 
                                            1967    1972    1985 

Tanks             144          125          254     243     252     290 

ATGM system       -            -            -       -       108     60 
combat vehicle 

IFV, combat       -            -            -       -       -       400 
reconnaissance 
vehicle with 
ATGM system 

Armored           -            -            76      149     54      84 
self-propelled 
artillery, MLRS 


Total             144          125          330     392     415     834 


  As is apparent from the table's data, while the number of 
armored antitank weapons in the U.S. mechanized division was 415 
in 1985, their number became 834 in the division of the modern 
organization. This led to a significant increase in density of 
these weapons in defense. Thus, based on experience of NATO 
Allied Forces exercises conducted in the 1980's, the average 
density of antitank weapons on the most important axes in the 
defense was 70-90 per kilometer of frontage. This is 2-3 times 
higher than in World War II. 
  But it is not only a matter of an increased number of 
antitank weapons in combined arms formations; it is also a 
matter of their qualitative upgrading. In the late 1950's a new, 
very effective antitank weapon--antitank guided missiles 
possessing a high probability of hitting a tank and high 
reliability of killing it--appeared and became widespread. The 
experience of local wars showed that ATGM's had taken a leading 
place among other antitank weapons. Thus, while in World War II 
troops suffered the main tank losses from the fire of antitank 
tube artillery, in the Arab-Israeli War (1973) these losses, 
distinguished by a previously unknown scale, were distributed as 
follows: More than half from ATGM's, up to 22 percent from tank 
fire, and around 28 percent from strikes by aircraft and other 
weapons.[.sup]53[/] 
  Now many armies have three generations of guided missiles in 
the inventory. While the accuracy of first-generation ATGM's was 
0.5-0.6, that of subsequent generations was 0.8-0.9. At the 
present time, engaging armored targets by direct laying is based 
on the principle of "find-fire-kill." It is typical that ATGM's 
are set up not only on mobile ground platforms, but also 
airborne platforms. As a result, very effective missile systems 
have been created on combat helicopters and IFV's, which 
increased the defense's antitank stability even more. But the 
arsenal of antitank defense weapons is not exhausted by this. In 
addition to ATGM's, tanks and antitank artillery, an important 
role in engaging armored targets is played by 
reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire complexes, 
robotized antitank missile systems, drones, fuel-air explosives, 
remote minelaying equipment and so on. 
  In connection with the sharp increase in antitank stability 
of the modern defense, its decisive surmounting demands a search 
for new, more effective methods. All personnel and equipment 
which the attacker has are used for this. Inasmuch as the 
majority of antitank weapons have armor protection, as already 
noted, destroying them requires delivering accurate, aimed 
strikes essentially against each armored target. 
Reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire complexes capable 
of quickly detecting targets and delivering a strike against 
them in a matter of seconds play an important role in 
accomplishing this mission. 
  New weapons are being developed and existing ones upgraded 
to 
increase the effectiveness of air strikes against armored 
targets. Cluster munitions filled with submunitions having 
individual systems for homing on targets are considered the most 
promising. Thus, the Skeet submunition, equipped with a thermal 
homing system, is intended for hitting an armored target in the 
most vulnerable spot (the roof). An important feature of the 
submunitions is their capability to turn into antitank mines 
when they fall to the ground. Air-to-ground guided missiles, 
free-flight rockets, aerial bombs, and pod dispensers which can 
be suspended from all types of attack aircraft are filled with 
such submunitions. 
  According to foreign press reports, in Operation Desert 
Storm 
U.S. aircraft employed such methods of delivering strikes with 
aircraft precision weapons as a "pocket strike," "a toss into 
the electronic basket over the battlefield," "delayed-attack 
strike," "swarming attack," and so on. In the assessment of 
foreign military experts, use of new weapons, 
reconnaissance-strike and reconnaissance-fire complexes, and 
combat helicopters with optimum operating methods reduces the 
requisite detail of aircraft forces and other weapons assigned 
to destroy antitank weapons in the enemy defense by 20-30 times. 
  Disrupting the enemy antitank defense system requires 
suppressing (destroying) or neutralizing 70-80 percent of his 
antitank weapons back in the period of fire preparation of the 
assault. Taking into account their considerable range (5-6 km), 
it is necessary to suppress antitank weapons to the depth of two 
positions simultaneously. Results of fire strikes against 
antitank targets must be exploited without delay by attacking 
tank and motorized rifle subunits. The swifter the assault, the 
fewer losses the attacker will suffer and the faster he will 
gain an opportunity to surmount the zone of massed, continuous, 
multilayered enemy antitank fire. Tactical exercise experience 
shows that with an increase in the pace of the attack by 1.5 
times, attacking subunits' losses from enemy fire dropped by 2-3 
times.[.sup]54[/] 
  The principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness is linked 
inseparably with attaining continuity of development of the 
offensive battle and meeting engagement and high rates of 
pursuit of the enemy; with nonstop assault crossing of water 
obstacles; and with the troops' ability to fight with maximum 
exertion of forces at any time of day or year, in any weather, 
and quickly surmount the obstacles and natural barriers they 
encounter. Zhukov noted that "swiftness is the principal means 
for fastest defeat of the enemy. It is necessary to act so 
swiftly that the enemy is late here, there and everywhere. It is 
necessary to learn this and to bring up our troops on it. Our 
technical outfitting permits us to execute the boldest and 
swiftest attacks."[.sup]55[/] 
  A characteristic feature of modern offensive battle is that 
it usually takes in the entire tactical depth of the enemy 
defense simultaneously. Under such conditions subunits must be 
able to conduct deep battle in his rear, acting for a lengthy 
time in isolation from the main body; make daring deep and close 
envelopments and surprise raids on staffs and weapon firing 
(launch) positions; intercept his lines of communication; and 
fight forward-moving reserves and airmobile subunits. It is 
important not to displace enemy groupings from one position to 
another, but to split them, surround them and destroy them in 
detail. 
  Commanders and staffs at all levels must unremittingly "keep 
their hands on the pulse of events" by displaying high mobility 
and promptly build up efforts on those axes where success has 
appeared. It is important not to give the enemy an opportunity 
to restore a disrupted fire and obstacle plan or to execute a 
planned regrouping of personnel and equipment laterally and out 
of the depth. The initiative of actions and command and control 
should be held firmly by commanders in any situation. 
  During the Great Patriotic War the Soviet command attached 
special importance to aggressive troop operations in the course 
of exploiting a breakthrough and in the pursuit. One directive 
of a tank army commander instructed: "Successful mission 
performance depends above all on swiftness, boldness and 
decisiveness of your actions. . . . Do not be afraid to break 
away from the infantry, swiftly move forward, boldly destroy 
individual enemy centers, and spread panic among his 
troops."[.sup]56[/] 
  But during the war our commanders did not always make 
skilled 
use of the principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness in their 
actions. In the book "V nachale voyny" [At the Beginning of the 
War] A. I. Yeremenko describes the following episode. In August 
1941 a serious situation took shape for Soviet troops in the 
vicinity of Bryansk. Having seized Unecha Station, the Germans 
cut 13th Army maneuver routes and created a threat of its 
encirclement. To disrupt the fascists' plans and restore the 
lost position, the Bryansk Front command sent the 55th Cavalry 
Division into the enemy rear. It successfully penetrated into 
the depth of the fascist German troop disposition. Division 
reconnaissance determined the Germans' total unconcern: Their 
columns were moving forward near our units often without 
security. But the division command lost valuable time and took 
no actions, awaiting instructions of the senior commander. 
Having spent around a week in all in the enemy rear, the 
division returned without having performed the assigned mission, 
although it had all opportunities for this -- it was well manned 
and armed.[.sup]57[/] 
  Commitment of second echelons of units and formations was 
the 
principal means of exploiting success in the past war. Already 
in the battle for the first position of the enemy defense it was 
necessary to put to use not only second echelons of regiments, 
but also often of divisions. The breakthrough of the main 
defense zone usually was accomplished with great difficulties. 
In many operations it was necessary to commit mobile groups of 
armies or even of fronts to complete its breakthrough. This 
reduced rates of development of the operation. 
  Now flexible massing of fire on a decisive axis is the 
principal condition for a successful buildup of combat efforts. 
Surprise fire strikes can disrupt the enemy's attempts to 
organize the closing of breaches which have formed or carry out 
a planned withdrawal of his troops to prepared lines and the 
maneuver of reserves. The western press notes that surprise in 
delivering a strike is the equivalent of increasing the assets 
participating in it by 2.5 times.[.sup]58[/] 
  Fire strikes, even those delivered against deep targets of 
the defense, must be exploited by the troops without delay. An 
important role here belongs to tactical airborne assault forces 
and to forward, enveloping and raiding detachments. The Great 
Patriotic War experience showed that bold raids through enemy 
rears even by small subunits are capable of significantly 
facilitating successful execution of a combat mission by a unit 
or formation. For example, success of the 1st and 2nd guards 
tank corps in the East Prussian operation in 1945 to defeat the 
German Insterburg-Gumbinnen grouping was ensured by decisive 
operations of tank platoons commanded by Senior Lieutenant I. P. 
Kondrashin and Junior Lieutenant I. S. Malov. In fierce fighting 
they captured bridges across the Pregel River, which was 
difficult to cross.[.sup]59[/] Conferral of the Hero of the 
Soviet Union title was a worthy reward for the daredevils. 
  Airborne assault forces are of special importance in swift 
realization of fire strikes against deep enemy targets and in 
creating a constantly operating active front in his rear. In the 
course of the offensive's development they perform missions of 
seizing road junctions, crossings, passes and other important 
objectives in the enemy rear, delay the forward movement of his 
reserves, disrupt their maneuver, assist attacking troops in 
swiftly surmounting enemy defensive lines and natural obstacles, 
and create conditions for defeating his groupings in detail. 
  Skilled advantage taken of night conditions largely 
contributes to attaining high decisiveness and continuity of 
development of the offensive. Aggressive, large-scale night 
actions give troops a number of tactical advantages. Under cover 
of the darkness of night they can deliver surprise attacks 
against the enemy, execute a concealed maneuver and carry out 
feints. 
  But night hampers the operations of advancing units and 
subunits to no small extent. Even with wide use of technical 
support equipment their maneuver capabilities are reduced by 
30-40 percent in the darkness, ammunition expenditure and time 
for damaging targets increases by 1.5-2 times, and the 
negotiation of engineer obstacles and natural barriers is 
substantially hampered. Personnel fatigue increases during 
operations in the darkness. Therefore a night offensive must be 
carefully prepared and supported. Only on this condition is it 
possible to count on its high effectiveness. 
  It is said correctly that night is the ally of the bold and 
brave. Taking advantage of nighttime in the past war, Soviet 
commanders widely employed varied procedures of stratagem. We 
will cite an example. In August 1943 Captain Ye. V. Shkudralov, 
commander of a tank battalion of the 181st Tank Brigade, 18th 
Tank Corps, making a raid in the enemy rear to take the city of 
Zlochev, took advantage of the darkness, joined an enemy column 
unnoticed and approached the city without hindrance. At dawn the 
tankers routed the enemy column by a surprise attack and burst 
into Zlochev. High combat aggressiveness, decisiveness and 
resourcefulness ensured success. Captain Shkudralov was awarded 
the Hero of the Soviet Union title for this battle.[.sup]60[/] 
  In conclusion, we will emphasize that skillful use of the 
principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness by commanders and 
staffs is a sure way to achieve success with fewer costs and 
losses. To confirm this conclusion we refer to experience of 
39th Army. In 1944 it conducted two offensive operations. In 
one, conducted in February, the army advanced at a rate of 0.5 
km per day and in the other operation (Vitebsk) at a rate of 9 
km per day. With higher rates of advance in the Vitebsk 
operation, personnel losses were six times fewer and tank losses 
20 times fewer than in the February operation.[.sup]61[/] 
<H5>  Conclusions and Recommendations </H5>
  1. Demands of the principle of decisiveness and 
aggressiveness can be traced through all Soviet Armed Forces 
field manuals. They emphasize that under all situations 
commanders, staffs and all personnel must act daringly, boldly, 
and vigorously; seize and hold the initiative; strive to impose 
their will on the enemy, disrupt his plans, place him in 
unfavorable conditions; skillfully use the enemy's weak spots 
and the advantages of friendly troops; boldly concentrate main 
efforts on the most important axis and persistently strive to 
execute assigned combat missions; and carry on an aggressive 
struggle to hold fire superiority and air supremacy. 
  2. This principle finds concrete reflection in the 
determination of decisive goals of battle and effective methods 
of achieving them which would allow taking full advantage of 
favorable situation conditions and combat capabilities of units 
and subunits--their striking power, firepower, mobility, and the 
personnel's morale and fighting qualities--in order to strive 
for delivery of a preemptive strike against the enemy and for 
his fastest defeat, and to deprive him of the opportunity to 
choose the methods, direction, character, time and place of 
actions favorable for him. 
  3. To fully realize demands of the principle of decisiveness 
and aggressiveness in the defense it is necessary to constantly 
upgrade methods of preparing and conducting the defense, taking 
advantage of the strong aspects both of the position form as 
well as mobile form of the defense; and to strive for deep fire 
damage of the enemy in the course of his concentration, forward 
movement and deployment. It is important to establish defensive 
fire barriers on distant and close approaches to the defense to 
isolate the battlefield, cut off enemy reserves, disrupt his 
maneuver and block lines of communication. To disrupt the enemy 
offensive and exploit results of fire counterpreparation 
conducted under the senior commander's plan, it is necessary to 
enliven the actions of defending troops in every way, land 
airborne assault forces and raiding and reconnaissance parties 
in his rear under favorable conditions in organizing daring 
raids against his rear areas, and deliver surprise strikes by a 
portion of the forces with a move beyond the FEBA. 
  Combat aggressiveness of defending troops must reach the 
culmination in the fight to hold the FEBA, since stability of 
the defense depends on this to a decisive extent. All defenders' 
short and long range forces and assets and all procedures of 
stratagem and for deceiving the attacker are committed to repel 
the enemy assault; a fixed and creeping artillery barrage ahead 
of the FEBA and on the flanks is established in combination with 
remote mining of the terrain; the enemy is drawn into fire 
pockets; and strikes are delivered against him from ambushes. 
The actions of roving tanks, IFV's, guns and self-propelled 
antiaircraft guns are used widely to mislead the enemy. 
  In case the enemy wedges into the defense, air-fire and 
ground screens are created on his forward movement routes and 
directions of overflight of airmobile detachments; decisive 
measures are taken to combat airborne assault forces and raiding 
and reconnaissance units which have been landed; attacking tanks 
and motorized infantry are destroyed by fire from in place; and 
under favorable conditions counterattacks are carried out to 
rout a wedged-in enemy grouping and restore a lost position. 
  4. Skillfully realizing demands of the principle of 
decisiveness and aggressiveness in an offensive battle and the 
meeting engagement means: 

  -  upgrading forms and methods of seizing and holding the 
initiative of operations; finding new ways to take advantage of 
the factor of time and surprise and of tactics unexpected by the 
enemy in methods of preparing and launching an offensive and in 
increasing the decisiveness of an "armored" attack; 
  -  ensuring 
that fire superiority is won over the enemy in the first minutes 
and firmly held in the course of battle, which requires the 
following: Striving to preempt him in delivering fire strikes; 
increasing the depth of fire effect on the enemy by 3-7 times 
compared with the past; increasing the degree of fire damage of 
primary targets in the defense by 1.5-2 times; achieving top 
priority destruction of enemy precision weapon systems and means 
of nuclear attack and swift disorganization of his systems for 
command and control of troops and weapons; and waging an 
effective fight against enemy combat helicopters; 
  -  comprehensively upgrading methods of defeating the enemy by 
attempting to deliver combination air-ground strikes against him 
from the front, flanks and rear in order to paralyze the actions 
of all elements of the defense to its full depth in short time 
periods; and striving for success in an early stage and swiftly 
exploiting it subsequently; 
  -  striving for continuity of the 
offensive's development at a high pace and to a great depth, and 
conducting it day and night in any weather; executing a decisive 
pursuit of the retreating enemy; making nonstop assault 
crossings of water obstacles; swiftly negotiating obstacles and 
natural barriers; promptly restoring combat effectiveness of 
troops subjected to nuclear and fire strikes; and keeping up the 
troops' high morale and fighting spirit. 

    5. The principle of decisiveness and aggressiveness places 
demands on combat employment of combat arms and air arms; it 
dictates the need to have them ensure continuity of fire support 
of troops in the course of battle, high stability of the 
defense, and attainment of swiftness and high rates of troop 
advance in the offensive. 
  6. Like other principles of battle, the principle of 
decisiveness and aggressiveness demands that commanders display 
creativeness and innovation, make uncommon decisions, and choose 
nonstandard ways of concentrating main efforts, achieving 
surprise, executing flexible, bold maneuver and maintaining 
precise interworking, flexible, firm command and control, and 
comprehensive support to battle. 
  It is important to remember that the enemy also will strive 
for decisive, aggressive actions in all kinds of battle. 
Consequently, it is necessary to constantly maintain the troops' 
high combat readiness, promptly take steps to prevent his 
surprise attack, conduct reconnaissance, and anticipate the 
development of combat events. 
